[
  {
    "tag": "h3",
    "innerHtml": "Introduction"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This work is a continuation of the \"Orlando Innamorato\" of Matteo\nMaria Boiardo, which was left unfinished upon the author's death\nin 1494.  It begins more or less at the point where Boiardo left\nit."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This is a brief synopsis of Boiardo's work, omitting most of the\nnumerous digressions and incidental episodes associated with\nthese events:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "To the court of King Charlemagne comes Angelica (daughter to the\nking of Cathay, or India and her brother Argalia.  Angelica is )"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "the most beautiful woman any of the Peers have ever seen, and all\nwant her.  However, in order to take her as wife they must first\ndefeat Argalia in combat.  The two most stricken by her are\nOrlando and Ranaldo (\"Rinaldo\" in Rose)."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "When Argalia falls to the heathen knight Ferrau, Angelica flees\n--- with Orlando and Ranaldo in hot pursuit.  Along the way, both\nAngelica and Ranaldo drink magic waters — Angelica is filled\nwith a burning love for Ranaldo, but Ranaldo is now indifferent."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Eventually, Orlando and Ranaldo arrive at Angelica's castle.\nOthers also gather at Angelica's castle, including Agricane, King\nof Tartary; Sacripant, King of Circassia; Agramante, King of\nAfrica and Marfisa (\"Marphisa\" in Rose), an Asian warrior-Queen.\nExcept for Orlando and Ranaldo, all are heathen."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Meanwhile, France is threatened by heathen invaders.  Led by King\nGradasso of Sericana (whose principal reason for going to war is\nto obtain Orlando's sword, Durindana and King Rodomonte of )"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Sarzia, a Holy War between Pagans and Christians ensues."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Ranaldo leaves Angelica's castle, and Angelica and a very\nlove-sick (but very chaste and proper Orlando, set out for )"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "France in search of him.  Again the same waters as before are\ndrunk from, but this time in reverse — Ranaldo now burns for\nAngelica, but Angelica is now indifferent.  Ranaldo and Orlando\nnow begin to fight over her, but King Charlemagne (fearing the\nconsequences if his two best knights kill each other in combat)\nintervenes and promises Angelica to whichever of the two fights\nthe best against the heathen; he leaves her in the care of Duke\nNamus.  Orlando and Ranaldo arrive in Paris just in time to\nrepulse an attack by Agramante."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Namus' camp is overrun by the heathen.  Angelica escapes, with\nRanaldo in pursuit.  Also in pursuit is Ferrau, who (because he\nhad defeated Argalia considers Angelica his.  It is at this )"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "point that the poem breaks off."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "While the Orlando-Ranaldo-Angelica triangle is going on, the\nstories of other knights and their loves are mixed in.  Most\nimportant of these is that of the female knight Bradamante\n(sister of Ranaldo), who falls in love with a very noble heathen\nknight named Ruggiero (\"Rogero\" in Rose).  Ruggiero, who is said\nto be a descendent of Alexander the Great and Hector, also falls\nin love with Bradamante, but because they are fighting on\nopposite sides it is felt that their love is hopeless.\nNevertheless, it is prophecised that they shall wed and found the\nfamous Este line, who shall rise to become one of the major\nfamilies of Medieval and Renaissance Italy (it is worth noting\nthat the Estes where the patrons of both Boiardo and Ariosto).\nOpposed to this prophecy is Atlantes, an African wizard who seeks\nto derail fate and keep Ruggiero from becoming a Christian.  By\nthe end of the poem, Ruggiero is imprisoned in Atlantes' castle.\nHowever, Bradamante (who has decided to follow her heart is in )"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "pursuit of her love, and is not too far away.  It is the\nBradamante-Ruggiero story that eventually takes center stage in\nAriosto's work."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Other characters of importance: Astolfo, a Peer and friend of\nOrlando, who is kidnaped by the evil witch Morgana and her sister\nAlcina; Mandricardo, a fierce but hot-headed heathen; and a young\nknight named Brandimarte, who falls in love with (and wins the\nheart of the beautiful Fiordelisa (\"Flordelice\" in Rose).  All )"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "play major or semi-major roles in the events of Ariosto's poem."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "——DBK"
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 1"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Angelica, whom pressing danger frights,\nFlies in disorder through the greenwood shade.\nRinaldo's horse escapes: he, following, fights\nFerrau, the Spaniard, in a forest glade.\nA second oath the haughty paynim plights,\nAnd keeps it better than the first he made.\nKing Sacripant regains his long-lost treasure;\nBut good Rinaldo mars his promised pleasure.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>I</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>OF LOVES and LADIES, KNIGHTS and ARMS, I sing,\nOf COURTESIES, and many a DARING FEAT;\nAnd from those ancient days my story bring,\nWhen Moors from Afric passed in hostile fleet,\nAnd ravaged France, with Agramant their king,\nFlushed with his youthful rage and furious heat,\nWho on king Charles', the Roman emperor's head\nHad vowed due vengeance for Troyano dead.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>II</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>In the same strain of Roland will I tell\nThings unattempted yet in prose or rhyme,\nOn whom strange madness and rank fury fell,\nA man esteemed so wise in former time;\nIf she, who to like cruel pass has well\nNigh brought my feeble wit which fain would climb\nAnd hourly wastes my sense, concede me skill\nAnd strength my daring promise to fulfil.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>III</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Good seed of Hercules, give ear and deign,\nThou that this age's grace and splendour art,\nHippolitus, to smile upon his pain\nWho tenders what he has with humble heart.\nFor though all hope to quit the score were vain,\nMy pen and pages may pay the debt in part;\nThen, with no jealous eye my offering scan,\nNor scorn my gifts who give thee all I can.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>IV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And me, amid the worthiest shalt thou hear,\nWhom I with fitting praise prepare to grace,\nRecord the good Rogero, valiant peer,\nThe ancient root of thine illustrious race.\nOf him, if thou wilt lend a willing ear,\nThe worth and warlike feats I shall retrace;\nSo thou thy graver cares some little time\nPostponing, lend thy leisure to my rhyme.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>V</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Roland, who long the lady of Catay,\nAngelica, had loved, and with his brand\nRaised countless trophies to that damsel gay,\nIn India, Median, and Tartarian land,\nWestward with her had measured back his way;\nWhere, nigh the Pyrenees, with many a band\nOf Germany and France, King Charlemagne\nHad camped his faithful host upon the plain.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>VI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>To make King Agramant, for penance, smite\nHis cheek, and rash Marsilius rue the hour;\nThis, when all trained with lance and sword to fight,\nHe led from Africa to swell his power;\nThat other when he pushed, in fell despite,\nAgainst the realm of France Spain's martial flower.\n'Twas thus Orlando came where Charles was tented\nIn evil hour, and soon the deed repented.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>VII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>For here was seized his dame of peerless charms,\n(How often human judgment wanders wide)!\nWhom in long warfare he had kept from harms,\nFrom western climes to eastern shores her guide\nIn his own land, 'mid friends and kindred arms,\nNow without contest severed from his side.\nFearing the mischief kindled by her eyes,\nFrom him the prudent emperor reft the prize.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>VIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>For bold Orlando and his cousin, free\nRinaldo, late contended for the maid,\nEnamored of that beauty rare; since she\nAlike the glowing breast of either swayed.\nBut Charles, who little liked such rivalry,\nAnd drew an omen thence of feebler aid,\nTo abate the cause of quarrel, seized the fair,\nAnd placed her in Bavarian Namus' care.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>IX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Vowing with her the warrior to content,\nWho in that conflict, on that fatal day,\nWith his good hand most gainful succour lent,\nAnd slew most paynims in the martial fray.\nBut counter to his hopes the battle went,\nAnd his thinned squadrons fled in disarray;\nNamus, with other Christian captains taken,\nAnd his pavilion in the rout forsaken.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>X</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>There, lodged by Charles, that gentle bonnibel,\nOrdained to be the valiant victor's meed,\nBefore the event had sprung into her sell,\nAnd from the combat turned in time of need;\nPresaging wisely Fortune would rebel\nThat fatal day against the Christian creed:\nAnd, entering a thick wood, discovered near,\nIn a close path, a horseless cavalier.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>With shield upon his arm, in knightly wise,\nBelted and mailed, his helmet on his head;\nThe knight more lightly through the forest hies\nThan half-clothed churl to win the cloth of red.\nBut not from cruel snake more swiftly flies\nThe timid shepherdess, with startled tread,\nThan poor Angelica the bridle turns\nWhen she the approaching knight on foot discerns.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>This was that Paladin, good Aymon's seed,\nWho Mount Albano had in his command;\nAnd late Baiardo lost, his gallant steed,\nEscaped by strange adventure from his hand.\nAs soon as seen, the maid who rode at speed\nThe warrior knew, and, while yet distant, scanned\nThe angelic features and the gentle air\nWhich long had held him fast in Cupid's snare.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The affrighted damsel turns her palfrey round,\nAnd shakes the floating bridle in the wind;\nNor in her panic seeks to choose her ground,\nNor open grove prefers to thicket blind.\nBut reckless, pale and trembling, and astound,\nLeaves to her horse the devious way to find.\nHe up and down the forest bore the dame,\nTill to a sylvan river's bank he came.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Here stood the fierce Ferrau in grisly plight,\nBegrimed with dust, and bathed with sweat and blood\nWho lately had withdrawn him from the fight,\nTo rest and drink at that refreshing flood:\nBut there had tarried in his own despite,\nSince bending from the bank, in hasty mood,\nHe dropped his helmet in the crystal tide,\nAnd vainly to regain the treasure tried.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Thither at speed she drives, and evermore\nIn her wild panic utters fearful cries;\nAnd at the voice, upleaping on the shore,\nThe Saracen her lovely visage spies.\nAnd, pale as is her cheek, and troubled sore,\nArriving, quickly to the warrior's eyes\n(Though many days no news of her had shown)\nThe beautiful Angelica is known.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Courteous, and haply gifted with a breast\nAs warm as either of the cousins two;\nAs bold, as if his brows in steel were dressed,\nThe succour which she sought he lent, and drew\nHis faulchion, and against Rinaldo pressed,\nWho saw with little fear the champion true.\nNot only each to each was known by sight,\nBut each had proved in arms his foeman's might.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Thus, as they are, on foot the warriors vie\nIn cruel strife, and blade to blade oppose;\nNo marvel plate or brittle mail should fly,\nWhen anvils had not stood the deafening blows.\nIt now behoves the palfrey swift to ply\nHis feet; for while the knights in combat close,\nHim vexed to utmost speed, with goading spurs,\nBy waste or wood the frighted damsel stirs.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>After the two had struggled long to throw\nEach other in the strife, and vainly still;\nSince neither valiant warrior was below\nHis opposite in force and knightly skill:\nThe first to parley with his Spanish foe\nWas the good master of Albano's hill\n(As one within whose raging breast was pent\nA reckless fire which struggled for a vent).</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Thou think'st,\" he said, \"to injure me alone,\nBut know thou wilt thyself as much molest:\nFor if we fight because yon rising sun\nThis raging heat has kindled in thy breast.\nWhat were thy gain, and what the guerdon won,\nThough I should yield my life, or stoop my crest;\nIf she shall never be thy glorious meed,\nWho flies, while vainly we in battle bleed?</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Then how much better, since our stake's the same,\nThou, loving like myself, should'st mount and stay\nTo wait this battle's end, the lovely dame,\nBefore she fly yet further on her way.\nThe lady taken, we repeat our claim\nWith naked faulchion to that peerless prey:\nElse by long toil I see not what we gain\nBut simple loss and unrequited pain.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The peer's proposal pleased the paynim well.\nAnd so their hot contention was foregone;\nAnd such fair truce replaced that discord fell,\nSo mutual wrongs forgot and mischief done;\nThat for departure seated in his sell,\nOn foot the Spaniard left not Aymon's son;\nBut him to mount his courser's crupper prayed;\nAnd both united chased the royal maid.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Oh! goodly truth in cavaliers of old!\nRivals they were, to different faith were bred.\nNot yet the weary warriors' wounds were cold —\nStill smarting from those strokes so fell and dread.\nYet they together ride by waste and wold,\nAnd, unsuspecting, devious dingle thread.\nThem, while four spurs infest his foaming sides,\nTheir courser brings to where the way divides.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And now the warlike pair at fault, for they\nKnew not by which she might her palfrey goad,\n(Since both, without distinction, there survey\nThe recent print of hoofs on either road),\nCommit the chase to fortune.  By this way\nThe paynim pricked, by that Rinaldo strode.\nBut fierce Ferrau, bewildered in the wood,\nFound himself once again where late he stood.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Beside the water, where he stoop'd to drink,\nAnd dropt the knightly helmet, — to his cost,\nSunk in the stream; and since he could not think\nHer to retrieve, who late his hopes had crossed.\nHe, where the treasure fell, descends the brink\nOf that swift stream, and seeks the morion lost.\nBut the casque lies so bedded in the sands,\n'Twill ask no light endeavour at his hands.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>A bough he severs from a neighbouring tree,\nAnd shreds and shapes the branch into a pole:\nWith this he sounds the stream, and anxiously\nFathoms, and rakes, and ransacks shelf and hole.\nWhile angered sore at heart, and restless, he\nSo lingered, where the troubled waters roll,\nBreast-high, from the mid river rose upright,\nThe apparition of an angry knight.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Armed at all points he was, except his head,\nAnd in his better hand a helmet bore:\nThe very casque, which in the river's bed\nFerrau sought vainly, toiling long and sore.\nUpon the Spanish knight he frowned, and said:\n\"Thou traitor to thy word, thou perjured Moor,\nWhy grieve the goodly helmet to resign,\nWhich, due to me long since, is justly mine?</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Remember, pagan, when thine arm laid low\nThe brother of Angelica.  That knight\nAm I; — thy word was plighted then to throw\nAfter my other arms his helmet bright.\nIf Fortune now compel thee to forego\nThe prize, and do my will in thy despite,\nGrieve not at this, but rather grieve that thou\nArt found a perjured traitor to thy vow.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"But if thou seek'st a helmet, be thy task\nTo win and wear it more to thy renown.\nA noble prize were good Orlando's casque;\nRinaldo's such, or yet a fairer crown;\nAlmontes', or Mambrino's iron masque:\nMake one of these, by force of arms, thine own.\nAnd this good helm will fitly be bestowed\nWhere (such thy promise it has long been owed.\" ) \n</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Bristled the paynim's every hair at view\nOf that grim shade, uprising from the tide,\nAnd vanished was his fresh and healthful hue,\nWhile on his lips the half-formed accents died.\nNext hearing Argalia, whom he slew,\n(So was the warrior hight that stream beside, ) \n\nThus his unknightly breach of promise blame,\nHe burned all over, flushed with rage and shame.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Nor having time his falsehood to excuse,\nAnd knowing well how true the phantom's lore,\nStood speechless; such remorse the words infuse.\nThen by Lanfusa's life the warrior swore,\nNever in fight, or foray would he use\nHelmet but that which good Orlando bore\nFrom Aspramont, where bold Almontes paid\nHis life a forfeit to the Christian blade.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And this new vow discharged more faithfully\nThan the vain promise which was whilom plight;\nAnd from the stream departing heavily,\nWas many days sore vexed and grieved in sprite;\nAnd still intent to seek Orlando, he\nRoved wheresoe'er he hoped to find the knight.\nA different lot befel Rinaldo; who\nHad chanced another pathway to pursue.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>For far the warrior fared not, ere he spied,\nBounding across the path, his gallant steed,\nAnd, \"Stay, Bayardo mine,\" Rinaldo cried,\n\"Too cruel care the loss of thee does breed.\"\nThe horse for this returned not to his side,\nDeaf to his prayer, but flew with better speed.\nFurious, in chase of him, Rinaldo hies.\nBut follow we Angelica, who flies.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Through dreary woods and dark the damsel fled,\nBy rude unharboured heath and savage height,\nWhile every leaf or spray that rustled, bred\n(Of oak, or elm, or beech), such new affright,\nShe here and there her foaming palfrey sped\nBy strange and crooked paths with furious flight;\nAnd at each shadow, seen in valley blind,\nOr mountain, feared Rinaldo was behind.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>As a young roe or fawn of fallow deer,\nWho, mid the shelter of its native glade,\nHas seen a hungry pard or tiger tear\nThe bosom of its bleeding dam, dismayed,\nBounds, through the forest green in ceaseless fear\nOf the destroying beast, from shade to shade,\nAnd at each sapling touched, amid its pangs,\nBelieves itself between the monster's fangs,</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>One day and night, and half the following day,\nThe damsel wanders wide, nor whither knows;\nThen enters a deep wood, whose branches play,\nMoved lightly by the freshening breeze which blows.\nThrough this two clear and murmuring rivers stray:\nUpon their banks a fresher herbage grows;\nWhile the twin streams their passage slowly clear,\nMake music with the stones, and please the ear.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Weening removed the way by which she wends,\nA thousand miles from loathed Rinaldo's beat,\nTo rest herself a while the maid intends,\nWearied with that long flight and summer's heat.\nShe from her saddle 'mid spring flowers descends\nAnd takes the bridle from her courser fleet.\nAnd loose along the river lets him pass,\nRoving the banks in search of lusty grass.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Behold! at hand a thicket she surveys\nGay with the flowering thorn and vermeil rose:\nThe tuft reflected in the stream which strays\nBeside it, overshadowing oaks enclose.\nHollow within, and safe from vulgar gaze,\nIt seemed a place constructed for repose;\nWith bows so interwoven, that the light\nPierced not the tangled screen, far less the sight.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Within soft moss and herbage form a bed;\nAnd to delay and rest the traveller woo.\n'Twas there her limbs the weary damsel spread,\nHer eye-balls bathed in slumber's balmy dew.\nBut little time had eased her drooping head,\nEre, as she weened, a courser's tramp she knew.\nSoftly she rises, and the river near,\nArmed cap-a-pie, beholds a cavalier.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>If friend or foe, she nothing comprehends,\n(So hope and fear her doubting bosom tear)\nAnd that adventure's issue mute attends,\nNor even with a sigh disturbs the air.\nThe cavalier upon the bank descends;\nAnd sits so motionless, so lost in care,\n(His visage propt upon his arm to sight ) \n\nChanged into senseless stone appeared the knight.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XL</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Pensive, above an hour, with drooping head,\nHe rested mute, ere he began his moan;\nAnd then his piteous tale of sorrow said,\nLamenting in so soft and sweet a tone,\nHe in a tiger's breast had pity bred,\nOr with his mournful wailings rent a stone.\nAnd so he sighed and wept; like rivers flowed\nHis tears, his bosom like an Aetna glowed.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Thought which now makes me burn, now freeze with hate,\nWhich gnaws my heart and rankles at its root!\nWhat's left to me,\" he said, \"arrived too late,\nWhile one more favoured bears away the fruit?\nBare words and looks scarce cheered my hopeless state,\nAnd the prime spoils reward another's suit.\nThen since for me nor fruit nor blossom hangs,\nWhy should I longer pine in hopeless pangs?</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"The virgin has her image in the rose\nSheltered in garden on its native stock,\nWhich there in solitude and safe repose,\nBlooms unapproached by sheperd or by flock.\nFor this earth teems, and freshening water flows,\nAnd breeze and dewy dawn their sweets unlock:\nWith such the wistful youth his bosom dresses.\nWith such the enamored damsel braids her tresses.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"But wanton hands no sooner this displace\nFrom the maternal stem, where it was grown,\nThan all is withered; whatsoever grace\nIt found with man or heaven; bloom, beauty, gone.\nThe damsel who should hold in higher place\nThan light or life the flower which is her own,\nSuffering the spoiler's hand to crop the prize,\nForfeits her worth in every other's eyes.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"And be she cheap with all except the wight\nOn whom she did so large a boon bestow.\nAh! false and cruel Fortune! foul despite!\nWhile others triumph, I am drown'd in woe.\nAnd can it be that I such treasure slight?\nAnd can I then my very life forego?\nNo! let me die; 'twere happiness above\nA longer life, if I must cease to love.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>If any ask who made this sorrowing,\nAnd pour'd into the stream so many tears,\nI answer, it was fair Circassia's king,\nThat Sacripant, oppressed with amorous cares.\nLove is the source from which his troubles spring,\nThe sole occasion of his pains and fears;\nAnd he to her a lover's service paid,\nNow well remembered by the royal maid.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>He for her sake from Orient's farthest reign\nRoved thither, where the sun descends to rest;\nFor he was told in India, to his pain,\nThat she Orlando followed to the west.\nHe after learned in France that Charlemagne\nSecluded from that champion and the rest,\nAs a fit guerdon, mewed her for the knight\nWho should protect the lilies best in fight.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The warrior in the field had been, and viewed,\nShort time before, king Charlemagne's disgrace;\nAnd vainly had Angelica pursued,\nNor of the damsel's footsteps found a trace.\nAnd this is what the weeping monarch rued,\nAnd this he so bewailed in doleful case:\nHence, into words his lamentations run,\nWhich might for pity stop the passing sun.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>While Sacripant laments him in this plight,\nAnd makes a tepid fountain of his eyes;\nAnd, what I deem not needful to recite,\nPours forth yet other plaints and piteous cries;\nPropitious Fortune will his lady bright\nShould hear the youth lament him in such wise:\nAnd thus a moment compassed what, without\nSuch chance, long ages had not brought about.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>With deep attention, while the warrior weeps,\nShe marks the fashion of the grief and tears\nAnd words of him, whose passion never sleeps;\nNor this the first confession which she hears.\nBut with his plaint her heart no measure keeps,\nCold as the column which the builder rears.\nLike haughty maid, who holds herself above\nThe world, and deems none worthy of her love.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>L</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>But her from harm amid those woods to keep,\nThe damsel weened she might his guidance need;\nFor the poor drowning caitiff, who, chin-deep,\nImplores not help, is obstinate indeed.\nNor will she, if she let the occasion sleep,\nFind escort that will stand her in such stead:\nFor she that king by long experience knew\nAbove all other lovers, kind and true.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>But not the more for this the maid intends\nTo heal the mischief which her charms had wrought,\nAnd for past ills to furnish glad amends\nIn that full bliss by pining lover sought.\nTo keep the king in play are all her ends,\nHis help by some device or fiction bought,\nAnd having to her purpose taxed his daring,\nTo reassume as wont her haughty bearing.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>An apparition bright and unforeseen,\nShe stood like Venus or Diana fair,\nIn solemn pageant, issuing on the scene\nFrom out of shadowy wood or murky lair.\nAnd \"Peace be with you,\" cried the youthful queen,\n\"And God preserve my honour in his care,\nNor suffer that you blindly entertain\nOpinion of my fame so false and vain!\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Not with such wonderment a mother eyes,\nWith such excessive bliss the son she mourned\nAs dead, lamented still with tears and sighs,\nSince the thinned files without her boy returned.\n— Not such her rapture as the king's surprise\nAnd ecstasy of joy when he discerned\nThe lofty presence, cheeks of heavenly hue,\nAnd lovely form which broke upon his view.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>He, full of fond and eager passion, pressed\nTowards his Lady, his Divinity;\nAnd she now clasped the warrior to her breast,\nWho in Catay had haply been less free.\nAnd now again the maid her thoughts addressed\nTowards her native land and empery:\nAnd feels, with hope revived, her bosom beat\nShortly to repossess her sumptuous seat.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Her chances all to him the damsel said,\nSince he was eastward sent to Sericane\nBy her to seek the martial monarch's aid,\nWho swayed the sceptre of that fair domain;\nAnd told how oft Orlando's friendly blade\nHad saved her from dishonour, death, and pain;\nAnd how she so preserved her virgin flower\nPure as it blossomed in her natal hour.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Haply the tale was true; yet will not seem\nLikely to one of sober sense possessed:\nBut Sacripant, who waked from worser dream,\nIn all without a cavil acquiesced:\nSince love, who sees without one guiding gleam,\nSpies in broad day but that which likes him best:\nFor one sign of the afflicted man's disease\nIs to give ready faith to things which please.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"If good Anglante's lord the prize forbore,\nNor seized the fair occasion when he might,\nThe loss be his, if Fortune never more\nHim to enjoy so fair a prize invite.\nTo imitate that lord of little lore\nI think not,\" said, apart, Circassa's knight.\n\"To quit such proffered good, and, to my shame,\nHave but myself on after-thought to blame.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"No!  I will pluck the fresh and morning rose,\nWhich, should I tarry, may be overblown.\nTo woman, (this my own experience shows),\nNo deed more sweet or welcome can be done.\nThen, whatsoever scorn the damsel shows,\nThough she awhile may weep and make her moan,\nI will, unchecked by anger, false or true,\nOr sharp repulse, my bold design pursue.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>This said, he for the soft assault prepares,\nWhen a loud noise within the greenwood shade\nBeside him, rang in his astounded ears,\nAnd sore against his will the monarch stayed.\nHe donned his helm (his other arms he wears),\nAye wont to rove in steel, with belted blade,\nReplaced the bridle on his courser fleet,\nGrappled his lance, and sprang into his seat.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>With the bold semblance of a valiant knight,\nBehold a warrior threads the forest hoar.\nThe stranger's mantle was of snowy white,\nAnd white alike the waving plume he wore.\nBalked of his bliss, and full of fell despite,\nThe monarch ill the interruption bore,\nAnd spurred his horse to meet him in mid space,\nWith hate and fury glowing in his face.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Him he defies to fight, approaching nigh,\nAnd weens to make him stoop his haughty crest:\nThe other knight, whose worth I rate as high,\nHis warlike prowess puts to present test;\nCuts short his haughty threats and angry cry,\nAnd spurs, and lays his levelled lance in rest.\nIn tempest wheels Circassia's valiant peer,\nAnd at his foeman's head each aims his spear.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Not brindled bulls or tawny lions spring\nTo forest warfare with such deadly will\nAs those two knights, the stranger and the king.\nTheir spears alike the opposing bucklers thrill:\nThe solid ground, at their encountering,\nTrembles from fruitful vale to naked hill:\nAnd well it was the mail in which they dressed\nTheir bodies was of proof, and saved the breast.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Nor swerved the chargers from their destined course;\nWho met like rams, and butted head to head.\nThe warlike Saracen's ill-fated horse,\nWell valued while alive, dropt short and dead:\nThe stranger's, too, fell senseless; but perforce\nWas roused by rowel from his grassy bed.\nThat of the paynim king, extended straight,\nLay on his battered lord with all his weight.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Upright upon his steed, the knight unknown,\nWho at the encounter horse and rider threw,\nDeeming enough was in the conflict done,\nCares not the worthless warfare to renew;\nBut endlong by the readiest path is gone,\nAnd measures, pricking frith and forest through,\nA mile, or little less, in furious heat,\nEre the foiled Saracen regains his feet.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>As the bewildered and astonished clown\nWho held the plough (the thunder storm o'erpast)\nThere, where the deafening bolt had beat him down,\nNigh his death-stricken cattle, wakes aghast,\nAnd sees the distant pine without its crown,\nWhich he saw clad in leafy honours last;\nSo rose the paynim knight with troubled face,\nThe maid spectatress of the cruel case.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>He sighs and groans, yet not for mischief sore\nEndured in wounded arm or foot which bled;\nBut for mere shame, and never such before\nOr after, dyed his cheek so deep a red,\nAnd if he rued his fall, it grieved him more\nHis dame should lift him from his courser dead.\nHe speechless had remained, I ween, if she\nHad not his prisoned tongue and voice set free.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Grieve not,\" she said, \"sir monarch, for thy fall;\nBut let the blame upon thy courser be!\nTo whom more welcome had been forage, stall,\nAnd rest, than further joust and jeopardy;\nAnd well thy foe the loser may I call,\n(Who shall no glory gain for such is he ) \n\nWho is the first to quit his ground, if aught\nAngelica of fighting fields be taught.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>While she so seeks the Saracen to cheer,\nBehold a messenger with pouch and horn,\nOn panting hackney! — man and horse appear\nWith the long journey, weary and forlorn.\nHe questions Sacripant, approaching near,\nHad he seen warrior pass, by whom were borne\nA shield and crest of white; in search of whom\nThrough the wide forest pricked the weary groom.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>King Sacripant made answer, \"As you see,\nHe threw me here, and went but now his way:\nThen tell the warrior's name, that I may be\nInformed whose valour foiled me in the fray.\"\nTo him the groom, — \"That which you ask of me\nI shall relate to you without delay:\nKnow that you were in combat prostrate laid\nBy the tried valour of a gentle maid.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Bold is the maid; but fairer yet than bold,\nNor the redoubted virgin's name I veil:\n'Twas Bradamant who marred what praise of old\nYour prowess ever won with sword and mail.\"\nThis said, he spurred again, his story told,\nAnd left him little gladdened by the tale.\nHe recks not what he says or does, for shame,\nAnd his flushed visage kindles into flame.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>After the woeful warrior long had thought\nUpon his cruel case, and still in vain,\nAnd found a woman his defeat had wrought,\nFor thinking but increased the monarch's pain,\nHe climbed the other horse, nor spake he aught;\nBut silently uplifted from the plain,\nUpon the croup bestowed that damsel sweet,\nReserved to gladder use in safer seat.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Two miles they had not rode before they hear\nThe sweeping woods which spread about them, sound\nWith such loud crash and trample, far and near,\nThe forest seemed to tremble all around;\nAnd shortly after see a steed appear,\nWith housings wrought in gold and richly bound;\nWho clears the bush and stream, with furious force\nAnd whatsoever else impedes his course.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Unless the misty air,\" the damsel cries,\n\"And boughs deceive my sight, yon noble steed\nIs, sure, Bayardo, who before us flies,\nAnd parts the wood with such impetuous speed.\n— Yes, 'tis Bayardo's self I recognize.\nHow well the courser understands our need!\nTwo riders ill a foundered jade would bear,\nBut hither speeds the horse to end that care.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The bold Circassian lighted, and applied\nHis hand to seize him by the flowing rein,\nWho, swiftly turning, with his heels replied,\nFor he like lightning wheeled upon the plain.\nWoe to the king! but that he leaps aside,\nFor should he smite, he would not lash in vain.\nSuch are his bone and sinew, that the shock\nOf his good heels had split a metal rock.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Then to the maid he goes submissively,\nWith gentle blandishment and humble mood;\nAs the dog greets his lord with frolic glee,\nWhom, some short season past, he had not viewed.\nFor good Bayardo had in memory\nAlbracca, where her hands prepared his food,\nWhat time the damsel loved Rinaldo bold;\nRinaldo, then ungrateful, stern, and cold.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>With her left hand she takes him by the bit,\nAnd with the other pats his sides and chest:\nWhile the good steed (so marvellous his wit),\nLamb-like, obeyed the damsel and caressed.\nMeantime the king, who sees the moment fit,\nLeapt up, and with his knees the courser pressed.\nWhile on the palfrey, eased of half his weight,\nThe lady left the croup, and gained the seat.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Then, as at hazard, she directs her sight,\nSounding in arms a man on foot espies,\nAnd glows with sudden anger and despite;\nFor she in him the son of Aymon eyes.\nHer more than life esteems the youthful knight,\nWhile she from him, like crane from falcon, flies.\nTime was the lady sighed, her passion slighted;\n'Tis now Rinaldo loves, as ill requited.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And this effect two different fountains wrought,\nWhose wonderous waters different moods inspire.\nBoth spring in Arden, with rare virtue fraught:\nThis fills the heart with amorous desire:\nWho taste that other fountain are untaught\nTheir love, and change for ice their former fire.\nRinaldo drank the first, and vainly sighs;\nAngelica the last, and hates and flies.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Mixed with such secret bane the waters glide,\nWhich amorous care convert to sudden hate;\nThe maid no sooner had Rinaldo spied,\nThan on her laughing eyes deep darkness sate:\nAnd with sad mien and trembling voice she cried\nTo Sacripant, and prayed him not to wait\nThe near approach of the detested knight,\nBut through the wood with her pursue his flight.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>To her the Saracen, with anger hot:\n\"Is knightly worship sunk so low in me,\nThat thou should'st hold my valour cheap, and not\nSufficient to make yonder champion flee?\nAlready are Albracca's fights forgot,\nAnd that dread night I singly stood for thee?\nThat night when I, though naked, was thy shield\nAgainst King Agrican and all his field?\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>She answers not, and knows not in her fear\nWhat 'tis she does; Rinaldo is too nigh:\nAnd from afar that furious cavalier\nThreats the bold Saracen with angry cry,\nAs soon as the known steed and damsel dear,\nWhose charms such flame had kindled, meet his eye.\nBut what ensued between the haughty pair</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>Canto shall declare.</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 2"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>A hermit parts, by means of hollow sprite,\nThe two redoubted rivals' dangerous play;\nRinaldo goes where Love and Hope invite,\nBut is dispatched by Charles another way;\nBradamont, seeking her devoted knight,\nThe good Rogero, nigh becomes the prey\nOf Pinabel, who drops the damsel brave\nInto the dungeon of a living grave.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>I</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Injurious love, why still to mar accord\nBetween desires has been thy favourite feat?\nWhy does it please thee so, perfidious lord,\nTwo hearts should with a different measure beat?\nThou wilt not let me take the certain ford,\nDragging me where the stream is deep and fleet.\nHer I abandon who my love desires,\nWhile she who hates, respect and love inspires.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>II</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Thou to Rinaldo show'st the damsel fair,\nWhile he seems hideous to that gentle dame;\nAnd he, who when the lady's pride and care,\nPaid back with deepest hate her amorous flame,\nNow pines, himself, the victim of despair,\nScorned in his turn, and his reward the same.\nBy the changed damsel in such sort abhorred,\nShe would choose death before that hated lord.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>III</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>He to the Pagan cries: \"Forego thy theft,\nAnd down, false felon, from that pilfer'd steed;\nI am not wont to let my own be reft.\nAnd he who seeks it dearly pays the deed.\nMore — I shall take from thee yon lovely weft;\nTo leave thee such a prize were foul misdeed;\nAnd horse and maid, whose worth outstrips belief,\nWere ill, methinks, relinquished to a thief.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>IV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Thou liest,\" the haughty Saracen retorts,\nAs proud, and burning with as fierce a flame,\n\"A thief thyself, if Fame the truth reports:\nBut let good deeds decide our dubious claim,\nWith whom the steed or damsel fair assorts:\nBest proved by valiant deeds: though, for the dame,\nThat nothing is so precious, I with thee\n(Search the wide world throughout may well agree.\" ) \n</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>V</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>As two fierce dogs will somtimes stand at gaze,\nWhom hate or other springs of strife inspire,\nAnd grind their teeth, while each his foe surveys\nWith sidelong glance and eyes more red than fire,\nThen either falls to bites, and hoarsely bays,\nWhile their stiff bristles stand on end with ire:\nSo from reproach and menace to the sword\nPass Sacripant and Clermont's angry lord.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>VI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Thus kindling into wrath the knights engage:\nOne is on foot, the other on his horse:\nSmall gain to this; for inexperienced page\nWould better rein his charger in the course.\nFor such Baiardo's sense, he will not wage\nWar with his master, or put out his force.\nFor voice, nor hand, nor manage, will he stir,\nRebellious to the rein or goading spur.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>VII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>He, when the king would urge him, takes the rest,\nOr, when he curbs him, runs in giddy rings;\nAnd drops his head beneath his spreading chest,\nAnd plays his spine, and runs an-end and flings.\nAnd now the furious Saracen distressed,\nSees 'tis no time to tame the beast, and springs,\nWith one hand on the pummel, to the ground;\nClear of the restless courser at a bound.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>VIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>As soon as Sacripant, with well-timed leap,\nIs from the fury of Bayardo freed,\nYou may believe the battle does not sleep\nBetween those champions, matched in heart and deed.\nTheir sounding blades such changeful measure keep,\nThe hammer-strokes of Vulcan with less speed\nDescend in that dim cavern, where he heats,\nAnd Jove's red thunders on his anvil beats.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>IX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Sometimes they lunge, then feign the thrust and parry:\nDeep masters of the desperate game they play;\nOr rise upon the furious stroke, and carry\nTheir swords aloft, or stoop and stand at bay.\nAgain they close, again exhausted tarry;\nNow hide, now show themselves, and now give way,\nAnd where one knight an inch of ground has granted,\nHis foeman's foot upon that inch is planted.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>X</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>When, lo!  Rinaldo, now impatient grown,\nStrikes full at Sacripant with lifted blade;\nAnd he puts forth his buckler made of bone,\nAnd well with strong and stubborn steel inlaid:\nThough passing thick, Fusberta cleaves it: groan\nGreenwood, and covert close, and sunny glade.\nThe paynim's arm rings senseless with the blow,\nAnd steel and bone, like ice, in shivers go.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>When the fair damsel saw, with timid eye,\nSuch ruin follow from the faulchion's sway,\nShe, like the criminal, whose doom is nigh,\nChanged her fair countenance through sore dismay,\nAnd deemed that little time was left to fly\nIf she would not be that Rinaldo's prey,\nRinaldo loathed by her as much, as he\nDoats on the scornful damsel miserably.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>So turned her horse into the gloomy chase,\nAnd drove him through rough path and tangled ally\nAnd oftentimes bent back her bloodless face,\nAnd saw Rinaldo from each thicket sally.\nNor flying long had urged the frantic race,\nBefore she met a hermit in a valley.\nDevotion in his aspect was expressed,\nAnd his long beard descended on his breast.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Wasted he was as much by fasts as age,\nAnd on an ass was mounted, slow and sure;\nHis visage warranted that never sage\nHad conscience more precise or passing pure.\nThough in his arteries time had stilled the rage\nOf blood, and spake him feeble and demure,\nAt sight of the delighted damsel, he\nWas inly stirred for very charity.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The lady prayed that kindly friar, that he\nWould straight conduct her to some haven near,\nFor that she from the land of France might flee,\nAnd never more of loathed Rinaldo hear.\nThe hermit, who was skilled in sorcery,\nCeased not to soothe the gentle damsel's fear.\nAnd with the promise of deliverance, shook\nHis pocket, and drew forth a secret book.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>This opened, quick and mighty marvel wrought;\nFor not a leaf is finished by the sage,\nBefore a spirit, by his bidding brought,\nWaits his command in likeness of a page:\nHe, by the magic writ constrained and taught,\nHastes where the warriors face to face engage,\nIn the cool shade — but not in cool disport —\nAnd steps between, and stops their battle short.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"In courtesy,\" he cried, \"let either show\nWhat his foe's death to either can avail,\nAnd what the guerdon conquest will bestow\nOn him who in the battle shall prevail,\nIf Roland, though he has not struck a blow,\nOr snapt in fight a single link of mail,\nTo Paris-town conveys the damsel gay,\nWho has engaged you in this bitter fray.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Within an easy mile I saw the peer\nPricking to Paris with that lady bright;\nRiding, in merry mood, with laugh and jeer,\nAnd mocking at your fierce and fruitless fight.\nSure it were better, while they yet are near,\nTo follow peer and damsel in their flight:\nFor should he once in Paris place his prize\nThe lady never more shall meet your eyes.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>You might have seen those angry cavaliers\nChange at the demon's tale for rage and shame;\nAnd curse themselves as wanting eyes and ears,\nTo let their rival cheat them of the dame.\nTowards his horse the good Rinaldo steers,\nBreathing forth piteous sighs which seem of flame;\nAnd, if he joins Orlando — ere they part —\nSwears in his fury he will have his heart.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>So, passing where the prompt Bayardo stood,\nLeaps on his back, and leaves, as swift as wind,\nWithout farewell, his rival in the wood;\nMuch less invites him to a seat behind.\nThe goaded charger, in his heat of blood,\nForces whate'er his eager course confined,\nDitch, river, tangled thorn, or marble block;\nHe swims the river, and he clears the rock.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Let it not, sir, sound strangely in your ear\nRinaldo took the steed thus readily,\nSo long and vainly followed far and near;\nFor he, endued with reasoning faculty,\nHad not in vice lured on the following peer,\nBut fled before his cherished lord, that he\nMight guide him whither went the gentle dame,\nFor whom, as he had heard, he nursed a flame.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>For when Angelica, in random dread,\nFrom the pavilion winged her rapid flight,\nBayardo marked the damsel as she fled,\nHis saddle lightened of Mount Alban's knight;\nWho then on foot an equal combat sped,\nMatched with a baron of no meaner might;\nAnd chased the maid by woods, and floods, and strands,\nIn hopes to place her in the warrior's hands.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And, with desire to bring him to the maid,\nGallopped before him still with rampant play;\nBut would not let his master mount, afraid\nThat he might make him take another way.\nSo luring on Rinaldo through the shade,\nTwice brought him to his unexpected prey;\nTwice foiled in his endeavour: once by bold\nFerrau; then Sacripant, as lately told.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Now good Bayardo had believed the tiding\nOf that fair damsel, which produced the accord;\nAnd in the devil's cunning tale confiding,\nRenewed his wonted service to his lord.\nBehold Rinaldo then in fury riding,\nAnd pushing still his courser Paris-ward!\nThough he fly fast, the champion's wishes go\nFaster; and wind itself had seemed too slow.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>At night Rinaldo rests his steed, with pain\nTo meet Anglante's lord he burned so sore;\nAnd lent such credit to the tidings vain\nOf the false courier of that wizard hoar:\nAnd that day and the next, with flowing rein,\nRode, till the royal city rose before\nHis eyes; where Charlemagne had taken post,\nWith the sad remnant of his broken host.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>He, for he fears the Afric king's pursuit,\nAnd sap and siege, upon his vassals calls\nTo gather in fresh victual, and recruit\nAnd cleanse their ditches, and repair their walls.\nAnd what may best annoy the foes, and suit\nFor safety, without more delay forestalls;\nAnd plans an embassy to England, thence\nTo gather fresher forces for defence.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>For he is bent again to try the fate\nOf arms in tented field, though lately shamed;\nAnd send Rinaldo to the neighbouring state\nOf Britain, which was after England named.\nIll liked the Paladin to cross the strait;\nNot that the people or the land he blamed,\nBut that King Charles was sudden; nor a day\nWould grant the valiant envoy for delay.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Rinaldo never executed thing\nLess willingly, prevented in his quest\nOf that fair visage he was following,\nWhose charms his heart had ravished from his breast.\nYet, in obediance to the christian king,\nPrepared himself to do the royal hest.\nTo Calais the good envoy wends with speed,\nAnd the same day embarks himself and steed.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And there, in scorn of cautious pilot's skill\n(Such his impatience to regain his home),\nLaunched on the doubtful sea, which boded ill,\nAnd rolled its heavy billows, white with foam.\nThe wind, enraged that he opposed his will,\nStirred up the waves; and, 'mid the gathering gloom,\nSo the loud storm and tempest's fury grew,\nThat topmast-high the flashing waters flew.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The watchful mariners, in wary sort,\nHaul down the mainsail, and attempt to wear;\nAnd would put back in panic to the port,\nWhence, in ill hour, they loosed with little care.\n— \"Not so,\" exclaims the wind, and stops them short,\n\"So poor a penance will not pay the dare.\"\nAnd when they fain would veer, with fiercer roar\nPelts back their reeling prow and blusters more.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Starboard and larboard bears the fitful gale,\nAnd never for a thought its ire assuages;\nWhile the strained vessel drives with humble sail\nBefore the billows, as the tempest rages.\nBut I, who still pursue a varying tale,\nMust leave awhile the Paladin, who wages\nA weary warfare with the wind and flood;\nTo follow a fair virgin of his blood.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>I speak of that famed damsel, by whose spear\nO'erthrown, King Sacripant on earth was flung;\nThe worthy sister of the valiant peer,\nFrom Beatrix and good Duke Aymon sprung.\nBy daring deeds and puissance no less dear\nTo Charlemagne and France: Since proved among\nThe first, her prowess, tried by many a test,\nEqual to good Rinaldo's shone confessed.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>A cavalier was suitor to the dame,\nWho out of Afric passed with Agramant;\nRogero was his valiant father's name,\nHis mother was the child of Agolant.\nAnd she, who not of bear or lion came,\nDisdained not on the Child her love to plant,\nThough cruel Fortune, ill their wishes meeting,\nHad granted to the pair a single greeting.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Alone thenceforth she sought her lover (he\nWas named of him to whom he owed his birth),\nAnd roved as safe as if in company\nOf thousands, trusting in her single worth.\nShe having made the king of Circassy\nSalute the visage of old mother earth,\nTraversed a wood, and that wood past, a mountain;\nAnd stopt at length beside a lovely fountain.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Through a delicious mead the fountain-rill,\nBy ancient trees o'ershaded, glides away;\nAnd him whose ear its pleasing murmurs fill,\nInvites to drink, and on its banks to stay;\nOn the left side a cultivated hill\nExcludes the fervors of the middle day.\nAs first the damsel thither turns her eyes,\nA youthful cavalier she seated spies;</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>A cavalier, who underneath the shade,\nSeems lost, as in a melancholy dream;\nAnd on the bank, which gaudy flowers displayed,\nReposing, overhangs the crystal stream.\nHis horse beneath a spreading beech is laid,\nAnd from a bough the shield and helmet gleam.\nWhile his moist eyes, and sad and downcast air,\nSpeak him the broken victim of despair.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Urged by the passion lodged in every breast,\nA restless curiosity to know\nOf others' cares, the gentle maid addressed\nThe knight, and sought the occasion of his woe.\nAnd he to her his secret grief confessed,\nWon by her gentle speech and courteous show,\nAnd by that gallant bearing, which at sight,\nPrepared who saw her for nimble knight.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Fair sir, a band of horse and foot,\" he said,\n\"I brought to Charlemagne; and thither pressed,\nWhere he an ambush for Marsilius spread,\nDescending from the Pyrenean crest;\nAnd in my company a damsel led,\nWhose charms with fervid love had fired my breast.\nWhen, as we journey by Rhone's current, I\nA rider on a winged courser spy.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"The robber, whether he were man or shade,\nOr goblin damned to everlasting woe,\nAs soon as he beheld my dear-loved maid,\nLike falcon, who, descending, aims its blow,\nSank in a thought and rose; and soaring, laid\nHands on his prize, and snatched her from below.\nSo quick the rape, that all appeared a dream,\nUntil I heard in air the damsel's scream.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"The ravening kite so swoops and plunders, when\nHovering above the shelterd yard, she spies\nA helpless chicken near unwatchful hen,\nWho vainly dins the thief with after cries.\nI cannot reach the mountain-robber's den,\nCompassed with cliffs, or follow one who flies.\nBesides, way-foundered is my weary steed,\nWho 'mid these rocks has wasted wind and speed.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XL</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"But I, like one who from his bleeding side\nWould liefer far have seen his heart out-torn,\nLeft my good squadrons masterless, to ride\nAlong the cliffs, and passes least forlorn;\nAnd took the way (love served me for a guide)\nWhere it appeared the ruthless thief had born,\nAscending to his den, the lovely prey,\nWhat time he snatched my hope and peace away.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Six days I rode, from morn to setting sun,\nBy horrid cliff, by bottom dark and drear;\nAnd giddy precipice, where path was none,\nNor sign, nor vestiges of man were near.\nAt last a dark and barren vale I won,\nWhere caverned mountains and rude cliffs appear;\nWhere in the middle rose a rugged block,\nWith a fair castle planted on the rock.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"From far it shone like flame, and seemed not dight\nOf marble or of brick; and in my eye\nMore wonderful the work, more fair to sight\nThe walls appeared, as I approached more nigh.\nI, after, learned that it was built by sprite\nWhom potent fumes had raised and sorcery:\nWho on this rock its towers of steel did fix,\nCase-hardened in the stream and fire of Styx.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Each polished turret shines with such a ray\nThat it defies the mouldering rust and rain:\nThe robber scours the country night and day,\nAnd after harbours in this sure domain.\nNothing is safe which he would bear away;\nPursued with curses and with threats in vain.\nThere (fruitless every hope to foil his art)\nThe felon keeps my love, oh! say my heart.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Alas! what more is left me but to eye\nHer prison on that cliff's aerial crest?\nLike the she-fox, who hears her offspring cry,\nStanding beneath the ravening eagle's nest;\nAnd since she has not wings to rise and fly,\nRuns round the rugged rock with hopeless quest.\nSo inaccessible the wild dominion\nTo whatsoever has not plume and pinion.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"While I so lingered where those rocks aspire,\nI saw a dwarf guide two of goodly strain;\nWhose coming added hope to my desire\n(Alas! desire and hope alike were vain)\nBoth barons bold, and fearful in their ire:\nThe one Gradasso, King of Sericane,\nThe next, of youthful vigour, was a knight,\nPrized in the Moorish court, Rogero hight.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"The dwarf exclaimed, `These champions will assay\nTheir force with him who dwells on yonder steep,\nAnd by such strange and unattempted way\nSpurs the winged courser from his mountain-keep.'\nAnd I to the approaching warriors say,\n`Pity, fair sirs, the cruel loss I weep,\nAnd, as I trust, yon daring spoiler slain,\nGive my lost lady to my arms again.'</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Then how my love was ravished I make known,\nVouching with bitter tears my deep distress.\nThey proffer aid, and down the path of stone\nWhich winds about the craggy mountain, press.\nWhile I, upon the summit left alone,\nLook on, and pray to God for their success.\nBeneath the wily wizard's castle strong\nExtends a little plain, two bow-shots long.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Arrived beneath the craggy keep, the two\nContend which warrior shall begin the fight.\nWhen, whether the first lot Gradasso drew,\nOr young Rogero held the honor light,\nThe King of Sericane his bugle blew,\nAnd the rock rang and fortress on the height;\nAnd, lo! apparelled for the fearful course,\nThe cavalier upon his winged horse!</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Upwards, by little and by little, springs\nThe winged courser, as the pilgrim crane\nFinds not at first his balance and his wings,\nRunning and scarcely rising from the plain;\nBut when the flock is launched and scattered, flings\nHis pinions to the wind, and soars amain.\nSo straight the necromancer's upward flight,\nThe eagle scarce attempts so bold a height.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>L</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"When it seems fit, he wheels his courser round,\nWho shuts his wings, and falling from the sky,\nShoots like a well trained falcon to the ground,\nWho sees the quarry, duck or pigeon, fly:\nSo, through the parting air, with whizzing sound,\nWith rested lance, he darted from on high;\nAnd while Gradasso scarcely marks the foe\nHe hears him swooping near, and feels the blow.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"The wizard on Gradasso breaks his spear,\nHe wounds the empty air, with fury vain.\nThis in the feathered monster breeds no fear;\nWho to a distance shifts, and swoops again.\nWhile that encounter made the Alfana rear,\nThrown back upon her haunches, on the plain.\nThe Alfana that the Indian monarch rode,\nThe fairest was that ever man bestrode.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Up to the starry sphere with swift ascent\nThe wizard soars, then pounces from the sky,\nAnd strikes the young Rogero, who, intent\nUpon Gradasso, deems no danger nigh.\nBeneath the wizard's blow the warrior bent,\nWhich made some deal his generous courser ply;\nAnd when to smite the shifting foe he turned,\nHim in the sky, and out of reach discerned.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"His blows Rogero, now Gradasso, bruise\nOn forehead, bosom, back, or flanks, between;\nWhile he the warrior's empty blows eschews,\nShifting so quickly that he scarce is seen.\nNow this, now that, the wizard seems to choose,\nThe monster makes such spacious rings and clean,\nWhile the enchanter so deceives the knights,\nThey view him not, and know not whence he smites.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Between the two on earth and him o' the sky,\nUntil that hour the warfare lasted there,\nWhich, spreading wide its veil of dusky dye,\nThroughout the world, discolours all things fair.\nWhat I beheld, I say; I add not, I,\nA tittle to the tale; yet scarcely dare\nTo tell to other what I stood and saw;\nSo strange it seems, so passing Nature's law.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Well covered in a goodly silken case,\nHe, the celestial warrior, bore his shield;\nBut why delayed the mantle to displace\nI know not, and its lucid orb concealed.\nSince this no sooner blazes in his face,\nThan his foe tumbles dazzled on the field;\nAnd while he, like a lifeless body, lies,\nBecomes the necromancer's helpless prize.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"LIke carbuncle, the magic buckler blazed,\nNo glare was ever seen which shone so bright:\nNor could the warriors choose but fall, amazed\nAnd blinded by the clear and dazzling light.\nI, too, that from a distant mountain gazed,\nFell senseless; and when I regained my sight,\nAfter long time, saw neither knights nor page,\nNor aught beside a dark and empty stage.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"This while the fell enchanter, I supposed,\nDragged both the warriors to his prison-cell;\nAnd by strange virtue of the shield disclosed,\nI from my hope and they from freedom fell:\nAnd thus I to the turrets, which enclosed\nMy heart, departing, bade a last farewell.\nNow sum my griefs, and say if love combine\nOther distress or grief to match with mine.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The knight relapsed into his first disease,\nAfter his melancholy tale was done.\nThis was Count Pinabel, the Maganzese,\nAnselmo d'Altaripa's faithless son.\nHe, where the blood ran foul through all degrees,\nDisdained to be the only virtuous one;\nNor played a simple part among the base,\nPassing in vice the villains of his race.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>With aspect changing still, the beauteous dame\nHears what the mournful Maganzese narrates;\nAnd, at first mention of Rogero's name,\nHer radiant face with eager joy dilates.\nBut, full of pity, kindles into flame\nAs Pinabel his cruel durance states.\nNor finds she, though twice told, the story stale;\nBut makes him oft repeat and piece his tale.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And, after, when she deemed that all was clear,\nCried to the knight, \"Repose upon my say.\nTo thee may my arrival well be dear,\nAnd thou as fortunate account this day.\nStraight wend me to the keep, sir cavalier,\nWhich holds a jewel of so rich a ray:\nNor shalt thou grudge thy labour and thy care,\nIf envious Fortune do but play me fair.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The knight replied, \"Then nought to me remains\nBut that I yonder mountain-passes show;\nAnd sure 'tis little loss to lose my pains,\nWhere every thing is lost I prize below.\nBut you would climb yon cliffs, and for your gains\nWill find a prison-house, and be it so!\nWhate'er betide you, blame yourself alone;\nYou go forewarned to meet a fate foreshown.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>So said, the cavalier remounts his horse,\nAnd serves the gallant damsel as a guide;\nWho is prepared Rogero's gaol to force,\nOr to be slain, or in his prison stied.\nWhen lo! a messenger, in furious course,\nCalled to the dame to stay, and rode and cried.\nThis was the post who told Circassa's lord\nWhat valiant hand had stretched him on the sward.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The courier, who so plied his restless heel,\nNews of Narbonne and of Montpelier bore:\nHow both had raised the standard of Castile,\nAll Acquamorta siding with the Moor;\nAnd how Marseilles' disheartened men appeal\nTo her, who should protect her straightened shore;\nAnd how, through him, her citizens demand\nCounsel and comfort at their captain's hand.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>This goodly town, with many miles of plain,\nWhich lie 'twixt Var and Rhone, upon the sea,\nTo her was given by royal Charlemagne:\nSuch trust he placed in her fidelity.\nStill wont with wonder on the tented plain\nThe prowess of that valiant maid to see.\nAnd now the panting courier, as I said,\nRode from Marseilles to ask the lady's aid.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Whether or not she should the call obey,\nThe youthful damsel doubts some little space;\nStrong in one balance Fame and Duty weigh,\nBut softer thoughts both Fame and Duty chase:\nAnd she, at length, resolved the emprize to assay,\nAnd free Rogero from the enchanted place:\nOr, should her valour in the adventure fail,\nWould with the cherished lover share his jail.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And did with such excuse that post appay,\nHe was contented on her will to wait:\nThen turned the bridle to resume her way\nWith Pinabel, who seemed no whit elate.\nSince of that line he knows the damsel gay,\nHeld in such open and such secret hate;\nAnd future trouble to himself foresees,\nWere he detected as a Maganzese.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>For 'twixt Maganza's and old Clermont's line\nThere was an ancient and a deadly feud:\nAnd oft to blows the rival houses came,\nAnd oft in civil blood their hands embrued.\nAnd hence some treason to this gentle dame\nIn his foul heart, the wicked County brewed;\nOr, as the first occasion served, would stray\nOut of the road, and leave her by the way.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And so the traitor's troubled fancy rack\nFear, doubt, and his own native, rancorous mood,\nThat unawares he issued from the track,\nAnd found himself within a gloomy wood:\nWhere a rough mountain reared its shaggy back,\nWhose stony peak above the forest stood;\nThe daughter of Dodona's duke behind,\nDogging his footsteps through the thicket blind.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>He, when he saw himself within the brake,\nThought to abandon his unweeting foe;\nAnd to the dame — \" 'Twere better that we make\nFor shelter ere the gathering darkness grow;\nAnd, yonder mountain past, (save I mistake)\nA tower is seated in the vale below.\nDo you expect me then, while from the peak\nI measure the remembered place I seek.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>So said, he pushed his courser up the height\nOf that lone mountain; in his evil mind\nRevolving, as he went, some scheme or sleight\nTo rid him of the gentle dame behind.\nWhen lo! a rocky cavern met his sight,\nAmid those precipices dark and blind:\nIts sides descended thirty yards and more,\nWorked smooth, and at the bottom was a door.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>A void was at the bottom, where a wide\nPortal conducted to an inner room:\nFrom thence a light shone out on every side,\nAs of a torch illumining the gloom.\nFair Bradamant pursued her faithless guide,\nSuspended there, and pondering on her doom:\nAnd came upon the felon where he stood,\nFearing lest she might lose him in the wood.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>When her approach the County's first intent\nMade vain, the wily traitor sought to mend\nHis toils, and some new stratagem invent\nTo rid her thence, or bring her to her end.\nAnd so to meet the approaching lady went,\nAnd showed the cave, and prayed her to ascend;\nAnd said that in its bottom he had seen\nA gentle damsel of bewitching mien.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Who, by her lovely semblance and rich vest,\nAppeared a lady of no mean degree;\nBut melancholy, weeping, and distressed,\nAs one who pined there in captivity:\nAnd that when he towards the entrance pressed,\nTo learn who that unhappy maid might be,\nOne on the melancholy damsel flew,\nAnd her within that inner cavern drew.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The beauteous Bradamant, who was more bold\nThan wary, gave a ready ear; and, bent\nTo help the maid, imprisoned in that hold,\nSought but the means to try the deep descent.\nThen, looking round, descried an elm-tree old,\nWhich furnished present means for her intent:\nAnd from the tree, with boughs and foliage stored,\nLopt a long branch, and shaped it with her sword.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The severed end she to the count commended,\nThen, grasping it, hung down that entrance steep.\nWith her feet foremost, by her arms suspended:\nWhen asking if she had the skill to leap,\nThe traitor, with a laugh, his hands extended.\nAnd plunged his helpless prey into the deep.\n\"And thus,\" exclaimed the ruffian, \"might I speed\nWith thee each sucker of thy cursed seed!\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>But not, as was the will of Pinabel,\nSuch cruel lot fair Bradamant assayed;\nFor striking on the bottom of the cell,\nThe stout elm-bough so long her weight upstayed,\nThat, though it split and splintered where it fell,\nIt broked her fall, and saved the gentle maid.\nSome while astounded there the lady lay,</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>Canto will display.</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 3"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Restored to sense, the beauteous Bradamant\nFinds sage Melissa in the vaulted tomb,\nAnd hears from her of many a famous plant\nAnd warrior, who shall issue from her womb.\nNext, to release Rogero from the haunt\nOf old Atlantes, learns how from the groom,\nBrunello hight, his virtuous ring to take;\nAnd thus the knight's and others' fetters break.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>I</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Who will vouchsafe me voice that shall ascend\nAs high as I would raise my noble theme?\nWho will afford befitting words, and lend\nWings to my verse, to soar the pitch I scheme?\nSince fiercer fire for such illustrious end,\nThan what was wont, may well my song beseem.\nFor this fair portion to my lord is due\nWhich sings the sires from whom his lineage grew.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>II</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Than whose fair line, 'mid those by heavenly grace\nChosen to minister this earth below,\nYou see not, Phoebus, in your daily race,\nOne that in peace or war doth fairer show;\nNor lineage that hath longer kept its place;\nAnd still shall keep it, if the lights which glow\nWithin me, but aright inspire my soul,\nWhile the blue heaven shall turn about the pole.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>III</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>But should I seek at full its worth to blaze,\nNot mine were needful, but that noble lyre\nWhich sounded at your touch the thunderer's praise,\nWhat time the giants sank in penal fire.\nYet should you instruments, more fit to raise\nThe votive work, bestow, as I desire,\nAll labour and all thought will I combine,\nTo shape and shadow forth the great design.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>IV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Till when, this chisel may suffice to scale\nThe stone, and give my lines a right direction;\nAnd haply future study may avail,\nTo bring the stubborn labour to perfection.\nReturn we now to him, to whom the mail\nOf hawberk, shield, and helm, were small protection:\nI speak of Pinabel the Maganzeze,\nWho hopes the damsel's death, whose fall he sees.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>V</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The wily traitor thought that damsel sweet\nHad perished on the darksome cavern's floor,\nAnd with pale visages hurried his retreat\nFrom that, through him contaminated door.\nAnd, thence returning, clomb into his seat:\nThen, like one who a wicked spirit bore,\nTo add another sin to evil deed,\nBore off with him the warlike virgin's steed.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>VI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Leave we sometime the wretch who, while he layed\nSnares for another, wrought his proper doom;\nAnd turn we to the damsel he betrayed,\nWho had nigh found at once her death and tomb.\nShe, after rising from the rock, dismayed\nAt her shrewd fall, and gazing through the gloom,\nBeheld and passed that inner door, which gave\nEntrance to other and more spacious cave.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>VII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>For the first cavern in a second ended,\nFashioned in form of church, and large and square;\nWith roof by cunning architect extended\nOn shafts of alabaster rich and rare.\nThe flame of a clear-burning lamp ascended\nBefore the central altar; and the glare,\nIlluminating all the space about,\nShone through the gate, and lit the cave without.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>VIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Touched with the sanctifying thoughts which wait\nOn worthy spirit in a holy place,\nShe prays with eager lips, and heart elate,\nTo the Disposer of all earthly grace:\nAnd, kneeling, hears a secret wicket grate\nIn the opposing wall; whence, face to face,\nA woman issuing forth, the maid addresses,\nBarefoot, ungirt, and with dishevelled tresses.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>IX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"O generous Bradamant,\" the matron cried,\n\"Know thine arrival in this hallowed hold\nWas not unauthorized of heavenly guide:\nAnd the prophetic ghost of Merlin told,\nThou to this cave shouldst come by path untried,\nWhich covers the renowned magician's mould.\nAnd here have I long time awaited thee,\nTo tell what is the heavens' pronounced decree.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>X</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"This is the ancient memorable cave\nWhich Merlin, that enchanter sage, did make:\nThou may'st have heard how that magician brave\nWas cheated by the Lady of the Lake.\nBelow, beneath the cavern, is the grave\nWhich holds his bones; where, for that lady's sake,\nHis limbs (for such her will the wizard spread. ) \n\nLiving he laid him there, and lies there dead.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Yet lives the spirit of immortal strain;\nLodged in the enchanter's corpse, till to the skies\nThe trumpet call it, or to endless pain,\nAs it with dove or raven's wing shall rise.\nYet lives the voice, and thou shalt hear how plain\nFrom its sepulchral case of marble cries:\nSince this has still the past and future taught\nTo every wight that has its counsel sought.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Long days have passed since I from distant land\nMy course did to this cemetery steer,\nThat in the solemn mysteries I scanned,\nMerlin to me the truth should better clear;\nAnd having compassed the design I planned,\nA month beyond, for thee, have tarried here;\nSince Merlin, still with certain knowledge summing\nEvents, prefixed this moment for thy coming.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The daughter of Duke Aymon stood aghast,\nAnd silent listened to the speech; while she\nKnew not, sore marvelling at all that passed,\nIf 'twere a dream or a reality.\nAt length, with modest brow, and eyes down cast,\nReplied (like one that was all modesty),\n\"And is this wrought for me? and have I merit\nWorthy the workings of prophetic spirit?\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And full of joy the adventure strange pursues,\nMoving with ready haste behind the dame,\nWho brings her to the sepulchre which mews\nThe bones and spirit, erst of Merlin's name.\nThe tomb, of hardest stone which masons use,\nShone smooth and lucid, and as red as flame.\nSo that although no sun-beam pierced the gloom,\nIts splendour lit the subterraneous room.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Whether it be the native operation\nO certain stones, to shine like torch i' the dark,\nOr whether force of spell or fumigation,\n(A guess that seems to come more near the mark)\nOr sign made under mystic constellation,\nThe blaze that came from the sepulchral ark\nDiscovered sculpture, colour, gems, and gilding,\nAnd whatsoever else adorned the building.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Scarcely had Bradamant above the sill\nLifter her foot, and trod the secret cave,\nWhen the live spirit, in clear tones that thrill,\nAddressed the martial virgin from the grave;\n\"May Fortune, chaste and noble maid, fulfil\nThine every wish!\" exclaimed the wizard brave.\n\"Since from thy womb a princely race shall spring,\nWhose name through Italy and earth shall ring.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"The noble blood derived from ancient Troy,\nMingling in thee its two most glorious streams,\nShall be the ornament, and flower, and joy\nOf every lineage on which Phoebus beams,\nWhere genial stars lend warmth, or cold annoy,\nWhere Indus, Tagus, Nile, or Danube gleams;\nAnd in thy progeny and long drawn line\nShall marquises, counts, dukes and Caesers shine.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Captains and cavaliers shall spring from thee,\nWho both by knightly lance and prudent lore,\nShall once again to widowed Italy\nHer ancient praise and fame in arms restore;\nAnd in her realms just lords shall seated be,\n(Such Numa and Augustus were of yore),\nWho with their government, benign and sage,\nShall re-create on earth the golden age.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Then, that the will of Heaven be duly brought\nTo a fair end through thee, in fitting date,\nWhich from the first to bless thy love has wrought,\nAnd destined young Rogero for thy mate,\nLet nothing interpose to break that thought,\nBut boldly tread the path perscribed by fate;\nNor let aught stay thee till the thief be thrown\nBy thy good lance, who keeps thee from thine own.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Here Merlin ceased, that for the solemn feat\nMelissa might prepare with fitting spell,\nTo show bold Bradamant, in aspect meet,\nThe heirs who her illustrious race should swell.\nHence many sprites she chose; but from what seat\nEvoked, I know not, or if called from hell;\nAnd gathered in one place (so bade the dame),\nIn various garb and guise the shadows came.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>This done, into the church she called the maid,\nWhere she had drawn a magic ring, as wide\nAs might contain the damsel, prostrate laid;\nWith the full measure of a palm beside.\nAnd on her head, lest spirit should invade,\nA pentacle for more assurance tied.\nSo bade her hold her peace, and stand and look,\nThen read, and schooled the demons from her book.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Lo! forth of that first cave what countless swarm\nPresses upon the circle's sacred round,\nBut, when they would the magic rampart storm,\nFinds the way barred as if by fosse or mound;\nThen back the rabble turns of various form;\nAnd when it thrice with bending march has wound\nAbout the circle, troops into the cave,\nWhere stands that beauteous urn, the wizard's grave.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"To tell at large the puissant acts and worth,\nAnd name of each who, figured in a sprite,\nIs present to our eyes before his birth,\"\nSaid sage Melissa to the damsel bright;\n\"To tell the deeds which they shall act on earth,\nWere labour not to finish with the night.\nHence I shall call few worthies of thy line,\nAs time and fair occasion shall combine.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"See yonder first-born of thy noble breed,\nWho well reflects thy fair and joyous face;\nHe, first of thine and of Rogero's seed,\nShall plant in Italy thy generous race.\nIn him behold who shall distain the mead,\nAnd his good sword with blood of Pontier base;\nThe mighty wrong chastised, and traitor's guilt,\nBy whom his princely father's blood was spilt.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"By him King Desiderius shall be pressed,\nThe valiant leader of the Lombard horde:\nAnd of the fiefs of Calaon and Este;\nFor this imperial Charles shall make him lord.\nHubert, thy grandson, comes behind; the best\nOf Italy, with arms and belted sword:\nWho shall defend the church from barbarous foes,\nAnd more than once assure her safe repose.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Alberto next, unconquered captain, see,\nWhose trophies shall so many fanes array.\nHugh, the bold son, is with the sire, and he\nShall conquer Milan, and the snakes display.\nAzo, that next approaching form shall be,\nAnd, his good brother dead, the Insubri sway.\nLo!  Albertazo!  by whose rede undone,\nSee Berengarius banished, and his son.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"With him shall the imperial Otho join\nIn wedlock worthily his daughter fair.\nAnd lo!  another Hugh!  O noble line!\nO!  sire succeeded by an equal heir!\nHe, thwarting with just cause their ill design,\nShall thrash the Romans' pride who overbear;\nShall from their hands the sovereign pontiff take,\nWith the third Otho, and their leaguer break.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"See Fulke, who to his brother will convey\nAll his Italian birth-right, and command\nTo take a mighty dukedom far away\nFrom his fair home, in Almayn's northern land.\nThere he the house of Saxony shall stay,\nAnd prop the ruin with his saving hand;\nThis in his mother's right he shall possess,\nAnd with his progeny maintain and bless.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"More famed for courtesy than warlike deed,\nAzo the second, he who next repairs!\nBertoldo and Albertazo are his seed:\nAnd, lo!  the father walkes between his heirs.\nBy Parma's walls I see the Germans bleed,\nTheir second Henry quelled; such trophy bears\nThe one renowned in story's future page:\nThe next shall wed Matilda, chaste and sage.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"His virtues shall deserve so fair a flower,\n(And in his age, I wot, no common grace)\nTo hold the half of Italy in dower,\nWith that descendent of first Henry's race.\nRinaldo shall succeed him in his power,\nPledge of Bertoldo's wedded love, and chase\nFierce Frederick Barbarossa's hireling bands,\nSaving the church from his rapacious hands.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Another Azo rules Verona's town,\nWith its fair fields; and two great chiefs this while\n(One wears the papal, one the imperial crown),\nThe baron, Marquis of Ancona style.\nBut to show all who rear the gonfalon\nOf the consistory, amid that file,\nWere task too long; as long to tell each deed\nAchieved for Rome by thy devoted seed.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"See Fulke and Obyson, more Azos, Hughs!\nBoth Henrys! — mark the father and his boy.\nTwo Guelphs: the first fair Umbria's land subdues,\nAnd shall Spoleto's ducal crown enjoy.\nBehold the princely phantom that ensues,\nShall turn fair Italy's long grief to joy;\nI speak of the fifth Azo of thy strain,\nBy whom shall Ezelin be quelled and slain.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Fierce Ezelin, that most inhuman lord,\nWho shall be deemed by men a child of hell.\nAnd work such evil, thinning with the sword\nWho in Ausonia's wasted cities dwell;\nRome shall no more her Anthony record,\nHer Marius, Sylla, Nero, Cajus fell.\nAnd this fifth Azo shall to scathe and shame\nPut Frederick, second Caeser of the name.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"He, with his better sceptre well contented,\nShall rule the city, seated by the streams,\nWhere Phoebus to his plaintive lyre lamented\nThe son, ill-trusted with the father's beams;\nWhere Cygnus spread his pinions, and the scented\nAmber was wept, as fabling poet dreams.\nTo him such honour shall the church decree;\nFit guerdon of his works, and valour's fee.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"But does no laurel for his brother twine,\nAldobrandino, who will carry cheer\nTo Rome (when Otho, with the Ghibelline,\nInto the troubled capital strikes fear),\nAnd make the Umbri and Piceni sign\nTheir shame, and sack the cities far and near;\nThen hopeless to relieve the sacred hold,\nSue to the neighbouring Florentine for gold:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"And trust a noble brother to his hands,\nBoasting no dearer pledge, the pact to bind:\nAnd next, victorious o'er the German bands,\nGive his triumphant ensigns to the wind:\nTo the afflicted church restore her lands,\nAnd take due vengeance of Celano's kind.\nThen die, cut off in manhood's early flower,\nBeneath the banners of the Papal power?</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"He, dying, leaves his brother Azo heir\nOf Pesaro and fair Ancona's reign,\nAnd all the cities which 'twixt Tronto are,\nAnd green Isauro's stream, from mount to main;\nWith other heritage, more rich and rare,\nGreatness of mind, and faith without a strain.\nAll else is Fortune's in this mortal state;\nBut Virtue soars beyond her love and hate.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"In good Rinaldo equal worth shall shine,\n(Such is the promise of his early fire)\nIf such a hope of thine exalted line.\nDark Fate and Fortune wreck not in their ire.\nAlas!  from Naples in this distant shrine,\nNaples, where he is hostage for his sire,\nHis dirge is heard: A stripling of thy race,\nYoung Obyson, shall fill his grandsire's place.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"This lord to his dominion shall unite\nGay Reggio, joined to Modena's bold land.\nAnd his redoubted valour lend such light,\nThe willing people call him to command.\nSixth of the name, his Azo rears upright\nThe church's banner in his noble hand:\nFair Adria's fief to him in dower shall bring\nThe child of second Charles, Sicilia's king.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XL</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Behold in yonder friendly group agreed.\nMany fair princes of illustrious name;\nObyson, Albert famed for pious deed,\nAldobrandino, Nicholas the lame.\nBut we may pass them by, for better speed,\nFaenza conquered, and their feats and fame;\nWith Adria (better held and surer gain)\nWhich gives her title to the neighbouring main:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"And that fair town, whose produce is the rose,\nThe rose which gives it name in Grecian speech:\nThat, too, which fishy marshes round enclose,\nAnd Po's two currents threat with double breach;\nWhose townsmen loath the lazy calm's repose,\nAnd pray that stormy waves may lash the beach.\nI pass, mid towns and towers, a countless store,\nArgenta, Lugo, and a thousand more.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"See Nicholas, whom in his tender age,\nThe willing people shall elect their lord;\nHe who shall laugh to scorn the civil rage\nOf the rebellious Tideus and his horde;\nWhose infantine delight shall be to wage\nThe mimic fight, and sweat with spear and sword:\nAnd through the discipline such nurture yields,\nShall flourish as the flower of martial fields.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"By him rebellious plans are overthrown,\nAnd turned upon the rash contriver's head;\nAnd so each stratagem of warfare blown,\nThat vainly shall the cunning toils be spread.\nTo the third Otho this too late is known,\nOf Parma and the pleasant Reggio dread;\nWho shall by him be spoiled in sudden strife,\nOf his possessions and his wretched life.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"And still the fair dominion shall increase,\nAnd without wrong its spreading bounds augment;\nNor its glad subjects violate the peace,\nUnless provoked some outrage to resent,\nAnd hence its wealth and welfare shall not cease;\nAnd the Divine Disposer be content\nTo let it flourish (such his heavenly love!)\nWhile the celestial spheres revolve above.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Lo!  Lionel!  lo!  Borse great and kind!\nFirst duke of thy fair race, his realm's delight;\nWho reigns secure, and shall more triumphs find\nIn peace, than warlike princes win in fight.\nWho struggling Fury's hands shall tie behind\nHer back, and prison Mars, removed from sight.\nHis fair endeavours bent to bless and stay\nThe people, that his sovereign rule obey.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Lo!  Hercules, who may reproach his neighbour,\nWith foot half burnt, and halting gait and slow,\nThat at Budrio, with protecting sabre,\nHe saved his troops from fatal overthrow;\nNot that, for guerdon of his glorious labour,\nHe should distress and vex him as a foe;\nChased into Barco.  It were hard to say,\nIf most he shine in peace or martial fray.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Lucania, Puglia, and Calabria's strand,\nShall with the rumour of his prowess ring:\nWhere he shall strive in duel, hand to hand,\nAnd gain the praise of Catalonia's king.\nHim, with the wisest captains of the land\nHis worth shall class; such fame his actions bring;\nAnd he the fief shall win like valiant knight,\nWhich thirty years before was his of right.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"To him his grateful city owes a debt,\nThe greatest subjects to their lord can owe;\nNot that he moves her from a marsh, to set\nHer stones, where Ceres' fruitful treasures grow.\nNor that he shall enlarge her bounds, nor yet\nThat he shall fence her walls against the foe;\nNor that he theatre and dome repairs,\nAnd beautifies her streets and goodly squares;</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Not that he keeps his lordship well defended\nFrom the winged lions' claws and fierce attacks;\nNor that, when Gallic ravage is extended,\nAnd the invader all Italia sacks,\nHis happy state alone is unoffended;\nUnharassed, and ungalled by toll or tax.\nNot for these blessings I recount, and more\nHis grateful realm shall Hercules adore;</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>L</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"So much as that from him shall spring a pair\nOf brothers, leagued no less by love than blood;\nWho shall be all that Leda's children were;\nThe just Alphonso, Hippolite the good.\nAnd as each twin resigned the vital air\nHis fellow to redeem from Stygian flood,\nSo each of these would gladly spend his breath,\nAnd for his brother brave perpetual death.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"In these two princes' excellent affection,\nTheir happy lieges more assurance feel,\nThan if their noble town, for its protection,\nWere girded twice by Vulcan's works of steel.\nAnd so Alphonso in his good direction,\nJustice, with knowledge and with love, shall deal,\nAstrea shall appear returned from heaven,\nTo this low earth to varying seasons given.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Well is it that his wisdom shines as bright\nAs his good sire's, nor is his valour less;\nSince here usurping Venice arms for fight,\nAnd her full troops his scanty numbers press,\nThere she (I know not if more justly hight\nMother or stepmother brings new distress; ) \n\nBut, if a mother, scarce to him more mild\nThan Progue or Medea to her child.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"This chief, what time soever he shall go\nForth with his faithful crew, by night or day,\nBy water or by land, will shame the foe,\nWith memorable rout and disarray;\nAnd this too late Romagna's sons shall know.\nLed against former friends in bloody fray,\nWho shall bedew the campaign with their blood,\nBy Santern, Po, and Zaniolus' flood.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"This shall the Spaniard know, to his dismay,\n'Mid the same bounds, whom papal gold shall gain,\nWho shall from him Bastia win and slay,\nWith cruel rage, her hapless Castellain,\nThe city taken; but shall dearly pay;\nHis crime, the town retrieved, and victor slain:\nSince in the rescued city not a groom\nIs left alive, to bear the news to Rome.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\" 'Tis he, who with his counsel and his lance,\nShall win the honours of Romagna's plain,\nAnd open to the chivalry of France\nThe victory over Julius, leagued with Spain.\nPaunch-deep in human blood shall steeds advance\nIn that fierce strife, and struggle through the slain,\n'Mid crowded fields, which scarce a grace supply,\nWhere Greek, Italian, Frank, and Spaniard die.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Lo!  who in priestly vesture clad, is crowned\nWith purple hat, conferred in hallowed dome!\n'Tis he, the wise, the liberal, the renowned\nHippolitus, great cardinal of Rome;\nWhose actions shall in every region sound,\nWhere'er the honoured muse shall find a home:\nTo whose glad era, by indulgent heaven,\nAs to Augustus' is a Maro given.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"His deeds adorn his race, as from his car\nThe glorious sun illumes the subject earth\nMore than the silver moon or lesser star;\nSo far all others he transcends in worth.\nI see this captain, ill bested for war,\nGo forth afflicted, and return in mirth:\nBacked by few foot, and fewer cavaliers,\nHe homeward barks, and fifteen gallies steers.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Two Sigismonds, the first, the second, see;\nTo these Alphonso's five good sons succeed;\nWhose glories spread o'er seas and land shall be.\nThe first shall wed a maid of France's seed.\nThis is the second Hercules; and he,\n(That you may know their every name and deed),\nHippolitus; who with the light shall shine,\nOf his wise uncle, gilding all his line.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Francis the third comes next; the other two\nAlphonsos both; — but yet again I say,\nThy line through all its branches to pursue,\nFair virgin, would too long protract thy stay;\nAnd Phoebus, many times, to mortal view,\nWould quench and light again the lamp of day.\nThen, with thy leave, 'tis time the pageant cease,\nAnd I dismiss the shades and hold my peace.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>So with the lady's leave the volume closed,\nWhose precepts to her will the spirits bent.\nAnd they, where Merlin's ancient bones reposed,\nFrom the first cavern disappearing, went.\nThen Bradamant her eager lips unclosed,\nSince the divine enchantress gave consent;\n\"And who,\" she cried, \"that pair of sorrowing mien,\nAlphonso and Hippolitus between?</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Sighing, those youths advanced amid the show,\nTheir brows with shame and sorrow overcast,\nWith downward look, and gait subdued and slow:\nI saw the brothers shun them as they passed.\"\nMelissa heard the dame with signs of woe,\nAnd thus, with streaming eyes, exclaim'd at last:\n\"Ah! luckless youths, with vain illusions fed,\nWhither by wicked men's bad counsel led!</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"O, worthy seed of Hercules the good,\nLet not their guilt beyond thy love prevail;\nAlas!  the wretched pair are of thy blood,\nSo many prevailing pity turn the scale!\"\nAnd in a sad and softer tone pursued,\n\"I will not further press the painful tale.\nChew on fair fancy's food: Nor deem unmeet\nI will not with a bitter chase the sweet.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Soon as to-morrow's sun shall gild the skies\nWith his first light, myself the way will show\nTo where the wizard knight Rogero sties;\nAnd built with polished steel the ramparts glow:\nSo long as through deep woods thy journey lies,\nTill, at the sea arrived, I shall bestow\nSuch new instructions for the future way,\nThat thou no more shalt need Melissa's stay.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>All night the maid reposes in the cave,\nAnd the best part in talk with Merlin spends;\nWhile with persuasive voice the wizard grave\nTo her Rogero's honest love commends;\nTill from the vault goes forth that virgin brave,\nAs through the sky the rising sun ascends,\nBy path, long space obscure on either side,\nThe weird woman still her faithful guide.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>They gain a hidden glen, which heights inclose,\nAnd mountains inaccessible to man:\nAnd they all day toil on, without repose,\nWhere precipices frowned and torrents ran.\nAnd (what may some diversion interpose)\nSweet subjects of discourse together scan,\nIn conference, which best might make appear\nThe rugged road less dismal and severe.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Of these the greater portion served to guide\n(Such the wise woman's scope the warlike dame; ) \n\nAnd teach by what device might be untied\nRogero's gyves, if stedfast were her flame.\n\"If thou wert Mars himself, or Pallas,\" cried\nThe sage Melissa, \"though with thee there came\nMore than King Charles or Agramant command,\nAgainst the wizard foe thou could'st not stand.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Besides that it is walled about with steel,\nAnd inexpugnable his tower, and high;\nBesides that his swift horse is taught to wheel,\nAnd caracol and gallop in mid sky,\nHe bears a mortal shield of power to seal,\nAs soon as 'tis exposed, the dazzled eye;\nAnd so invades each sense, the splendour shed,\nThat he who sees the blaze remains as dead.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"And lest to shut thine eyes, thou should'st suppose\nMight serve, contending with the wizard knight;\nHow would'st thou know, when both in combat close,\nWhen he strikes home, or when eschews the fight?\nBut to escape the blaze which blinds his foes,\nAnd render vain each necromantic sleight,\nHave here a speedy mean which cannot miss;\nNor can the world afford a way but this.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"King Agramant of Africa a ring.\nThieved from an Indian queen by subtle guiles,\nHas to a baron of his following\nConsigned, who now precedes us by few miles;\nBrunello he.  Who wears the gift shall bring\nTo nought all sorceries and magic wiles.\nIn thefts and cheats Brunello is as well\nInstructed, as the sage in charm and spell.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Brunello, he so practised and so sly\nAs now I tell thee, by his king is sent,\nThat he with aid of mother wit may try,\nAnd of this ring, well proved in like event,\nTo take Rogero from the castle high;\nSo has he boasted, by the wizard pent:\nAnd to his lord such promise did impart,\nWho has Rogero's presence most at heart.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"That his escape to thee alone may owe,\nNot to the king, the youthful cavalier,\nHow to release Rogero from his foe\nAnd his enchanted cage, prepare to hear.\nThree days along the shingle shalt thou go,\nBeside the sea, whose waves will soon appear;\nThee the third day shall to a hostel bring,\nWhere he shall come who bears the virtuous ring.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"That thou may'st recognise the man, in height\nLess than six palms, observe one at this inn\nOf black and curly hair, the dwarfish wight!\nBeard overgrown about the cheek and chin;\nWith shaggy brow, swoln eyes, and cloudy sight,\nA nose close flattened, and a sallow skin;\nTo this, that I may make my sketch complete,\nSuccinctly clad, like courier, goes the cheat.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Thy conversation with this man shall turn\nUpon enchantment, spell, and mystic pact;\nAnd thou shalt, in thy talk, appear to yearn\nTo prove the wizard's strength, as is the fact.\nBut, lady, let him not thy knowledge learn\nOf his good ring, which mars all magic act:\nHe shall propose to bring thee as a guide\nTo the tall castle, whither thou would'st ride.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Follow him close, and viewing (for a sign),\nNow near, the fortress of the enchanter hoar;\nLet no false pity there thy mind incline\nTo stay the execution of my lore.\nGive him his death; but let him not divine\nThy thought, nor grant him respite; for before\nThine eyes, concealed by it, the caitiff slips\nIf once he place the ring between his lips.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Discoursing thus, they came upon the sea\nWhere Garonne near fair Bordeaux meets the tide;\nHere, fellow travellers no more to be,\nSome natural tears they drop and then divide.\nDuke Aymon's child, who slumbers not till she\nRelease her knight, holds on till even-tide:\n'Twas then the damsel at a hostel rested,\nWhere Sir Brunello was already guested.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The maid Brunello knows as soon as found\n(So was his image on her mind impressed),\nAnd asks him whence he came, and whither bound;\nAnd he replies and lies, as he is pressed.\nThe dame, who is forewarned, and knows her ground,\nFeigns too as well as he, and lies her best:\nAnd changes sex and sect, and name and land,\nAnd her quick eye oft glances at his hand;</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Oft glances at his resless hand, in fear\nThat he might undetected make some prize;\nNor ever lets the knave approach too near,\nWell knowing his condition: In this guise\nThe couple stand together, when they hear\nA sudden sound:  but what that sound implies\nI, sir, shall tell hereafter with its cause;\nBut first shall break my song with fitting pause.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 4"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The old Atlantes suffers fatal wreck,\nFoiled by the ring, and young Rogero freed,\nWho soars in air till he appears a speck,\nMounted upon the wizard's winged steed.\nObediant to the royal Charles's beck,\nHe who had followed Love's imperious lead,\nRinaldo, disembarks on British land,\nAnd saves Genevra, doomed to stake and brand.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>I</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Though an ill mind appear in simulation,\nAnd, for the most, such quality offends;\n'Tis plain that this in many a situation\nIs found to further beneficial ends,\nAnd save from blame, and danger, and vexation;\nSince we converse not always with our friends,\nIn this, less clear than clouded, mortal life,\nBeset with snares, and full of envious strife.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>II</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>If after painful proof we scarcely find\nA real friend, through various chances sought,\nTo whom we may communicate our mind,\nKeeping no watch upon our wandering thought;\nWhat should the young Rogero's lady kind\nDo with Brunello, not sincere, but fraught\nWith treasons manifold, and false and tainted,\nAs by the good enchantress truly painted?</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>III</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>She feigns as well with that deceitful scout;\n(Fitting with him the father of all lies)\nWatches his thievish hands in fear and doubt;\nAnd follows every motion with her eyes.\nWhen lo!  a mighty noise is heard without!\n\"O mighty mother!  king of heaven!\" she cries,\n\"What thing is this I hear?\" and quickly springs\nTowards the place from whence the larum rings,</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>IV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And sees the host and all his family,\nWhere, one to door, and one to window slips,\nWith eyes upturned and gazing at the sky,\nAs if to witness comet or eclipse.\nAnd there the lady views, with wondering eye,\nWhat she had scarce believed from other's lips,\nA feathered courser, sailing through the rack,\nWho bore an armed knight upon his back.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>V</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Broad were his pinions, and of various hue;\nSeated between, a knight the saddle pressed,\nClad in steel arms, which wide their radiance threw,\nHis wonderous course directed to the west:\nThere dropt among the mountains lost to view.\nAnd this was, as that host informed his guest,\n(And true the tale a sorcerer, who made ) \n\nNow farther, now more near, his frequent raid.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>VI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"He, sometimes towering, soars into the skies;\nThen seems, descending, but to skim the ground:\nAnd of all beauteous women makes a prize,\nWho, to their mischief, in these parts are found.\nHence, whether in their own or other's eyes,\nEsteemed as fair, the wretched damsels round,\n(And all in fact the felon plunders hine; ) \n\nAs fearing of the sun to be descried.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>VII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"A castle on the Pyrenean height\nThe necromancer keeps, the work of spell.\"\n(The host relates \"of steel, so fair and bright, ) \n\nAll nature cannot match the wonderous shell.\nThere many cavaliers, to prove their might,\nHave gone, but none returned the tale to tell.\nSo that I doubt, fair sir, the thief enthralls\nOr slays whoever in the encounter falls.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>VIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The watchful maid attends to every thing,\nGlad at her heart, and trusting to complete\n(What she shall compass by the virtuous ring)\nThe downfall of the enchanter and his seat.\nThen to the host — \"A guide I pray thee bring,\nWho better knows than me the thief's retreat.\nSo burns my heart. (nor can I choose but go)\nTo strive in battle with this wizard foe.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>IX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"It shall not need,\" exclaimed the dwarfish Moor,\n\"For I, myself, will serve you as a guide;\nWho have the road set down, with other lore,\nSo that you shall rejoice with me to ride.\"\nHe meant the ring, but further hint forbore;\nLest dearly he the avowed should abide.\nAnd she to him — \"Your guidance gives me pleasure.\"\nMeaning by this she hoped to win his treasure.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>X</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>What useful was to say, she said, and what\nMight hurt her with the Saracen, concealed.\nWell suited to her ends, the host had got\nA palfrey, fitting for the road or field.\nShe bought the steed, and as Aurora shot\nHer rosy rays, rode forth with spear and shield:\nAnd maid and courier through a valley wind,\nBrunello now before and now behind.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>From wood to wood, from mount to mountain hoar,\nThey clomb a summit, which in cloudless sky\nDiscovers France and Spain, and either shore.\nAs from a peak of Apennine the eye\nMay Tuscan and Sclavonian sea explore,\nThere, whence we journey to Camaldoli.\nThen through a rugged path and painful wended,\nWhich thence into a lowly vale descended.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>A rock from that deep valley's centre springs;\nBright walls of steel about its summit go:\nAnd this as high that airy summit flings,\nAs it leaves all the neighbouring cliffs below.\nHe may not scale the height who has not wings,\nAnd vainly would each painful toil bestow.\n\"Lo!  where his prisoners!\"  Sir Brunello cries,\n\"Ladies and cavaliers, the enchanter sties.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Scarped smooth upon four parts, the mountain bare\nSeemed fashioned with the plumb, by builder's skill\nNor upon any side was path or stair,\nWhich furnished man the means to climb the hill.\nThe castle seemed the very nest and lair\nOf animal, supplied with plume and quill.\nAnd here the damsel knows 'tis time to slay\nThe wily dwarf, and take the ring away.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>But deems it foul, with blood of man to stain\nUnarmed and of so base a sort, her brand;\nFor well, without his death, she may obtain\nThe costly ring; and so suspends her hand.\nBrunello, off his guard, with little pain,\nShe seized, and strongly bound with girding band:\nThen to a lofty fir made fast the string;\nBut from his finger first withdrew the ring.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Neither by tears, nor groans, nor sound of woe,\nTo move the stedfast maid the dwarf had power:\nShe down the rugged hill descended slow,\nUntil she reached the plain beneath the tower.\nThen gave her bugle breath, the keep below,\nTo call the castled wizard to the stower:\nAnd when the sound was finished, threatening cried,\nAnd called him to the combat and defied.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Not long within his gate the enchanter stayed,\nAfter he heard the voice and bugle ring.\nAgainst the foe, who seemed a man, arrayed\nIn arms, with him the horse is on the wing.\nBut his appearance well consoled the maid,\nWho, with small cause for fear, beheld him bring\nNor mace, nor rested lance, nor bitting sword,\nWherewith the corselet might be bruised or gored.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>On his left arm alone his shield he took,\nCovered all o'er with silk of crimson hue;\nIn his right-hand he held an open book,\nWhence, as the enchanter read, strange wonder grew:\nFor often times, to sight, the lance he shook;\nAnd flinching eyelids could not hide the view;\nWith tuck or mace he seemed to smite the foe:\nBut sate aloof and had not struck a blow.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>No empty fiction wrought by magic lore,\nBut natural was the steed the wizard pressed;\nFor him a filly to griffin bore;\nHight hippogryph.  In wings and beak and crest,\nFormed like his sire, as in the feet before;\nBut like the mare, his dam, in all the rest.\nSuch on Riphaean hills, though rarely found,\nAre bred, beyond the frozen ocean's bound.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Drawn by enchantment from his distant lair,\nThe wizard thought but how to tame the foal;\nAnd, in a month, instructed him to bear\nSaddle and bit, and gallop to the goal;\nAnd execute on earth or in mid air,\nAll shifts of manege, course and caracole;\nHe with such labour wrought.  This only real,\nWhere all the rest was hollow and ideal.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>This truth by him with fictions was combined,\nWhose sleight passed red for yellow, black for white:\nBut all his vain enchantments could not blind\nThe maid, whose virtuous ring assured her sight:\nYet she her blows discharges at the wind;\nAnd spurring here and there prolongs the fight.\nSo drove or wheeled her steed, and smote at nought,\nAnd practised all she had before been taught.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>When she sometime had fought upon her horse,\nShe from the courser on her feet descends:\nTo compass and more freely put in force,\nAs by the enchantress schooled, her wily ends.\nThe wizard, to display his last resource,\nUnweeting the defence, towards her wends.\nHe bares the shield, secure to blind his foe,\nAnd by the magic light, astonished, throw.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The shield might have been shown at first, nor he\nNeeded to keep the cavaliers at bay;\nBut that he loved some master-stroke to see,\nAchieved by lance or sword in single fray.\nAs with the captive mouse, in sportive glee,\nThe wily cat is sometimes seen to play;\nTill waxing wroth, or weary of her prize,\nShe bites, and at a snap the prisoner dies.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>To cat and mouse, in battles fought before,\nI liken the magician and his foes;\nBut the comparison holds good no more:\nFor, with the ring, the maid against him goes;\nFirm and attentive still, and watching sore,\nLest upon her the wizard should impose:\nAnd as she sees him bare the wondrous shield,\nCloses her eyes and falls upon the field.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Not that the shining metal could offend,\nAs wont those others, from its cover freed;\nBut so the damsel did, to make descend\nThe vain enchanter from his wondrous steed.\nNor was in ought defeated of her end;\nFor she no sooner on the grassy mead\nHad laid her head, than wheeling widely round,\nThe flying courser pitched upon the ground.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Already cased again, the shield was hung,\nBy the magician, at his sadle bow.\nHe lights and seeks her, who like wolf among\nThe bushes, couched in thicket, waits the roe;\nShe without more delay from ambush sprung,\nAs he drew near, and grappled fast the foe.\nThat wretched man, the volume by whose aid\nHe all his battles fought, on earth had laid:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And ran to bind her with a chain, which he,\nGirt round about him for such a purpose, wore;\nBecause he deemed she was no less to be\nMastered and bound than those subdued before.\nHim hath the dame already flung; by me\nExcused with reason, if he strove not more.\nFor fearful were the odds between that bold\nAnd puissant maid, and warrior weak and old!</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Intending to behead the fallen foe,\nShe lifts her conquering hand; but in mid space,\nWhen she beholds his visage, stops the blow,\nAs if disdaining a revenge so base.\nShe sees in him, her prowess has laid low,\nA venerable sire, with sorrowing face;\nWhose hair and wrinkles speak him, to her guess,\nOf years six score and ten, or little less.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Kill me, for love of God!\" (afflicted sore,\nThe old enchanter full of wrath did cry).\nBut the victorious damsel was not more\nAverse to kill, than he was bent to die.\nTo know who was the necromancer hoar\nThe gentle lady had desire, and why\nThe tower he in that savage place designed,\nDoing such outrage foul to all mankind.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Nor I, by malice moved, alas!  poor wight,\"\n(The weeping necromancer answer made,)\n\"Built the fair castle on the rocky height,\nNor yet for rapine ply the robber's trade;\nBut only to redeem a gentle knight\nFrom danger sore and death, by love was swayed;\nWho, as the skies foreshow, in little season,\nIs doomed to die a Christian, and by treason.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"The sun beholds not 'twixt the poles, a Child\nSo excellent as him, and passing fair;\nWho from his infancy, Rogero styled,\n(Atlantes I was tutored by my care. ) \n\nBy love of fame and evil stars beguiled,\nHe follows into France Troyano's heir.\nHim, in my eyes, than son esteemed more dear,\nI seek to snatch from France and peril near.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"I only built the beauteous keep to be\nRogero's dungeon, safely harboured there;\nWho whilom was subdued in fight by me,\nAs I to-day had hoped thyself to snare,\nAnd dames and knights, and more of high degree,\nHave to this tower conveyed, his lot to share,\nThat with such partners of his prison pent,\nHe might the loss of freedom less lament.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Save they should seek to break their dungeon's bound,\nI grant my inmates every other pleasure.\nFor whatsoever in the world is found,\nSearch its four quarters, in this keep I treasure;\n(Whatever heart can wish or tongue can sound)\nCates, brave attire, game, sport, or mirthful measure.\nMy field well sown, I well had reaped my grain.\nBut that thy coming makes my labour vain.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Ah!  then unless thy heart less beauteous be\nThan thy sweet face, mar not my pious care;\nTake my steel buckler, this I give to thee,\nAnd take that horse, which flies so fast in air,\nNor meddle with my castle more; or free\nOne or two captive friends, the rest forbear —\nOr (for I crave but this release them all, ) \n\nSo that Rogero but remain my thrall.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Or if disposed to take him from my sight,\nBefore the youth be into France conveyed,\nBe pleased to free my miserable sprite\nFrom its now rotted bark, long decayed.\"\n\"Prate as thou wilt, I shall restore the knight\nTo liberty,\"  replied the martial maid,\n\"Nor offer shield and courser to resign,\nWhich are not in thy gift, — already mine.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Nor were they thine to take or to bestow,\nWould it appear that such exchange were wise;\nThou sayest to save him from what stars foreshow,\nAnd cheat an evil influence of the skies\nRogero is confined.  Thou canst not know,\nOr knowing, canst not change his destinies:\nFor, if unknown an ill so near to thee,\nFar less mayest thou another's fate foresee.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Seek not thy death from me; for the petition\nIs made in vain; but if for death thou sigh,\nThough the whole world refused the requisition,\nA soul resolved would find the means to die.\nBut ope thy gates to give thy guests dismission\nBefore thine hand the knot of life untie.\"\nSo spake the scornful dame with angry mock,\nSpeeding her captive still towards the rock.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Round by the conqueror with the chain he bore,\nAtlantes walked, the damsel following nigh,\nWho trusted not to the magician hoar,\nAlthough he seemed subdued in port and eye.\nNor many paces went the pair, before\nThey at the mountain's foot the cleft espy,\nWith steps by which the rugged hill to round;\nAnd climb, till to the castle-gate they wound:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Atlantes from the threshold, graved by skill,\nWith characters and wondrous signs, upturned\nA virtuous stone, where, underneath the sill,\nPots, with perpetual fire and secret, burned.\nThe enchanter breaks them; and at once the hill\nTo an inhospitable rock is turned.\nNor wall nor tower on any side is seen,\nAs if no castle there had ever been.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Then from the lady's toils the wizard clears\nHis limbs, as thrush escapes the fowler's snare;\nWith him as well his castle disappears,\nAnd leaves the prisoned troop in open air;\nFrom their gay lodgings, dames and cavaliers,\nUnhoused upon that desert, bleak and bare.\nAnd many at the freedom felt annoy,\nWhich dispossessed them of such life of joy.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XL</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>There is Gradasso, there is Sacripant,\nThere is Prasildo, noble cavalier,\nWho with Rinaldo came from the Levant;\nIroldo, too, Prasildo's friend sincere.\nAnd there, at last, the lovely Bradamant\nDiscerns Rogero, long desired and dear;\nWho, when assured it was that lady, flew\nWith joyful cheer to greet the damsel true;</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>As her he prized before his eyes, his heart,\nHis life; from that day cherished when she stood\nUncasqued for him, and from the fight apart;\nAnd hence an arrow drank her virgin blood.\n'Twere long to tell who launched the cruel dart,\nAnd how the lovers wandered in the wood;\nNow guided by the sun, and now benighted,\nHere first since that encounter reunited.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Now that the stripling sees her here, and knows\nAlone she freed him from the wizard's nest,\nHe deems, his bosom with such joy overflows,\nThat he is singly fortunate and blest.\nThither, where late the damsel conquered, goes\nThe band, descending from the mountain's crest;\nAnd finds the hippogryph, who bore the shield,\nBut in its case of crimson silk concealed.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>To take him by the rein the lady there\nApproached, and he stood fast till she was nigh,\nThen spread his pinions to the liquid air,\nAnd at short distance lit, half-mountain high:\nAnd, as she follows him with fruitless care,\nNot longer flight nor shorter will he try.\n'Tis thus the raven, on some sandy beach,\nLures on the dog, and flits beyond his reach.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Gradasso, Sacripant, Rogero, who\nWith all those other knights below were met,\nWhere'er, they hope he may return, pursue\nThe beast, and up and down, each pass beset.\nHe having led those others, as he flew,\nOften to rocky height, and bottom wet,\nAmong the rocks of the moist valley dropt,\nAnd at short distance from Rogero stopt.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>This was Atlantes the enchanter's deed,\nWhose pious wishes still directed were,\nTo see Rogero from his peril freed:\nThis was his only thought, his only care;\nWho for such end dispatched the winged steed,\nHim out of Europe by this sleight to bear.\nRogero took his bridle, but in vain;\nFor he was restive to the guiding rein.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Now the bold youth from his Frontino flings\n(Frontino was his gentle courser hight)\nThen leaps on him who towers in air, and stings\nAnd goads his haughty heart with rowels bright.\nHe runs a short career; then upward springs.\nAnd through mid ether soars a fairer flight\nThan hawk, from which the falconer plucks away\nIn time the blinding hood, and points her prey.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>When her Rogero the fair dame discerned,\nIn fearful peril, soar so high a strain,\nShe stood long space amazed, ere she returned\nTo her right judgement, and sound wits again:\nAnd what she erst of Ganymede had learned,\nSnatched up to heaven from his paternal reign,\nFeared might befall the stripling, born through air,\nAs gentle as young Ganymede and fair.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>She on Rogero looks with stedfast eyes\nAs long as feeble sight can serve her use;\nAnd in her mind next tracks him through the skies,\nWhen sight in vain the cherished youth pursues.\nAnd still renewing tears, and groans, and sighs,\nWill not afford her sorrow peace or truce.\nAfter the knight had vanished from her view,\nHer eyes she on the good Frontino threw.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And lest the courser should become the prey\nOf the first traveller, who passed the glen,\nHim will not leave; but thence to bear away\nResolves, in trust to see his lord again.\nThe griffin soars, nor can Rogero stay\nThe flying courser; while, beneath his ken,\nEach peak and promontory sinks in guise,\nThat he discerns not flat from mountain-rise.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>L</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>After the hippogryph has won such height,\nThat he is lessened to a point, he bends\nHis course for where the sun, with sinking light,\nWhen he goes round the heavenly crab, descends;\nAnd shoots through air, like well-greased bark and light,\nWhich through the sea a wind propitious sends.\nHim leave we on his way, who well shall speed,\nAnd turn we to Rinaldo in his need.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Day after day the good Rinaldo fares,\nForced by the wind, the spacious ocean through;\nNow westward borne, and now toward the Bears;\nFor night and day the ceaseless tempest blew.\nScotland at last her dusky coast uprears,\nAnd gives the Caledonian wood to view;\nWhich, through its shadowy groves of ancient oak,\nOft echoes to the champion's sturdy stroke.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Through this roves many a famous cavalier,\nRenowned for feat in arms, of British strain;\nAnd throng from distant land, or country near,\nFrench, Norse, of German knights, a numerous train.\nLet none, save he be valiant, venture here,\nWhere, seeking glory, death may be his gain.\nHere Arthur, Galahalt, and Gauvaine fought,\nAnd well Sir Launcelot and Tristram wrought.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And other worthies of the table round;\n(Of either table, whether old or new)\nWhose trophies yet remain upon the ground;\nProof of their valiant feats, Rinaldo true\nForthwith his armour and Bayardo found,\nAnd landed on the woody coast: The crew\nHe bade, with all the haste they might, repair\nTo Berwick's neighbouring port, and wait him there.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Without a guide or company he went\nThrough that wide forest; choosing now this way,\nNow that, now other, as it might present\nHope of adventurous quest or hard assay:\nAnd, ere the first day's circling sun is spent,\nThe peer is guested in an abbey gray:\nWhich spends much wealth in harbouring those who claim\nIts shelter, warlike knight or wandering dame.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The monks and abbot to Mount Alban's peer\nA goodly welcome in their house accord;\nWho asked, but not before with savoury cheer\nHe amply had his wearied strength restored,\nIf in that tract, by errant cavalier,\nOften adventurous quest might be explored,\nIn which a man might prove, by dangerous deed,\nIf blame or glory were his fitting meed.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>They answered, in those woods he might be sure\nMany and strange adventures would be found;\nBut deeds, there wrought, were, like the place, obscure,\nAnd, for the greater part, not bruited round.\n\"Then seek (they said a worthier quest, secure ) \n\nYour works will not be buried underground.\nSo that the glorious act achieved, as due,\nFame may your peril and your pain pursue.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"And if you would your warlike worth assay,\nPrepare the worthiest enterprize to hear,\nThat, e'er in times of old or present day,\nWas undertaken by a cavalier.\nOur monarch's daughter needs some friendly stay,\nNow sore bested, against a puissant peer:\nLurcanio is the doughty baron's name,\nWho would bereave her both of life and fame.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Her he before her father does pursue,\nPerchance yet more for hatred than for right;\nAnd vouches, to a gallery she updrew\nA lover, seen by him, at dead of night.\nHence death by fire will be the damsel's due,\nSuch is our law, unless some champion fight\nOn her behalf, and, ere a month go by,\n(Nigh spent upon the accuser prove the lie. ) \n</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Our impious Scottish law, severe and dread,\nWills, that a woman, whether low or high\nHer state, who takes a man into her bed,\nExcept her husband, for the offence shall die.\nNor is there hope of ransom for her head,\nUnless to her defence some warrior hie;\nAnd as her champion true, with spear and shield,\nMaintain her guiltless in the listed field.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"The king, sore grieving for Geneura bright,\nFor such is his unhappy daughter's name,\nProclaims by town and city, that the knight\nWho shall deliver her from death and shame,\nHe to the royal damsel will unite,\nWith dower, well suited to a royal dame;\nSo that the valiant warrior who has stood\nIn her defence, be come of gentle blood.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"But if within a month no knight appear,\nOr coming, conquer not, the damsel dies.\nA like emrpize were worthier of your spear\nThan wandering through these woods in lowly guise.\nBesides, the eternal trophy you shall rear,\nYou by the deed shall gain a glorious prize,\nThe sweetest flower of all the ladies fair\nThat betwixt Ind and Atlas' pillars are.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"And you with wealth and state shall guerdoned be,\nSo that you evermore may live content,\nAnd the king's grace, if through your means he see\nHis honour raised anew, now well-nigh spent.\nBesides, you by the laws of chivalry\nAre bound to venge the damsel foully shent.\nFor she, whose life is by such treason sought,\nIs chaste and spotless in the common thought.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Rinaldo mused awhile, and then replied,\n\"And must a gentle damsel die by fire,\nBecause she with a lover's wish complied,\nAnd quenched within her arms his fond desire?\nCursed be the law by which the dame is tried!\nCursed he who would permit a doom so dire!\nPerish (such fate were just! who cruel proves! ) \n\nNot she that life bestows on him who loves.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Or true or false Geneura's tale of shame;\nIf she her lover blessed I little heed:\nFor this my praise the lady well might claim,\nIf manifest were not that gentle deed.\nMy every thought is turned to aid the dame.\nGrant me but one to guide my steps, and lead\nQuickly to where the foul accuser stands,\nI trust in God to loose Geneura's bands.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"I will not vouch her guiltless in my thought,\nIn fear to warrant what is false; but I\nBoldly maintain, in such an act is nought\nFor which the damsel should deserve to die;\nAnd ween unjust, or else of wit distraught,\nWho statutes framed of such severity;\nWhich, as iniquitous, should be effaced,\nAnd with a new and better code replaced.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"If like desire, and if an equal flame\nMove one and the other sex, who warmly press\nTo that soft end of love (their goal the same)\nWhich to the witless crowd seems rank excess;\nSay why shall woman — merit scathe or blame,\nThough lovers, one or more, she may caress;\nWhile man to sin with whom he will is free,\nAnd meets with praise, not mere impunity?</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"By this injurious law, unequal still,\nOn woman is inflicted open wrong;\nAnd to demonstrate it a grievous ill,\nI trust in God, which has been borne too long.\"\nTo good Rinaldo's sentence, with one will,\nDeeming their sires unjust, assents the throng,\nTheir sires who such outrageous statute penned,\nAnd king, who might, but does not, this amend.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>When the new dawn, with streaks of red and white,\nBroke in the east, and cleared the hemisphere,\nRinaldo took his steed and armour bright:\nA squire that abbey furnished to the peer.\nWith him, for many leagues and miles, the knight\nPricked through the dismal forest dark and drear;\nWhile they towards the Scottish city ride,\nWhere the poor damsel's cause is to be tried.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Seeking their way to shorten as they wound,\nThey to the wider track a path preferred;\nWhen echoing through the gloomy forest round,\nLoud lamentations nigh the road were heard.\nTowards a neighbouring vale, whence came the sound,\nThis his Bayardo, that his hackney spurred;\nAnd viewed, between two grisly ruffians there,\nA girl, who seemed at distance passing fair.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>But woe begone and weeping was the maid\nAs ever damsel dame, or wight was seen:\nHard by the barbarous twain prepared the blade,\nTo deluge with that damsel's blood the green.\nShe to delay her death awhile essayed,\nUntil she pity moved with mournful mien.\nThis when Rinaldo near approaching eyes,\nHe thither drives with threats and furious cries.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The ruffians turn their backs and take to flight\nAs soon as they the distant succour view,\nAnd squat within a valley out of sight:\nNor cares the good Rinaldo to pursue.\nTo her approaching, sues Mount Alban's knight,\nTo say what on her head such evil drew;\nAnd, to save time, commands his squire to stoop,\nAnd take the damsel on his horse's croup.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And as the lady nearer he surveyed,\nHer wise behaviour marked and beauty's bloom;\nThough her fait countenance was all dismayed,\nAnd by the fear of death o'erspread with gloom.\nAgain to know, the gentle knight essayed,\nWho had prepared for her so fell a doom;\nAnd she began to tell in humble tone</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>Canto I postpone.</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 5"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Lurcanio, by a false report abused,\nDeemed by Geneura's fault his brother dead,\nWeening the faithless duke, whom she refused,\nWas taken by the damsel to her bed;\nAnd her before the king and peers accused:\nBut to the session Ariodantes led,\nStrives with his brother in disguise.  In season\nRinaldo comes to venge the secret treason.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>I</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Among all other animals who prey\nOn earth, or who unite in friendly wise,\nWhether they mix in peace or moody fray,\nNo male offends his mate.  In safety hies\nThe she bear, matched with hers, through forest gray:\nThe lioness beside the lion lies:\nWolves, male and female, live in loving cheer;\nNor gentle heifer dreads the wilful steer.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>II</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>What Fury, what abominable Pest\nSuch poison in the human heart has shed,\nThat still 'twixt man and wife, with rage possessed,\nInjurious words and foul reproach are said?\nAnd blows and outrage hase their peace molest,\nAnd bitter tears still wash the genial bed;\nNot only watered by the tearful flood,\nBut often bathed by senseless ire with blood?</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>III</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Not simply a rank sinner, he appears\nTo outrage nature, and his God to dare,\nWho his foul hand against a woman rears,\nOr of her head would harm a single hair.\nBut who what drug the burning entrail sears,\nOr who for her would knife or noose prepare,\nNo man appears to me, though such to sight\nHe seem, but rather some infernal sprite.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>IV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Such, and no other were those ruffians two,\nWhom good Rinaldo from the damsel scared,\nConducted to these valleys out of view,\nThat none might wot of her so foully snared.\nI ended where the damsel, fair of hue,\nTo tell the occasion of her scathe prepared,\nTo the good Paladin, who brought release;\nAnd in conclusion thus my story piece.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>V</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Of direr deed than ever yet was done,\"\nThe gentle dame began, \"Sir cavalier,\nIn Thebes, Mycene, Argos, or upon\nOther more savage soil, prepare to hear;\nAnd I believe, that if the circling sun\nTo these our Scottish shores approach less near\nThan other land, 'tis that he would eschew\nA foul ferocious race that shocks his view.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>VI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"All times have shown that man has still pursued\nWith hair, in every clime, his natural foe;\nBut to deal death to those who seek our good\nDoes from too ill and foul a nature flow.\nNow, that the truth be better understood,\nI shall from first to last the occasion show,\nWhy in my tender years, against all right,\nThose caitiffs would have dome me foul despite.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>VII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\" 'Tis fitting you should know, that in the spring\nOf life, I to the palace made resort;\nThere served long time the daughter of the king,\nAnd grew with her in growth, well placed in court.\nWhen cruel love, my fortune envying,\nWilled I should be his follower and his sport;\nAnd made, beyond each Scottish lord and knight,\nAlbany's duke find favour in my sight.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>VIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"And for he seemed to cherish me above\nAll mean; his love a love as ardent bred.\nWe hear, indeed, and see, but do not prove\nMan's faith, nor is his bosom's purpose read.\nBelieving still, and yielding to my love,\nI ceased not till I took him to my bed;\nNor, of all chambers, in that evil hour,\nMarked I was in Geneura's priviest bower.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>IX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Where, hoarded, she with careful privacy\nPreserved whatever she esteemed most rare;\nThere many times she slept.  A gallery\nFrom thence projected into the open air.\nHere oft I made my lover climb to me,\nAnd (what he was to mount a hempen stair, ) \n\nWhen him I to my longing arms would call,\nFrom the projecting balcony let fall.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>X</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"For here my passion I as often fed\nAs good Geneura's absence made me bold;\nWho with the varying season changed her bed,\nTo shun the burning heat or pinching cold,\nAnd Albany, unseen and safely sped;\nFor, fronting a dismantled street, and old,\nWas built that portion of the palace bright;\nNor any went that way by day or night.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"So was for many days and months maintained\nBy us, in secrecy, the amorous game;\nStill grew by love, and such new vigour gained,\nI in my inmost bosom felt the flame;\nAnd that he little loved, and deeply feigned\nWeened not, so was I blinded to my shame:\nThough, in a thousand certain signs betrayed,\nThe faithless knight his base deceit bewrayed.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"After some days, of fair Geneura he\nA suitor showed himself; I cannot say\nIf this began before he sighed for me,\nOr, after, of this love he made assay:\nBut judge, alas!  with what supremacy\nHe ruled my heart, how absolute his sway!\nSince this he owned, and thought no shame to move\nMe to assist him in his second love.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Unlike what he bore me, he said, indeed,\nThat was not true which he for her displayed;\nBut so pretending love, he hoped to speed,\nAnd celebrate due spousals with the maid.\nHe with her royal sire might well succeed,\nWere she consenting to the boon he prayed;\nFor after our good king, for wealth and birth\nIn all the realm, was none of equal worth.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Me he persuades, if through my ministry\nHe the king's son-in-law elected were,\nFor I must know he next the king would be\nAdvanced as high, as subject could repair,\nThe merit should be mine, and ever he\nSo great a benefit in mind would bear;\nAnd he would cherish me above his bride,\nAnd more than every other dame beside.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"I, who to please him was entirely bent,\nWho never could or would gainsay his will,\nUpon those days alone enjoy content,\nWhen I find means his wishes to fulfil:\nAnd snatch at all occasions which present\nA mode, his praise and merits to instil:\nAnd for my lover with all labour strain,\nAnd industry, Geneura's love to gain.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"With all my heart, in furtherance of his suit,\nI wrought what could be done, God truly knows;\nBut with Geneura this produced no friut,\nNor her to grace my duke could I dispose.\nFor that another love had taken root\nIn her, whose every fond affection flows\nTowards a gentle knight of courteous lore,\nWho sought our Scotland from a distant shore:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"And with a brother, then right young, to stay\nIn our king's court, came out of Italy:\nAnd there of knightly arms made such assay,\nWas none in Britain more approved than he;\nPrized by the king, who (no ignoble pay),\nRewarding him like his nobility,\nBestowed upon the youth, with liberal hand,\nBurghs, baronies, and castles, woods and land.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Dear to the monarch, to the daughter still\nThis lord was dearer, Ariodantes hight.\nHer with affection might his valour fill;\nBut knowledge of his love brought more delight.\nNor old Vesuvius, nor Sicilia's hill,\nNor Troy-town, ever, with a blaze so bright,\nFlamed, as with all his heart, the damsel learned,\nFor love of her young Ariodantes burned.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"The passion which she bore the lord, preferred\nAnd loved with perfect truth and all her heart,\nWas the occassion I was still unheard;\nNor hopeful answer would she e'er impart:\nAnd still the more my lover's suit I stirred,\nAnd to obtain his guerdon strove with art,\nHim she would censure still, and ever more\nWas strengthened in the hate she nursed before.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"My wayward lover often I excite\nSo vain and bootless an emprize to quit;\nNor idly hope to turn her stedfast sprite,\nToo deeply with another passion smit;\nAnd make apparent to the Scottish knight,\nAriodantes such a flame had lit\nIn the young damsel's breast, that seas in flood\nWould not have cooled one whit her boiling blood.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"This Polinesso many times had heard\nFrom me (for such the Scottish baron's name)\nWell warranted by sight as well as word,\nHow ill his love was cherished by the dame.\nTo see another to himself preferred\nNot only quenched the haughty warrior's flame,\nBut the fond love, which in his bosom burned\nInto despiteful rage and hatred turned.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Between Geneura and her faithful knight\nSuch discord and ill will he schemed to shed,\nAnd put betwixt the pair such foul despite.\nNo time should heal the quarrel he had bred;\nBringing such scandal on that damsel bright,\nThe stain should cleave to her, alive or dead:\nNor, bent to wreck her on this fatal shelf,\nCounselled with me, or other but himself.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\" `Dalinda mine,' he said, his project brewed,\n(Dalinda is my name `you needs must know, ) \n\nThat from the root although the trunk be hewed,\nSuccessive suckers many times will grow.\nThus my unhappy passion is renewed,\nTenacious still of life, and buds; although\nCut off by ill success, with new increase:\nNor, till I compass my desire, will cease.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\" `Nor hope of pleasure this so much has wrought,\nAs that to compass my design would please;\nAnd, if not in effect, at least in thought\nTo thrive, would interpose some little ease.\nThen every time your bower by me is sought,\nWhen in her bed Geneura slumbers, seize\nWhat she puts off, and be it still your care\nTo dress yourself in all her daily wear.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\" `Dispose your locks and deck yourself as she\nGoes decked; and, as you can, with cunning heed,\nImitate her; then to the gallery\nYou, furnished with the corded stair, shall speed:\nI shall ascend it in the phantasy\nThat you are she, of whom you wear the weed:\nAnd hope, that putting on myself this cheat,\nI in short time shall quench my amorous heat.'</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"So said the knight; and I, who was distraught,\nAnd all beside myself, was not aware\nThat the design, in which he help besought,\nWas manifestly but too foul a snare;\nAnd in Geneura's clothes disguised, as taught,\nLet down (so oft I used the corded stair. ) \n\nNor I the traitor's foul deceit perceived,\nUntil the deadly mischief was achieved.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"The duke, this while, to Ariodantes' ears\nHad these, or other words like these, addressed;\n(For leagued in friendship were the cavaliers,\nTill, rivals, they pursued this common quest)\n\"I marvel, since you are of all my peers\nHe, whom I must have honoured and caressed,\nAnd held in high regard, and cherished still,\nYou should my benefits repay so ill.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\" `I am assured you comprehend and know\nMine and Geneura's love, and old accord;\nAnd, in legitimate espousal, how\nI am about to claim her from my lord:\nThen why disturb my suit, and why bestow\nYour heart on her who offers no reward?\nBy Heaven, I should respect your claim and place,\nWere your condition mine, and mine your case.'</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\" `And I,' cried Ariodantes, `marvel more'\n(In answer to the Scottish lord `at you, ) \n\nSince I of her enamoured was, before\nThat gentle damsel ever met your view;\nAnd know, you are assured how evermore\nWe two have loved; — was never love more true —\nAre certain she alone would share my lot;\nAnd are as well assured she loves you not.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\" `Why have not I from you the same respect,\nTo which, for friendship past, you would pretend\nFrom me; and I should bear you in effect,\nIf your hope stood more fair to gain its end?\nNo less than you, to wed her I expect;\nAnd if your fortunes here my wealth transcend,\nAs favoured of the king, as you, above\nYou, am I happy in his daughter's love.'</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\" `Of what a strange mistake,' (to him replied\nThe duke `your foolish passion is the root! ) \n\nYou think yourself beloved; I, on my side,\nBelieve the same; this try we by the fruit.\nYou of your own proceeding nothing hide,\nAnd I will tell the secrets of my suit:\nAnd let the man who proves least favoured, yield,\nProvide himself elsewhere, and quit the field.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\" `I am prepared, if such your wish, to swear\nNothing of what is told me to reveal;\nAnd will that you assure me, for your share,\nYou shall what I recount as well conceal.'\nUniting in the pact, the rival pair\nTheir solemn vows upon the Bible seal:\nAnd when they had the mutual promise plighted,\nAriodantes first his tale recited.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Then plainly, and by simple facts averred,\nHow with Geneura stood his suit, avows;\nAnd how, engaged by writing and by word,\nShe swore she would not be another's spouse.\nHow, if to him the Scottish king demurred,\nVirgin austerity she ever vows;\nAnd other bridal bond for aye eschewed,\nTo pass her days in barren solitude.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Then added, how he hoped by worth, which he\nHad more than once avouched, with knightly brand,\nAnd yet might vouch, to the prosperity\nAnd honour of the king, and of his land,\nTo please so well that monarch, as to be\nBy him accounted worthy of the hand\nOf his fair child, espoused with his consent:\nSince he in this her wishes would content.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Then so concludes — `I stand upon this ground,\nNor I intruder fear, encroaching nigh;\nNor seek I more; 'tis here my hopes I bound;\nNor, striving for Geneura's love, would I\nSeek surer sign of it than what is found,\nBy God allowed, in wedlock's lawful tie;\nAnd other suit were hopeless, am I sure,\nSo excellent she is, and passing pure.'</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"When Ariodantes had, with honest mind,\nTold what reward he hoped should quit his pain,\nFalse Polinesso, who before designed\nTo make Geneura hateful to her swain,\nBegan — `Alas!  you yet are far behind\nMy hopes, and shall confess your own are vain;\nAnd say, as I the root shall manifest\nOf my good fortune, I alone am blest.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\" `With you Geneura feigns, nor pays nor prizes\nYour passion, which with hopes and words is fed;\nAnd, more than this, your foolish love despises:\nAnd this to me the damsel oft has said,\nOf hers I am assured; of no surmises,\nVain, worthless words, or idle promise bred.\nAnd I to you the fact in trust reveal,\nThough this I should in better faith conceal.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\" `There passes not a month, but in that space\nThree nights, four, six, and often ten, the fair\nReceives me with that joy in her embrace,\nWhich seems to second so the warmth we share.\nThis you may witness, and shall judge the case;\nIf empty hopes can with my bliss compare.\nThen since my happier fortune is above\nYour wishes, yield, and seek another love.'</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\" `This will I not believe,' in answer cried\nAriodantes, `well assured you lie,\nAnd that you have this string of falsehoods tied,\nTo scare me from the dear emprize I try.\nBut charge, so passing foul, you shall abide,\nAnd vouch what you have said in arms; for I\nNot only on your tale place no reliance;\nBut as a traitor hurl you my defiance.'</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XL</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"To him rejoined the duke, 'I ween 'twere ill\nTo take the battle upon either part,\nSince surer mean our purpose may fulfill;\nAnd if it please, my proof I can impart.'\nAriodantes trembled, and a chill\nWent through his inmost bones; and sick at heart,\nHad he in full believed his rival's boast,\nWould on the spot have yielded up the ghost.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"With wounded heart, and faltering voice, pale face,\nAnd mouth of gall, he answered, 'When I see\nProofs of thy rare adventure, and the grace\nWith which the fair Geneura honours thee,\nI promise to forego the fruitless chase\nOf one, to thee so kind, so cold to me.\nBut think not that thy story shall avail,\nUnless my very eyes confirm the tale.'</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\" `To warn in due time shall be my care.'\n(Said Polinesso and so went his way. ) \n\nTwo nights were scarecly passed, ere his repair\nTo the known bower was fixed for the assay.\nAnd, ready now to spring his secret snare,\nHe sought his rival on the appointed day,\nAnd him to hide, the night ensuing, prayed\nI' the street, which none their habitation made.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"And to the youth a station over-right\nThe balcony, to which he clambered, shows.\nAriodantes weened, this while, the knight\nWould him to seek that hidden place dispose,\nAs one well suited to his fell despite,\nAnd, bent to take his life, this ambush chose,\nUnder the false pretence to make him see\nWhat seemed a sheer impossibility.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"To go the peer resolved, but in such guise,\nHe should not be with vantage overlaid;\nAnd should he be assaulted by surprise,\nHe need not be by fear of death dismay'd.\nHe had a noble brother, bold and wise,\nFirst of the court in arms; and on his aid,\nLurcanio hight, relied with better heart\nThan if ten others fought upon his part.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"He called him to his side, and willed him take\nHis arms; and to the place at evening led:\nYet not his secret purpose would be break;\nNor this to him, or other would have read:\nHim a stone's throw removed he placed, and spake:\n` — Come if thou hearest he cry,' the warrior said;\n`But as thou lovest me (whatsoe'er befall)\nCome not and move not, brother, till I call.'</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\" `Doubt not' (the valiant brother said `but go'; ) \n\nAnd thither went that baron silently,\nAnd hid within the lonely house, and low,\nOver against my secret gallery.\nOn the other side approached the fraudful foe,\nSo pleased to work Geneura's infamy;\nAnd, while I nothing of the cheat divine,\nBeneath my bower renews the wonted sign.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"And I in costly robe, in which were set\nFair stripes of gold upon a snowy ground,\nMy tresses gathered in a golden net,\nShaded with tassels of vermillion round,\nMimicking fashions, which were only met\nIn fair Geneura, at the accustomed sound,\nThe gallery mount, constructed in such mode,\nAs upon every side my person showed.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"This while Lurcanio, either with a view\nTo snares which might beset his brother's feet,\nOr with the common passion to pursue,\nAnd play the spy on other, where the street\nWas darkest, and its deepest shadows threw,\nFollowed him softly to his dim retreat:\nAnd not ten paces from the knight aloof,\nBestowed himself beneath the self same roof.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Suspecting nought, I seek the balcony,\nIn the same habits which I mentioned, dressed;\nAs more than once or twice (still happily)\nI did before; meanwhile the goodly vest\nWas in the moonlight clearly seen, and I,\nIn aspect not unlike her, in the rest\nResembling much Geneura's shape and cheer,\nOne visage well another might appear.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>L</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"So much the more, that there was ample space\nBetween the palace and the ruined row:\nHence the two brothers, posted in that place,\nWere lightly cheated by the lying show.\nNow put yourself in his unhappy case,\nAnd figure what the wretched lover's woe,\nWhen Polinesso climbed the stair, which I\nCast down to him, and scaled the gallery.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Arrived, my arms about his neck I throw,\nWeening that we unseen of others meet,\nAnd kiss his lips and face with loving show,\nAs him I hitherto was wont to greet;\nAnd he assayed, with more than wonted glow,\nMe to caress, to mask his hollow cheat.\nLed to the shameful spectacle, aghast,\nThat other, from afar, viewed all that passed,</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"And fell into such fit of deep despair,\nHe there resolved to die; and, to that end,\nPlanted the pommel of his falchion bare\nI' the ground, its point against his breast to bend.\nLurcanio, who with marvel by that stair,\nSaw Polinesso to my bower ascend,\nBut knew not who the wight, with ready speed\nSprang forward, when he saw his brother's deed.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"And hindered him in that fell agony\nFrom turning his own hand against his breast.\nHad the good youth been later, or less nigh,\nTo his assistance he had vainly pressed.\nThen, `Wretched brother, what insanity.'\n(He cried `your better sense has dispossessed? ) \n\nDie for a woman!  rather let her kind\nBe scattered like the mist before the wind!</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\" `Compass her death!  'tis well deserved; your own\nReserve, as due to more illustrious fate.\n'Twas well to love, before her fraud was shown,\nBut she, once loved, now more deserves your hate:\nSince, witnessed by your eyes, to you is known\nA wanton of what sort you worshipped late.\nHer fault before the Scottish king to attest,\nReserve those arms you turn against your breast.'</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Ariodantes, so surprised, forewent,\nJoined by his brother, the design in show;\nBut resolute to die, in his intent\nWas little shaken: Rising thence to go,\nHe bears away a heart not simply rent,\nBut dead and withered with excess of woe:\nYet better comfort to Lurcanio feigns,\nAs if the rage were spent which fired his veins.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"The morn ensuing, without further say\nTo his good brother, or to man beside,\nHe from the city took his reckless way\nWith deadly desperation for his guide;\nNor, save the duke and knight, for many a day\nWas there who knew what moved the youth to ride:\nAnd in the palace, touching this event,\nAnd in the realm, was various sentiment.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"But eight days past or more, to Scotland's court\nA traveller came, and to Geneura he\nRelated tidings of disastrous sort;\nThat Ariodantes perished in the sea:\nDrowned of his own free will was the report,\nNo wind to blame for the calamity!\nSince from a rock, which over ocean hung,\nInto the raging waves he headlong sprung;</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\" `Who said, before he reached that frowning crest,\nTo me, whom he encountered by the way,\nCome with me, that your tongue may manifest,\nAnd what betides me to Geneura say;\nAnd tell her, too, the occasion of the rest,\nWhich you shall witness without more delay;\nIn having seen too much, the occasion lies;\nHappy had I been born without these eyes!\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\" `By chance, upon a promontory we\nWere standing, overright the Irish shore;\nWhen, speaking thus on that high headland, he\nPlunged from a rock amid the watery roar.\nI saw him leap, and left him in the sea;\nAnd, hurrying thence, to you the tidings bore.'\nGeneura stood amazed, her colour fled,\nAnd, at the fearful tale, remained half dead.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"O God!  what said, what did she, when alone,\nShe on her faithful pillow layed her head!\nShe beat her bosom, and she tore her gown,\nAnd in despite her golden tresses shed;\nRepeating often, in bewildered tone,\nThe last sad words which Ariodantes said; —\nThat the sole source of such despair, and such\nDisaster, was that he had seen too much.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Wide was the rumour scattered that the peer\nHad slain himself for grief; nor was the cry\nBy courtly dame, or courtly cavalier,\nOr by the monarch, heard with tearless eye.\nBut, above all the rest, his brother dear\nWas whelmed with sorrow of so deep a dye,\nThat, bent to follow him, he well nigh turned\nHis hand against himself, like him he mourned.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"And many times repeating in his thought,\nIt was Geneura who his brother slew,\nWho was to self-destruction moved by nought\nBut her ill deed, which he was doomed to view,\nSo on his mind the thirst of vengeance wrought,\nAnd so his grief his season overthrew;\nThat he thought little, graced of each estate,\nTo encounter king and people's common hate;</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"And, when the throng was fullest in the hall,\nStood up before the Scottish king, and said,\n`Of having marred my brother's wits withal,\nSir king, and him to his destruction led,\nYour daughter only can I guilty call:\nFor in his inmost soul such sorrow bred\nThe having seen her little chastity,\nHe loathed existence, and preferred to die.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\" `He was her lover; and for his intent\nWas honest, this I seek not, I, to veil;\nAnd to deserve her by his valour meant\nOf thee, if faithful service might avail;\nBut while he stood aloof, and dared but scent\nThe blossoms, he beheld another scale,\nScale the forbidden tree with happier boot,\nAnd bear away from him the wished-for fruit.'</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Then added, how into the gallery came\nGeneura, and how dropped the corded stair;\nAnd how into the chamber of the dame\nHad climbed a leman of that lady fair;\nWho, for disguise (he knew not hence his name),\nHad changed his habits, and concealed his hair;\nAnd, in conclusion, vowed that every word\nSo said, he would avouch with lance and sword.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"You may divine how grieves the sire, distraught\nWith woe, when he the accusation hears:\nAs well that what he never could have thought,\nHe of his daughter learns with wondering ears,\nAs that he knows, if succour be not brought\nBy cavalier, that in her cause appears,\nWho may upon Lurcanio prove the lie,\nHe cannot choose, but doom the maid to die.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"I do not think our Scottish law to you\nIs yet unknown, which sentences to fire\nThe miserable dame, or damsel, who\nGrants other than her wedded lord's desire.\nShe dies, unless a champion, good and true,\nArm on her side before a month expire;\nAnd her against the accuser base maintain\nUnmeriting such death, and free from stain.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"The king has made proclaim by town and tower,\n(For he believes her wronged, his child to free)\nHer he shall have to wife, with ample dower,\nWho saves the royal maid from infamy.\nBut each to the other looks, and to this hour\nNo champion yet, 'tis said, appears: for he,\nLurcanio, is esteemed so fierce in fight,\nIt seems as he were feared of every knight.\n\n\"And evil Fate has willed her brother dear,\nZerbino, is not here the foe to face;\nSince many months has roved the cavalier,\nProving his matchless worth with spear and mace;\nFor if the valiant champion were more near,\n(Such is his courage or in any place, ) \n\nWhither in time the news might be conveyed,\nHe would not fail to bear his sister aid.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"The king, mean time, who would the quest pursue,\nAnd by more certain proof than combat, try\nIf the accuser's tale be false or true,\nAnd she deserve, or merit not, to die,\nArrests some ladies of her retinue,\nThat, as he weens, the fact can verify.\nWhence I foresaw, that if I taken were,\nToo certain risque the duke and I must share.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"That very night I from the palace flee,\nAnd to the duke repair, escaped from court;\nAnd, were I taken, make him plainly see\nHow much it either's safety would import:\nHe praised, and bade me of good courage be,\nAnd, for his comfort, prayed me to resort\nTo a strong castle which he held hard by;\nAnd gave me two to bear me company.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"With what full proofs, sir stranger, you have heard,\nI of my love assured the Scottish peer;\nAnd clearly can discern, if so preferred,\nThat lord was justly bound to hold me dear.\nMark, in conclusion, what was my reward;\nThe glorious meed of my great merit hear!\nAnd say if woman can expect to earn,\nHowever well she love, her love's return.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"For this perfidious, foul, ungrateful man,\nAt length suspicious of my faith and zeal,\nAnd apprehending that his wily plan,\nIn course of time, I haply might reveal,\nFeigned that meanwhile the monarch's anger ran\nToo high, he would withdraw me, and conceal\nWithin a fortress of his own, where I\n(Such was his real end was doomed to die. ) \n</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"For secretly the duke enjoined the guide,\nWho with me through the gloomy forest went,\nThe worthy guerdon of a faith so tried,\nTo slay me; and had compassed his intent,\nBut for your ready succour, when I cried.\nBehold!  what wages love's poor slaves content.\"\nThus to Rinaldo did Dalinda say,\nAs they together still pursued their way.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Above all other fortune, to the knight\nWas welcome to have found the gentle maid,\nWho the whole story of Geneura bright,\nAnd her unblemished innocence displayed;\nAnd, if he hoped, although accused with right,\nTo furnish the afflicted damsel aid,\nPersuaded of the calumny's disproof,\nHe with more courage warred in her behoof.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And for St. Andrew's town, with eager speed,\nWhere was the king with all his family,\nAnd where the single fight, in listed mead,\nUpon his daughter's quarrel, was to be,\nThe good Rinaldo pricked, nor spared his steed,\nUntil, within an easy distance, he\nNow near the city, met a squire who brought\nMore recent tidings than the damsel taught:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>That thither had repaired a stranger knight,\nTo combat in Geneura's quarrel bent,\nWith ensigns strange, not known of living wight,\nSince ever close concealed the warrior went;\nNot, since he had been there, had bared to sight\nHis visage, aye within his helmet pent:\nAnd that the very squire who with him came,\nSwore that he knew not what the stranger's name.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Not far they ride before the walls appear,\nAnd now before the gate their coursers stand.\nTo advance the sad Dalinda was in fear,\nYet followed, trusting in Rinaldo's brand.\nThe gate was shut, and to the porter near,\nWhat this implies Rinaldo makes demand:\nTo him was said, the people, one and all,\nWere trooped to see a fight without the wall:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Beyond the city, fought upon accord,\nBetween Lurcanio and a stranger knight;\nWhere, on a spacious meadow's level sward,\nThe pair already had begun the fight.\nThe porter opened to Mount Alban's lord,\nAnd straight behind the peer the portal hight.\nRinaldo through the empty city rode,\nBut in a hostel first the dame bestowed:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And will that she (he will not long delay\nTo seek her there till his return repose; ) \n\nAnd quickly to the lists pursued his way,\nWhere the two made that fell exchange of blows,\nAnd strove and struggled yet in bloody fray.\nLurcanio's heart with vengeful hatred glows\nAgainst Geneura; while that other knight\nAs well maintains the quarrel for her right.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Six knights on foot within the palisade\nStand covered with the corslet's iron case;\nBeneath the Duke of Albany arrayed,\nBorne on a puissant steed of noble race:\nWho there, as lord high-constable obeyed,\nWas keeper of the field and of the place,\nAnd joyed Geneura's peril to espy\nWith swelling bosom and exulting eye.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Rinaldo pierces through the parted swarm,\n(So wide is felt the good Bayardo's sway,)\nAnd he who hears the courser come in storm,\nHalts not, in his desire to make him way:\nAbove is seen Rinaldo's lofty form,\nThe flower of those who mix in martial fray.\nHe stops his horse before the monarch's chair,\nWhile all to hear the paladin repair.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Dread sir,\" to him the good Rinaldo said,\n\"Let not the pair this combat longer ply;\nSince whichsoever of the two falls dead,\nKnow, that you let him perish wrongfully:\nThis thinks that he is right, and is misled,\nVouches the false, and knows not 'tis a lie:\nSince that which brought his brother to his end,\nMoves him in causeless battle contend.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"That, in pure gentleness, with little care\nIf what he here maintains be wrong or right,\nBecause he would preserve a maid so fair,\nPerils his person in the furious fight.\nTo injured innocence I safety bear,\nAnd to the evil man its opposite.\nBut first, for love of God, the battle stay;\nThen list, sir king, to what I shall display.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>So moved the king the grave authority\nOf one who seemed so worthy, by his cheer,\nThat he made sign the battle should not be\nFurther continued then with sword or spear:\nTo whom, together with his chivalry,\nAnd barons of the realm and others near\nRinaldo all the treacherous plot displayed,\nWhich Polinesso for Geneura layed.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Next that he there in arms would testify\nThe truth of what he vouched, the warrior cried.\nFalse Polinesso, called, with troubled eye,\nStood forth, but daringly the tale denied.\nTo him the good Rinaldo in reply;\n\"By deeds be now the doubtful quarrel tried.\"\nThe field was cleared, and, ready armed, the foes,\nWithout more let, in deadly duel close.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>How was the hope to king and people dear,\nThe proof might show Geneura innocent!\nAll trust that God will make the treason clear,\nAnd show she was accused with foul intent:\nFor Polinesso, greedy and severe,\nAnd proud was held, and false and fraudulent.\nSo that none there, of all assembled, deemed\nIt marvel, if the knight such fraud had schemed.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>False Polinesso, with a mien distressed,\nA pallid cheek, and heart which thickly beat,\nAt the third trumpet, laid his lance in rest;\nAs well Rinaldo spurred the knight to meet,\nAnd levelled at his evil foeman's breast,\nEager to finish at a single heat.\nNor counter to his wish was the event;\nSince through the warrior half his weapon went.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Him, through his breast, impaled upon the spear,\nMore than six yards beyond his horse he bore.\nWith speed alighted Mount Albano's peer,\nAnd, ere he rose, unlaced the helm he wore:\nBut he for mercy prayed with humble cheer,\nUnfit to strive in joust or warfare more:\nAnd, before king and court, with faltering breath,\nConfessed the fraud which brought him to his death.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XC</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>He brings not his confession to a close,\nAnd pangs of death the failing accents drown:\nThe prince, who ended saw his daughter's woes,\nRedeemed from death and scorn, her virtue shown,\nWith more delight and rapture overflows,\nThan if he, having lost his kingly crown,\nThen saw it first upon his head replaced;\nSo that he good Rinaldo singly graced.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XCI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And when, through his uplifted casque displaid,\nFeatures, well known before, the king descried,\nHis thanks to God with lifted hands he paid,\nThat he had deigned such succour to provide.\nThat other cavalier, who bared his blade,\nUnknown of all, upon Geneura's side,\nAnd thither came from far, his aid to impart,\nLooked upon all that passed, and stood apart.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XCII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Him the good king entreated to declare\nHis name, or, at the least, his visage shew;\nThat he might grace him with such guerdon fair,\nAs to his good intent was justly due.\nThe stranger, after long and earnest prayer,\nLifted to covering casque, and bared to view</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>Canto will appear, If you are fain the history to hear.</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 6"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Ariodantes has, a worthy meed,\nWith his loved bride, the fief of Albany.\nMeantime Rogero, on the flying steed,\nArrives in false Alcina's empery:\nThere from a myrtle-tree her every deed,\nA human myrtle hears, and treachery,\nAnd thence would go; but they who first withdrew\nHim from one strife, engage him in a new.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>I</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Wretched that evil man who lives in trust\nHis secret sin is safe in his possession!\nSince, if nought else, the air, the very dust\nIn which the crime is buried, makes confession,\nAnd oftentimes his guilt compels the unjust,\nThough sometime unarraigned in worldly session,\nTo be his own accuser, and bewray,\nSo God has willed, deeds hidden from the day.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>II</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The unhappy Polinesso hopes had nursed,\nWholly his secret treason to conceal.\nBy taking off Dalinda, who was versed\nIn this, and only could the fact reveal;\nAnd adding thus a second to his first\nOffence, but hurried on the dread appeal,\nWhich haply he had stunned, at least deferred;\nBut he to self-destruction blindly spurred.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>III</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And forfeited estate, and life, and love\nOf friends at once, and honour, which was more.\nThe cavalier unknown, I said above,\nLong of the king and court entreated sore,\nAt length the covering helmet did remove,\nAnd showed a visage often seen before,\nThe cherished face of Ariodantes true,\nOf late lamented weeping Scotland through;</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>IV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Ariodantes, whom with tearful eye\nHis brother and Geneura wept as dead,\nAnd king, and people, and nobility:\nSuch light his goodness and his valour shed.\nThe pilgrim therefore might appear to lie\nIn what he of the missing warrior said.\nYet was it true that from a headland, he\nHad seen him plunge into the foaming sea.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>V</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>But, as it oft befalls despairing wight,\nWho grisly Death desires till he appear;\nBut loathes what he had sought, on nearer sight;\nSo painful seems the cruel pass and drear.\nThus, in the sea engulphed, the wretched knight,\nRepentant of his deed, was touched with fear;\nAnd, matchless both for spirit and for hand,\nBeat back the billows, and returned to land.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>VI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And, now despising, as of folly bred,\nThe fond desire which did to death impell,\nThence, soaked and dripping wet, his way did tread,\nAnd halted at a hermit's humble cell:\nAnd housed within the holy father's shed,\nThere secretly awhile designed to dwell;\nTill to his ears by rumour should be voiced,\nIf his Geneura sorrowed or rejoiced.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>VII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>At first he heard that, through excess of woe,\nThe miserable damsel well-nigh died:\nFor so abroad the doleful tidings go,\n'Twas talked of in the island, far and wide:\nFar other proof than that deceitful show,\nWhich to his cruel grief he thought he spied!\nAnd next against the fair Geneura heard\nLurcanio to her sire his charge preferred:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>VIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Nor for his brother felt less enmity\nThan was the love he lately bore the maid;\nFor he too foul, and full of cruelty,\nEsteemed the deed, although for him essayed;\nAnd, hearing after, in her jeopardy,\nThat none appeared to lend the damsel aid,\nBecause so puissant was Lurcanio's might,\nAll dreaded an encounter with the knight,</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>IX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And that who well the youthful champion knew,\nBelieved he was so wary and discreet,\nThat, had what he related been untrue,\nHe never would have risqued so rash a feat,\n— For this the greater part the fight eschew,\nFearing in wrongful cause the knight to meet —\nAriodantes (long his doubts are weighed)\nWill meet his brother in Geneura's aid.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>X</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Alas! (he said I cannot bear to see ) \n\nThus by my cause the royal damsel die;\nMy death too bitter and too dread would be,\nDid I, before my own, her death descry;\nFor still my lady, my divinity\nShe is; — the light and comfort of my eye.\nHer, right or wrong, I cannot choose but shield,\nAnd for her safety perish in the field.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"I know I choose the wrong, and be it so!\nAnd in the cause shall die: nor this would move;\nBut that, alas!  my death, as well I know,\nWill such a lovely dame's destruction prove,\nTo death I with one only comfort go,\nThat, if her Polinesso bears her love,\nTo her will manifestly be displayed,\nThat hitherto he moves not in her aid.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"And me, so wronged by her, the maid shall view\nEncounter death in her defence; and he,\nMy brother, who such flames of discord blew,\nShall pay the debt of vengeance due to me.\nFor well I ween to make Lurcanio rue\n(Informed of the event his cruelty, ) \n\nWho will have thought to venge me with his brand,\nAnd will have slain me with his very hand.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>He, having this concluded in his thought,\nMade new provision of arms, steed, and shield;\nBlack was the vest and buckler which he bought,\nWhere green and yellow striped the sable field:\nBy hazard found, with him a squire he brought,\nA stranger in that country; and, concealed\n(As is already told the unhappy knight, ) \n\nAgainst his brother came, prepared for fight.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And yielding to his natural inclination,\nAnd at the suit of all his court beside,\nAnd mostly at Rinaldo's instigation,\nAssigned the youth the damsel as his bride.\nAlbany's duchy, now in sequestration,\nLate Polinesso's, who in duel died,\nCould not be forfeited in happier hour;\nSince this the monarch made his daughter's dower.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Rinaldo for Dalinda mercy won;\nWho from her fault's due punishment went free.\nShe, satiate of the world, (and this to shun,\nThe damsel so had vowed to God will flee: ) \n\nAnd hence, in Denmark's land, to live a nun,\nStraight from her native Scotland sailed the sea.\nBut it is time Rogero to pursue,\nWho on his courser posts the welkin through.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Although Rogero is of constant mind,\nNot from his cheek the wonted hues depart.\nI ween that faster than a leaf i' the wind\nFluttered within his breast the stripling's heart.\nAll Europe's region he had left behind\nIn his swift course; and, issuing in that part,\nPassed by a mighty space, the southern sound\nWhere great Alcides fixed the sailor's bound.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>That hippogryph, huge fowl, and strange to sight,\nBears off the warrior with such rapid wing,\nHe would have distanced, in his airy flight,\nThe thunder bearing bird of Aether's king:\nNor other living creature soars such height,\nHim in his mighty swiftness equalling.\nI scarce believe that bolt, or lightning flies,\nOr darts more swiftly from the parted skies.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>When the huge bird his pinions long had plied,\nIn a straight line, without one stoop or bend,\nHe, tired of air, with sweeping wheel and wide,\nBegan upon an island to descend;\nLike that fair region, whither, long unspied\nOf him, her wayward mood did long offend,\nWhilom in vain, through strange and secret sluice,\nPassed under sea the Virgin Arethuse.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>A more delightful place, wherever hurled\nThrough the whole air, Rogero had not found:\nAnd, had he ranged the universal world,\nWould not have seen a lovelier in his round,\nThan that, where, wheeling wide, the courser furled\nHis spreading wings, and lighted on the ground,\n'Mid cultivated plain, delicious hill,\nMoist meadow, shady bank, and crystal rill.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Small thickets, with the scented laurel gay,\nCedar, and orange, full of fruit and flower,\nMyrtle and palm, with interwoven spray,\nPleached in mixed modes, all lovely, form a bower;\nAnd, breaking with their shade the scorching ray,\nMake a cool shelter from the noontide hour.\nAnd nightingales among those branches wing\nTheir flight, and safely amorous descants sing.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Amid red roses and white lilies there,\nWhich the soft breezes freshen as they fly,\nSecure the cony haunts, and timid hare,\nAnd stag, with branching forehead broad and high.\nThese, fearless of the hunter's dart or snare,\nFeed at their ease, or ruminating lie:\nWhile, swarming in those wilds, from tuft or steep\nDun deer or nimble goat, disporting, leap.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>When the hyppogryph above the island hung,\nAnd had approached so nigh that landscape fair,\nThat, if his rider from the saddle sprung,\nHe might the leap with little danger dare,\nRogero lit the grass and flowers among,\nBut held him, lest he should remount the air:\nAnd to a myrtle, nigh the rolling brine,\nMade fast, between a bay-tree and a pine.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And there, close-by where rose a bubbling fount,\nBegirt the fertile palm and cedar-tree,\nHe drops the shield, the helmet from his front\nUplifts, and, either hand from gauntlet free,\nNow turning to the beach, and now the mount,\nCatches the gales which blow from hill or sea,\nAnd, with a joyous murmur, lightly stir\nThe lofty top of beech, or feathery fir:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And, now, to bathe his burning lips he strains;\nNow dabbles in the crystal wave, to chase\nThe scorching heat which rages in his veins,\nCaught from the heavy corslet's burning case.\nNor is it marvel if the burden pains;\nNo ramble his in square or market-place!\nThree thousand miles, without repose, he went,\nAnd still, at speed, in ponderous armour pent.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Meanwhile the courser by the myrtle's side,\nWhom he left stabled in the cool retreat,\nStarted at something in the wood descried,\nScared by I know not what; and in his heat\nSo made the myrtle shake where he was tied,\nHe brought a shower of leaves about his feet;\nHe made the myrtle shake and foliage fall,\nBut, struggling, could not loose himself withal.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>As in a stick to feed the chimney rent,\nWhere scanty pith ill fills the narrow sheath,\nThe vapour, in its little channel pent,\nStruggles, tormented by the fire beneath;\nAnd, till its prisoned fury find a vent,\nIs heard to hiss and bubble, sing and seethe:\nSo the offended myrtle inly pined,\nGroaned, murmured, and at last unclosed its rind:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And hence a clear, intelligible speech\nThus issued, with a melancholy sound;\n\"If, as thy cheer and gentle presence teach,\nThou courteous art and good, his reign unbound,\nRelease me from this monster, I beseech:\nGriefs of my own inflict sufficient wound:\nNor need I, compassed with such ills about,\nOther new pain to plague me from without.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>At the first sound, Rogero turns to see\nWhence came the voice, and, in unused surprise,\nStands, when he finds it issues from the tree;\nAnd swiftly to remove the courser hies.\nThen, with a face suffused with crimson, he\nIn answer to the groaning myrtle, cries;\n\"Pardon! and, whatsoe'er thou art, be good,\nSpirit of man, or goddess of the wood!</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Unweeting of the wonderous prodigy\nOf spirit, pent beneath the knotty rind,\nTo your fair leaf and living body I\nHave done this scathe and outrage undesigned.\nBut not the less for that, to me reply,\nWhat art thou, who, in rugged case confined,\nDost live and speak?  And so may never hail\nFrom angry heaven your gentle boughs assail!</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"And if I now or ever the despite\nI did thee can repair, or aid impart,\nI, by that lady dear, my promise plight,\nWho in her keeping has my better part,\nTo strive with word and deed, till thou requite\nThe service done with praise and grateful heart.\"\nRogero said; and, as he closed his suit,\nThat gentle myrtle shook from top to root.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Next drops were seen to stand upon the bark,\nAs juice is sweated by the sapling-spray,\nNew-severed, when it yields to flame and spark,\nSometime in vain kept back and held at bay.\nAnd next the voice began:  \"My story dark,\nForced by thy courteous deed, I shall display; —\nWhat once I was — by whom, through magic lore,\nChanged to a myrtle on the pleasant shore.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"A peer of France, Astolpho was my name,\nWhilom a paladin, sore feared in fight;\nCousin I was to two of boundless fame,\nOrlando and Rinaldo.  I by right\nLooked to all England's crown; my lawful claim\nAfter my royal father, Otho hight.\nMore dames than one my beauty served to warm,\nAnd in conclusion wrought my single harm.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Returning from those isles, whose eastern side\nThe billows of the Indian ocean beat,\nWhere good Rinaldo and more knights beside\nWith me were pent in dark and hollow seat,\nThence, rescued by illustrious Brava's pride,\nWhose prowess freed us from that dark retreat,\nWestward I fared along the sandy shores,\nOn which the stormy north his fury pours.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Pursuing thus our rugged journey, we\nCame (such our evil doom upon the strand, ) \n\nWhere stood a mansion seated by the sea:\nPuissant Alcina owned the house and land.\nWe found her, where, without her dwelling, she\nHad taken on the beach her lonely stand;\nAnd though nor hook nor sweeping net she bore,\nWhat fish she willed, at pleasure drew to shore.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Thither swift dolphins gambol, inly stirred,\nAnd open-mouthed the cumbrous tunnies leap;\nThither the seal or porpus' wallowing herd\nTroop at her bidding, roused from lazy sleep;\nRaven-fish, salmon, salpouth, at her word,\nAnd mullet hurry through the briny deep,\nWith monstrous backs above the water, sail\nOrk, physeter, sea-serpent, shark, and whale.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"There we behold a mighty whale, of size\nThe hugest yet in any water seen:\nMore than eleven paces, to our eyes,\nHis back appears above the surface green:\nAnd (for still firm and motionless he lies,\nAnd such the distance his two ends between)\nWe all are cheated by the floating pile,\nAnd idly take the monster for an isle.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Alcina made the ready fish obey\nBy simple words and by mere magic lore:\nBorn with Morgana — but I cannot say\nIf at one birth, or after or before.\nAs soon as seen, my aspect pleased the fay;\nWho showed it in the countenance she wore:\nThen wrought with art, and compassed her intent,\nTo part me from the friends with whom I went.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"She came towards us with a cheerful face,\nWith graceful gestures, and a courteous air,\nAnd said:  'So you my lodging please to grace,\nSir cavalier, and will with me repair,\nYou shall behold the wonders of my chace,\nAnd note the different sorts of fish I snare;\nShaggy or smooth, or clad in scales of light,\nAnd more in number than the stars of night:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XL</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\" 'And would you hear a mermaid sing so sweet,\nThat the rude sea grows civil at her song,\nWont at this hour her music to repeat,\n(With that she showed the monster huge and long\n— I said it seemed an island — as her seat)\nPass with me where she sings the shoals among.'\nI, that was always wilful, at her wish,\nI now lament my rashness, climb the fish.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"To Dudon and Rinaldo's signal blind,\nI go, who warn me to misdoubt the fay.\nWith laughing face Alcina mounts behind,\nLeaving the other two beside the bay.\nThe obedient fish performs the task assigned,\nAnd through the yielding water works his way.\nRepentant of my deed, I curse the snare,\nToo far from land my folly to repair.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"To aid me swam Mount Alban's cavalier,\nAnd was nigh drowned amid the waves that rise;\nFor a south-wind sprang up that, far and near,\nCovered with sudden darkness seas and skies.\nI know not after what befel the peer:\nThis while Alcina to console me tries,\nAnd all that day, and night which followed, me\nDetained upon that monster in mid-sea,</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Till to this isle we drifted with the morn,\nOf which Alcina keeps a mighty share;\nBy that usurper from a sister torn,\nWho was her father's universal heir:\nFor that she only was in wedlock born,\nAnd for those other two false sisters were\n(So well-instructed in the story, said\nOne who rehearsed the tale in incest bred. ) \n</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"As these are practised in iniquity,\nAnd full of every vice and evil art;\nSo she, who ever lives in chastity,\nWisely on better things has set her heart.\nHence, leagued against her, in conspiracy,\nThose others are, to drive her from her part:\nAnd more than once their armies have o'errun\nHer realm, and towns above a hundred won.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Nor at this hour a single span of ground\nWould Logistilla (such her name command, ) \n\nBut that a mountain here, and there a sound,\nProtects the remnant from the invading band.\n'Tis thus the mountain and the river bound\nEngland, and part it from the Scottish land.\nYet will the sisters give their foe no rest,\nTill of her scanty remnant dispossest.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Because in wickedness and vice were bred\nThe pair, as chaste and good they loath the dame.\nBut, to return to what I lately said,\nAnd to relate how I a plant became;\nMe, full of love, the kind Alcina fed\nWith full delights; nor I a weaker flame\nFor her, within my burning heart did bear,\nBeholding her so courteous and so fair.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Clasped in her dainty limbs, and lapt in pleasure,\nI weened that I each separate good had won,\nWhich to mankind is dealt in different measure,\nLittle or more to some, and much to none.\nI evermore contemplated my treasure,\nNor France nor aught beside I thought upon:\nIn her my every fancy, every hope\nCentered and ended as their common scope.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"By her I was as much beloved, or more;\nNor did Alcina now for other care;\nShe left her every lover; for before,\nOthers, in truth, the fairy's love did share:\nI was her close adviser evermore;\nAnd served by her, where they commanded were.\nWith me she counselled, and to me referred;\nNor, night nor day, to other spake a word.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Why touch my wounds, to aggravate my ill,\nAnd that, alas!  without the hope of cure?\nWhy thus the good possessed remember still,\nAmid the cruel penance I endure?\nWhen kindest I believed Alcina's will,\nAnd fondly deemed my happiness secure,\nFrom me the heart she gave, the fay withdrew,\nAnd yielded all her soul to love more new.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>L</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Late I discerned her light and fickle bent,\nStill loving and unloving at a heat:\nTwo months, I reigned not more, no sooner spent,\nThan a new paramour assumed my seat;\nAnd me, with scorn, she doomed to banishment,\nFrom her fair grace cast out.  'Tis then I weet\nI share a thousand lovers' fate, whom she\nHad to like pass reduced, all wrongfully.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"And these, because they should not scatter bruits,\nRoaming the world, of her lascivious ways,\nShe, up and down the fruitful soil, transmutes\nTo olive, palm, or cedar, firs or bays.\nThese, as you see me changed, Alcina roots;\nWhile this transformed into a monster strays;\nAnother melts into a liquid rill;\nAs suits that haughty fairy's wanton will.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Thou, too, that to this fatal isle art led\nBy way unwonted and till now unknown,\nThat some possessor of the fairy's bed,\nMay be for thee transformed to wave or stone,\nThou shalt, with more than mortal pleasures fed,\nHave from Alcina seigniory and throne;\nBut shalt be sure to join the common flock,\nTransformed to beast or fountain, plant or rock.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"I willingly to thee this truth impart,\nNot that I hope with profit to advise:\nYet 'twill be better, that informed, in part,\nOf her false ways, she harm not by surprise.\nPerhaps, as faces differ, and in art\nAnd wit of man an equal difference lies,\nThou may'st some remedy perchance apply\nTo the ill, which thousand others could not fly.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The good Rogero, who from Fame had learned\nThat he was cousin to the dame he wooed,\nLamented much the sad Astolpho, turned\nFrom his true form, to barren plant and rude:\nAnd for her love, for whom so sore he burned,\nWould gladly serve the stripling if he cou'd:\nBut, witless how to give the wished relief,\nMight but console the unhappy warrior's grief.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>As best he could, he strove to soothe his pain;\nThen asked him, if to Logistil's retreat\nWere passage, whether over hill or plain;\nThat he might so eschew Alcina's seat.\n— `There was a way', the myrtle said again,\n— `But rough with stones, and rugged to the feet —\nIf he, some little further to the right,\nWould scale the Alpine mountain's very height:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>`But that he must not think he shall pursue\nThe intended journey far; since by the way\nHe will encounter with a frequent crew,\nAnd fierce, who serve as rampart to the fay,\nThat block the road against the stranger, who\nWould break her bounds, and the deserter stay.'\nRogero thanked the tree for all, and taught,\nDeparted thence with full instructions fraught.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The courser from the myrtle he untied,\nAnd by the bridle led behind him still;\nNor would he, as before, the horse bestride,\nLest he should bear him off against his will:\nHe mused this while how safely he might find\nA passage to the land of Logistil;\nFirm in his purpose every nerve to strain,\nLest empire over him Alcina gain.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>He to remount the steed, and through the air\nTo spur him to a new career again\nNow thought; but doubted next, in fear to fare\nWorse on the courser, restive to the rein.\n\"No, I will win by force the mountain stair,\"\nRogero said; (but the resolve was vain)\nNor by the beach two miles his way pursued,\nEre he Alcina's lovely city viewed.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>A lofty wall at distance meets his eye\nWhich girds a spacious town within its bound;\nIt seems as if its summit touched the sky,\nAnd all appears like gold from top to ground.\nHere some one says it is but alchemy\n— And haply his opinion is unsound —\nAnd haply he more wittily divines:\nFor me, I deem it gold because it shines.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>When he was nigh the city-walls, so bright,\nThe world has not their equal, he the straight\nAnd spacious way deserts, the way which dight\nAcross the plain, conducted to the gate;\nAnd by that safer road upon the right,\nStrains now against the mountain; but, in wait,\nEncounters soon the crowd of evil foes,\nWho furiously the Child's advance oppose.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Was never yet beheld a stranger band,\nOf mien more hideous, or more monstrous shape.\nFormed downwards from neck like men, he scanned\nSome with the head of cat, and some of ape;\nWith hoof of goat that other stamped the sand;\nWhile some seemed centaurs, quick in fight and rape;\nNaked, or mantled in outlandish skin.\nThese doting sires, those striplings bold in sin.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>This gallops on a horse without a bit;\nThis backs the sluggish ass, or bullock slow;\nThese mounted on the croup of centaur sit:\nThose perched on eagle, crane, or estridge, go.\nSome male, some female, some hermaphrodit,\nThese drain the cup and those the bungle blow.\nOne bore a corded ladder, one a book;\nOne a dull file, or bar of iron shook.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The captain of this crew, which blocked the road,\nAppeared, with monstrous paunch and bloated face;\nWho a slow tortoise for a horse bestrode,\nThat passing sluggishly with him did pace:\nDown looked, some here, some there, sustained the load,\nFor he was drunk, and kept him in his place.\nSome wipe his brows and chin from sweat which ran,\nAnd others with their vests his visage fan.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>One, with a human shape and feet, his crest,\nFashioned like hound, in neck and ears and head,\nBayed at the gallant Child with angry quest,\nTo turn him to the city whence he fled.\n\"That will I never, while of strength possessed\nTo brandish this,\" the good Rogero said:\nWith that his trenchant faulchion he displayed,\nAnd pointed at him full the naked blade.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>That monster would have smote him with a spear,\nBut swiftly at his foe Rogero sprung,\nThrust at his paunch, and drove his faulchion sheer\nThrough his pierced back a palm; his buckler flung\nBefore him, and next sallied there and here:\nBut all too numerous was the wicked throng.\nNow grappled from behind, now punched before,\nHe stands, and plies the crowd with warfare sore.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>One to the teeth, another to the breast,\nOf that foul race he cleft; since no one steeled\nIn mail, his brows with covering helmet dressed,\nOr fought, secured by corslet or by shield;\nYet is he so upon all quarters pressed,\nThat it would need the Child, to clear the field,\nAnd to keep off the wicked crew which swarms,\nMore than Briareus' hundred hands and arms.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>If he had thought the magic shield to show,\n(I speak of that the necromancer bore,\nWhich dazed the sight of the astonished foe,\nLeft at his saddle by the wizard Moor)\nThat hideous band, in sudden overthrow,\nBlinded by this, had sunk the knight before.\nBut haply he despised such mean as vile,\nAnd would prevail by valour, not by guile.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>This as it may: the Child would meet his fate,\nEre by so vile a band be prisoner led;\nWhen, lo!  forth issuing from the city's gate,\nWhose wall appeared like shining gold I said,\nTwo youthful dames, not born in low estate,\nIf measured by their mien and garb, nor bred\nBy swain, in early wants and troubles versed;\nBut amid princely joys in palace nursed!</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>On unicorn was seated either fair,\nA beast than spotless ermine yet more white;\nSo lovely were the damsels, and so rare\nTheir garb, and with such graceful fashion dight,\nThat he who closely viewed the youthful pair,\nWould need a surer sense than mortal sight,\nTo judge between the two.  With such a mien\nEmbodied Grace and Beauty would be seen.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Into the mead rode this and the other dame,\nWhere the foul crew opposed the Child's retreat.\nThe rabble scattered as the ladies came,\nWho with extended hand the warrior greet.\nHe, with a kindling visage, red with shame,\nThanked the two damsels for their gentle feat;\nAnd was content upon their will to wait,\nWith them returning to that golden gate.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Above, a cornice round the gateway goes,\nSomedeal projecting from the colonnade,\nIn which is not a single part but glows,\nWith rarest gems of India overlaid.\nPropp'd at four points, the portal did repose\nOn columns of one solid diamond made.\nWhether what met the eye was false or true,\nWas never sight more fair or glad to view.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Upon the sill and through the columns there,\nRan young and wanton girls, in frolic sport;\nWho haply yet would have appeared more fair,\nHad they observed a woman's fitting port.\nAll are arrayed in green, and garlands wear\nOf the fresh leaf.  Him these in courteous sort,\nWith many proffers and fair mien entice,\nAnd welcome to this opening Paradise:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>For so with reason I this place may call,\nWhere, it is my belief, that Love had birth;\nWhere life is spent in festive game and ball,\nAnd still the passing moments fleet in mirth.\nHere hoary-headed Thought ne'er comes at all,\nNor finds a place in any bosom.  Dearth,\nNor yet Discomfort, never enter here,\nWhere Plenty fills her horn throughout the year.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Here, where with jovial and unclouded brow,\nGlad April seems to wear a constant smile,\nTroop boys and damsels: One, whose fountains flow,\nOn the green margin sings in dulcet style;\nOthers, the hill or tufted tree below,\nIn dance, or no mean sport the hours beguile.\nWhile this, who shuns the revellers' noisy cheer,\nTells his love sorrows in his comrade's ear.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Above the laurel and pine-tree's height,\nThrough the tall beech and shaggy fir-tree's spray,\nSport little loves, with desultory flight:\nThese, at their conquests made, rejoiced and gay:\nThese, with the well-directed shaft, take sight\nAt hearts, and those spread nets to catch their prey;\nOne wets his arrows in the brook which winds,\nAnd one on whirling stone the weapon grinds.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>To good Rogero here was brought a steed,\nPuissant and nimble, all of sorel hue;\nWho was caparisoned with costly weed,\nBroidered with gold, and jewels bright to view.\nThat other winged horse, which, at his need,\nObedient to the Moorish wizard flew,\nThe friendly damsels to a youth consigned,\nWho led him at a slower pace behind.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>That kindly pair who, by the wicked band\nOffended fate, had saved the youthful knight;\nThe wicked crew, that did the Child withstand,\nWhen he the road had taken on his right,\nExclaimed, \"Fair sir, your works already scanned\nBy us, who are instructed of your might,\nEmbolden us, in our behalf, to pray\nYou will the prowess of your arm assay.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"We soon shall reach a bottom which divides\nThe plain into two parts: A cruel dame\nA bridge maintains, which there a stream bestrides,\nEriphila the savage beldam's name;\nWho cheats, and robs, and scathes, whoever rides\nTo the other shore, a giantess in frame;\nWho has long poisonous teeth her prey to tear,\nAnd scratches with her talons like a bear.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Besides that she infests the public way,\nWhich else were free; she often ranging through\nAll this fair garden, puts in disarray\nThis thing or that.  Of the assassin crew,\nThat people who without the portal gay,\nLately with brutal rage assaulted you,\nMany her sons, the whole her followers call,\nAs greedy and inhospitable all.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"For you not only her I would assail,\nBut do a hundred battles, well content:\nThen of my person, where it may avail,\nDispose (Rogero said to you intent. ) \n\nSilver and land to conquer, plate or mail\nI swear not, I, in warlike cuirass pent;\nBut to afford my aid to others due;\nAnd, most of all, to beauteous dames like you.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Their grateful thanks the ladies, worthily\nBestowed on such a valiant champion, paid:\nThey talking thus the bridge and river see,\nAnd at her post the haughty dame arraid\n(Sapphire and emerald decked the panoply)\nIn arms of gold: but I awhile delay\nTill other strain the issue of the fray.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 7"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Rogero, as directed by the pair,\nThe giantess Eriphila o'erthrows.\nThat done, he to Alcina's labyrinth, where\nMore than one knight is tied and prisoned, goes.\nTo him Melissa sage the secret snare,\nAnd remedy for that grave evil shows.\nWhence he, by her advised, with downcast eye,\nAnd full of shame forthwith resolves to fly.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>I</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The traveller, he, whom sea or mountain sunder\nFrom his own country, sees things strange and new;\nThat the misjudging vulgar, which lies under\nThe mist of ignorance, esteems untrue:\nRejecting whatsoever is a wonder,\nUnless 'tis palpable and plain to view:\nHence inexperience, as I know full well,\nWill yield small credence to the tale I tell.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>II</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>But this be great or small, I know not why\nThe rabble's silly judgement I should fear,\nConvinced you will not think the tale a lie,\nIn whom the light of reason shines so clear.\nAnd hence to you it is I only try\nThe fruit of my fatigues to render dear.\nI ended where Eriphila in guard\nOf bridge and stream was seen, the passage barred.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>III</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Of finest metal was her armour bright,\nWith gems of many colours overspread,\nThe tawny jacinth, yellow chyrsolite,\nThe emerald green of hue, and ruby red.\nMounted, but not on palfrey, for the fight:\nIn place of that, she on a wolf had sped,\nSped on a wolf towards the pass; and rode\nOn sell, that rich beyond all custom showed.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>IV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>No larger wolf, I ween, Apulia roams;\nMore huge than bull, unguided by her hand;\nAlthough upon no bit the monster foams,\nDocile, I know not why, to her command.\nThe accursed Plague, arrayed in surcoat, comes\nAbove her arms, in colour like the sand;\nThat, saving in its dye, was of the sort\nWhich bishops and which prelates wear at court.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>V</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The giantess's crest and shield appear,\nFor ensign, decked with swoln and poisonous toad.\nHer the two damsels to the cavalier\nBefore the bridge, prepared for battle, showed,\nThreatening, as wont to some, with levelled spear,\nTo do the warrior scorn and bar the road.\nBidding him turn, she to Rogero cries;\nA lance he takes, and threats her and defies.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>VI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>As quick and daring, the gigantic Pest\nSpurred her wolf, seated well for that dread game:\nIn mid career she laid her lance in rest,\nAnd made earth quake beneath her as she came;\nYet at the encounter fierce the champaign pressed;\nFor underneath the casque, with stedfast aim,\nSo hard Rogero smote her, that he bore\nThe beldam backward six good yards and more:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>VII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And came already with his lifted blade,\nDrawn for that end, to take her haughty head;\nTo him an easy task; for she was laid\nAmong the grass and flowers, like one that's dead.\nBut, \" 'Tis enough that she is vanquished,\" said\nThe pair, \"No further press thy vengeance dread.\nSheathe, courteous cavalier, thy sword anew:\nPass we the river, and our way pursue.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>VIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Along the path, which through a forest lay,\nRoughish and somedeal ill to beat, they went.\nBesides that strait and stony was the way,\nThis, nigh directly, scaled a hill's ascent.\nBut, when arrived upon the summit, they\nIssued upon a mead of vast extent;\nAnd a more pleasant palace on that green\nBeheld, and brighter than was ever seen.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>IX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>To meet the Child, Alcina, fair of hue,\nAdvanced some way beyond the outer gate;\nAnd, girded by a gay and courtly crew,\nRogero there received in lordly state:\nWhile all the rest to him such honour do,\nAnd on the knight with such deep reverence wait,\nThey could not have displayed more zeal and love,\nHad Jove descended from the choirs above.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>X</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Not so much does the palace, fair to see,\nIn riches other princely domes excel,\nAs that the gentlest, fairest, company\nWhich the whole world contains, within it dwell:\nOf either sex, with small variety\nBetween, in youth and beauty matched as well:\nThe fay alone exceeds the rest as far\nAs the bright sun outshines each lesser star.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Her shape is of such perfect symmetry,\nAs best to feign the industrious painter knows,\nWith long and knotted tresses; to the eye\nNot yellow gold with brighter lustre glows.\nUpon her tender cheek the mingled dye\nIs scattered, of the lily and the rose.\nLike ivory smooth, the forehead gay and round\nFills up the space, and forms a fitting bound.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Two black and slender arches rise above\nTwo clear black eyes, say suns of radiant light,\nWhich ever softly beam and slowly move;\nRound these appears to sport in frolic flight,\nHence scattering all his shafts, the little Love,\nAnd seems to plunder hearts in open sight.\nThence, through mid visage, does the nose descend,\nWhere Envy finds not blemish to amend.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>As if between two vales, which softly curl,\nThe mouth with vermeil tint is seen to glow:\nWithin are strung two rows of orient pearl,\nWhich her delicious lips shut up or show.\nOf force to melt the heart of any churl,\nHowever rude, hence courteous accents flow:\nAnd here that gentle smile receives its birth,\nWhich opes at will a paradise on earth.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Like milk the bosom, and the neck of snow;\nRound is the neck, and full and large the breast;\nWhere, fresh and firm, two ivory apples grow,\nWhich rise and fall, as, to the margin pressed\nBy pleasant breeze, the billows come and go.\nNot prying Argus could discern the rest.\nYet might the observing eye of things concealed\nConjecture safely, from the charms revealed.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>To all her arms a just proportion bear,\nAnd a white hand is oftentimes descried,\nWhich narrow is, and somedeal long; and where\nNo knot appears, nor vein is signified.\nFor finish of that stately shape and rare,\nA foot, neat, short, and round, beneath is spied.\nAngelic visions, creatures of the sky,\nConcealed beneath no covering veil can lie.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>A springe is planted in Rogero's way,\nOn all sides did she speak, smile, sing, or move;\nNo wonder then the stripling was her prey,\nWho in the fairy saw such show of love.\nWith him the guilt and falsehood little weigh,\nOf which the offended myrtle told above.\nNor will he think that perfidy and guile\nCan be united with so sweet a smile.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>No!  he could now believe, by magic art,\nAstolpho well transformed upon the plain,\nFor punishment of foul ungrateful heart,\nAnd haply meriting severer pain.\nAnd, as for all he heard him late impart,\n'Twas prompted by revenge, 'twas false and vain.\nBy hate and malice was the sufferer stung,\nTo blame and wound the fay with slanderous tongue.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The beauteous lady whom he loved so well\nIs newly banished from his altered breast;\nFor (such the magic of Alcina's spell)\nShe every ancient passion dispossessed;\nAnd in his bosom, there alone to dwell,\nThe image of her love, and self impressed.\nSo witched, Rogero sure some grace deserves,\nIf from his faith his frail affection swerves.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>At board lyre, lute and harp of tuneful string,\nAnd other sounds, in mixed diversity,\nMade, round about, the joyous palace ring,\nWith glorious concert and sweet harmony.\nNor lacked there well-accorded voice to sing\nOf love, its passion and its ecstasy;\nNor who, with rare inventions, choicely versed,\nDelightful fiction to the guests rehearsed.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>What table, spread by whatsoever heir\nOf Ninus, though triumphant were the board,\nOr what more famous and more costly, where\nCleopatra feasted with the Latian lord,\nCould with this banquet's matchless joys compare,\nBy the fond fairy for Rogero stored?\nI think not such a feast is spread above,\nWhere Ganymede presents the cup to Jove.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>They form a ring, the board and festive cheer\nRemoved, and sitting, play a merry game:\nEach asks, still whispering in a neighbour's ear,\nWhat secret pleases best; to knight and dame\nA fair occasion, without let or fear,\nTheir love, unheard of any, to proclaim.\nAnd in conclusion the two lovers plight\nTheir word, to meet together on that night.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Soon, and much sooner than their wont, was ended\nThe game at which the palace inmates play:\nWhen pages on the troop with torches tended,\nAnd with their radiance chased the night away.\nTo seek his bed the paladin ascended,\nGirt with that goodly squadron, in a gay\nAnd airy bower, appointed for his rest,\nMid all the others chosen as the best.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And when of comfits and of cordial wine\nA fitting proffer has been made anew,\nThe guests their bodies reverently incline,\nAnd to their bowers depart the courtly crew.\nHe upon perfumed sheets, whose texture fine\nSeemed of Arachne's loom, his body threw:\nHearkening this while with still attentive ears,\nIf he the coming of the lady hears.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>At every movement heard on distant floor,\nHoping 'twas her, Rogero raised his head:\nHe thinks he hears; but it is heard no more,\nThen sighs at his mistake: ofttimes from bed\nHe issued, and undid his chamber door,\nAnd peeped abroad, but still no better sped;\nAnd cursed a thousand times the hour that she\nSo long retarded his felicity.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Yes, now she comes,\" the stripling often said,\nAnd reckoned up the paces, as he lay,\nWhich from her bower where haply to be made\nTo that where he was waiting for the fay.\nThese thoughts, and other thoughts as vain, he weighed\nBefore she came, and restless at her stay,\nOften believed some hinderance, yet unscanned,\nMight interpose between the fruit and hand.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>At length, when dropping sweets the costly fay\nHad put some end to her perfumery,\nThe time now come she need no more delay,\nSince all was hushed within the palace, she\nStole from her bower alone, through secret way,\nAnd passed towards the chamber silently,\nWhere on his couch the youthful cavalier\nLay, with a heart long torn by Hope and Fear.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>When the successor of Astolpho spies\nThose smiling stars above him, at the sight\nA flame, like that of kindled sulphur, flies\nThrough his full veins, as ravished by delight\nOut of himself; and now up to the eyes\nPlunged in a sea of bliss, he swims outright.\nHe leaps from bed and folds her to his breast,\nNor waits until the lady he undressed;</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Though but in a light sendal clad, that she\nWore in the place of farthingale or gown;\nWhich o'er a shift of finest quality,\nAnd white, about her limbs the fay had thrown:\nThe mantle yielded at his touch, as he\nEmbraced her, and that veil remained alone,\nWhich upon every side the damsel shows,\nMore than clear glass the lily or the rose.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The plant no closer does the ivy clip,\nWith whose green boughs its stem is interlaced.\nThan those fond lovers, each from either's lip\nThe balmy breath collecting, he embraced:\nRich perfume this, whose like no seed or slip\nBears in sweet Indian or Sabacan waste;\nWhile so to speak their joys is either fixed,\nThat oftentimes those meeting lips are mixed.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>These things were carried closely by the dame\nAnd youth, or if surmised, were never bruited;\nFor silence seldom was a cause for blame,\nBut oftener as a virtue well reputed.\nBy those shrewd courtiers, conscious of his claim,\nRogero is with proffers fair saluted:\nWorshipped of all those inmates, who fulfil\nIn this the enamoured far, Alcina's will.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>No pleasure is omitted there; since they\nAlike are prisoners in Love's magic hall.\nThey change their raiment twice or thrice a day,\nNow for this use, and now at other call.\n'Tis often feast, and always holiday;\n'Tis wrestling, tourney, pageant, bath, and ball.\nNow underneath a hill by fountain cast,\nThey read the amorous lays of ages past:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Now by glad hill, or through the shady dale,\nThey hunt the fearful hare, and now they flush\nWith busy dog, sagacious of the trail,\nWild pheasant from the stubble-field or bush.\nNow where green junipers perfume the gale,\nSuspend the snare, or lime the fluttering thrush:\nAnd casting now for fish, with net or book,\nDisturb their secret haunts in pleasant brook.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Rogero revels there, in like delight,\nWhile Charles and Agramant are troubled sore.\nBut not for him their story will I slight,\nNor Bradamant forget: who evermore,\nMid toilsome pain and care, her cherished knight,\nRavished from her, did many a day deplore;\nWhom by unwonted ways, transported through\nMid air, the damsel saw, nor whither knew.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Of her I speak before the royal pair,\nWho many days pursued her search in vain;\nBy shadowy wood, or over champaign bare,\nBy farm and city, and by hill and plain;\nBut seeks her cherished friend with fruitless care,\nDivided by such space of land and main:\nOften she goes among the Paynim spears,\nYet never aught of her Rogero hears.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Of hundreds questioned, upon every side,\nEach day, no answer ever gives content.\nShe roams from post to post, and far and wide\nSearches pavilion, lodging, booth, or rent,\nAnd this, mid foot or horsemen, unespied,\nMay safely do, without impediment,\nThanks to the ring, whose more than mortal aid,\nWhen in her mouth, conceals the vanished maid.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>She cannot, will not, think that he is dead;\nBecause the wreck of such a noble knight\nWould, from Hydaspes' distant waves have spread,\nTo where the sun descends with westering light.\nShe knows not what to think, nor whither sped,\nHe roams in earth or air; yet, hapless wight,\nHim ever seeks, and for attendant train\nHas sobs and sighs, and every bitter pain.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>At length to find the wondrous cave she thought,\nWhere the prophetic homes of Merlin lie,\nAnd there lament herself until she wrought\nUpon the pitying marble to reply;\nFor thence, if yet he lived would she be taught,\nOf this glad life to hard necessity\nHad yielded up; and, when she was possessed\nOf the seer's councils, would pursue the best.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>With this intention, Bradamant her way\nDirected thither, where in Poictier's wood\nThe vocal tomb, containing Merlin's clay,\nConcealed in Alpine place and savage, stood.\nBut that enchantress sage, who night and day\nThought of the damsel, watchful for her good,\nShe, I repeat, who taught her what should be\nIn that fair grotto her posterity;</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>She who preserved her with protecting care,\nThat same enchantress, still benign and wise,\nWho, knowing she a matchless race should bear\nOf men, or rather semi-deities,\nSpies daily what her thoughts and actions are,\nAnd lots for her each day, divining, tries; —\nShe all Rogero's fortune knew, how freed;\nThen borne to India by the griffin steed:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XL</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Him on that courser plainly she had eyed,\nWho would not the controlling rein obey;\nWhen, severed by such interval, he hied,\nBorne through the perilous, unwonted way:\nAnd knew that he sport, dance, and banquet plied,\nAnd lapt in idleness and pleasure lay;\nNor memory of his lord nor of the dame,\nOnce loved so well, preserved, not of his fame.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And thus such gentle knight ingloriously\nWould have consumed his fairest years and best,\nIn long inaction, afterwards to be,\nBody and soul, destroyed; and that, possessed\nAlone by us in perpetuity.\nThat flower, whose sweets outlive the fragile rest\nWhich quickens man when he in earth is laid,\nWould have been plucked or severed in the blade.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>But that enchantress kind, who with more care\nThan for himself he watched, still kept the knight,\nDesigned to drag him, by rough road and bare,\nTowards true virtue, in his own despite;\nAs often cunning leech will burn and pare\nThe flesh, and poisonous drug employ aright:\nWho, though at first his cruel art offend,\nIs thanked, since he preserves us in the end.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>She, not like old Atlantes, rendered blind\nBy the great love she to the stripling bore,\nSet not on gifting him with life her mind,\nAs was the scope of that enchanter hoar;\nWho, reckless all of fame and praise declined,\nWished length of days to his Rogero more\nThan that, to win a world's applause, the peer\nShould of his joyous life forego one year.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>By him he to Alcina's isle had been\nDispatched, that in her palace he might dwell,\nForgetting arms; and, as enchanter seen\nIn magic and the use of every spell,\nThe heart had fastened of that fairy-queen,\nEnamoured of the gentle youth, so well,\nThat she the knot would never disengage,\nThough he should live to more than Nestor's age.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Returning now to her that well foreknew\nWhatever was to come to pass, I say\nShe thither did her journey straight pursue,\nWhere she met Aymon's daughter by the way\nForlorn and wandering: Bradamant at view\nOf her enchantress, erst to grief a prey,\nChanges it all to hope: the other tells\nThat with Alcina her Rogero dwells.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Nigh dead the maid remains, in piteous guise,\nHearing of him so far removed, and more\nGrieves that she danger to her love descries,\nSave this some strong and speedy cure restore.\nBut her the enchantress comforts, and applies\nA salve where it was needed most, and swore\nThat few short days should pass before anew\nRogero should return to glad her view.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Since thou, an antidote to sorcery,\nLady (she said), the virtuous ring dost wear,\nI have no doubt if to yon island I\nThis, where thine every good is hidden, hear,\nTo foil Alcina's wiles and witchery,\nAnd thence to bring thee back thy cherished care.\nThis evening, early, will I hence away,\nAnd be in India by the break of day.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And told to her, the tale continuing,\nThe mode which she was purposing to employ,\nFrom that effeminate, soft realm to bring\nBack into warlike France the cherished boy.\nBradamant from her finger slipt the ring,\nNor this alone would have bestowed with joy;\nBut heart and life would at her feet have laid,\nIf she had deemed they could Rogero aid.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Giving the ring, her cause she recommends\nTo her, and recommends Rogero more.\nCountless salutes by her the damsel sends,\nThen of Provence, departing seeks the shore.\nThe enchantress to another quarter wends;\nAnd, for the execution of her lore,\nConjures, that eve, a palfrey, by her art,\nWith one foot red, black every other part.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>L</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Some Farfarello, or Alchino he,\nI think, whom in that form she raised from hell;\nAnd with loose hair, dishevelled horribly,\nUngirt and barefoot, mounted in the sell.\nBut, with wise caution, from her finger she\nWithdrew the ring, lest it should mar the spell:\nAnd then by him was with such swiftness born,\nShe in Alcina's isle arrived at morn.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Herself she changed with wonderful disguise,\nAdding a palm of stature to her height;\nAnd made her limbs of a proportioned size;\nAnd of the very measure seemed to sight,\nAs was she deemed, the necromancer wise,\nWho with such care had reared the youthful knight.\nWith long-descending beard she clothed her chin,\nAnd wrinkled o'er her front and other skin.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>To imitate his speech, and face, and cheer,\nShe knew so well, that, by the youth descried,\nShe might the sage Atlantes' self appear;\nNext hid, and watched so long, that she espied\nUpon a day (rare chance the cavalier ) \n\nAt length detached from his Alcina's side:\nFor still, in motion or at rest, the fay\nIll bore the youth should be an hour away.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Alone she finds him, fitting well her will,\nAs he enjoys the pure and morning air\nBeside a brook, which trickled from a hill,\nStreaming towards a limpid lake and fair.\nHis fine, soft garments, wove with cunning skill,\nAll over, ease and wantonness declare;\nThese with her hand, such subtle toil well taught,\nFor him in silk and gold Alcina wrought.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>About the stripling's neck, a splendid string\nOf gems, descending to mid-breast, is wound;\nOn each once manly arm, now glittering\nWith the bright hoop, a bracelet fair is bound.\nPierced with golden wire, in form of ring,\nIs either ear; and from the yellow round\nDepend two precious pearls; not such the coast\nOf Araby or sumptuous India boast.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Crisped into comely ringlets was his hair,\nWet with the costliest odours and the best;\nAnd soft and amorous all his gestures were,\nLike one who does Valentian lady's hest.\nIn him, beside his name, was nothing fair,\nAnd more than half corrupted all the rest.\nSo was Rogero found, within that dell,\nChanged from his former self by potent spell.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Him in the figure of Atlantes sage\nShe fronts, who bore the enchanter's borrowed cheer;\nWith that grave face, and reverend with age,\nWhich he was always wonted to revere;\nAnd with that eye, which in his pupillage,\nBeaming with wrath, he whilom so did fear.\nAnd sternly cries, \"Is this the fruit at last\nWhich pays my tedious pain and labour past?</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"The marrow of the lion and the bear\nDidst thou for this thine early banquet make,\nAnd, trained by me, by cliff or cavern-lair,\nStrangle with infant hands the crested snake;\nTheir claws from tiger and from panther tear,\nAnd tusks from living boar in tangled brake,\nThat, bred in such a school, in thee should I\nAlcina's Atys or Adonis spy?</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Is this the hope that stars, observed by me,\nSigns in conjunction, sacred fibres, bred;\nWith what beside of dream or augury,\nAnd all those lots I but too deeply read,\nWhich, while yet hanging at the breast, of thee,\nWhen these thy years should be accomplished, said,\nThy fears should so be bruited far and near,\nThou justly should be deemed without a peer?</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"This does, in truth, a fair beginning show;\nA seed which, we may hope, will soon conceive\nA Julius, Alexander, Scipio.\nWho thee Alcina's bondsman could believe;\nAnd (for the world the shameful fact might know)\nThat all should, manifest to sight, perceive\nUpon thy neck and arms the servile chains,\nWherewith she at her will her captive trains?</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"If thine own single honour move not thee,\nAnd the high deeds which thou art called to do,\nWherefore defraud thy fair posterity\nOf what, was oft predicted, should ensue?\nAlas!  why seal the womb God willed should be\nPregnant by thee with an illustrious crew,\nThat far renowned, and more than human line,\nDestined the sun in glory to outshine?</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Forbid not of the noblest souls the birth,\nFormed in the ideas of Eternal Mind,\nDestined, from age to age, to visit earth,\nSprung from thy stock, and clothed in corporal rind;\nThe spring of thousand palms and festal mirth,\nThrough which, to Italy with losses pined\nAnd wounds, thy good descendants shall restore\nThe fame and honours she enjoyed of yore.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Not only should these many souls have weight\nTo bend thy purpose, holy souls, and bright,\nWhich from thy fruitful tree shall vegetate;\nBut, though alone, a single couple might\nSuffice a nobler feeling to create,\nAlphonso and his brother Hyppolite:\nWhose like was seldom witnessed to this time,\nThrough all the paths whence men to virtue climb.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"I was more wont to dwell upon this pair\nThan all the rest, of whom I prophesied;\nAs well that these a greater part should bear\nIn lofty virtues, as that I descried\nThee, listening to my lore with closer care,\nThan to the tale of all thy seed beside.\nI saw thee joy that such a pair would shine\nAmid the heroes of thy noble line.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Say, what has she, thou makest thy fancy's queen,\nMore than what other courtezans possess?\nWho of so many concubine has been;\nHow used her lovers in the end to bless,\nThou truly know'st: but that she may be seen\nWithout disguise, and in her real dress,\nThis ring, returning, on thy finger wear,\nAnd thou shalt see the dame, and mark how fair.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Abashed and mute, Rogero, listening,\nIn vain to her reproof an answer sought:\nWho on his little finger put the ring,\nWhose virtue to himself the warrior brought.\nAnd such remorse and shame within him spring,\nWhen on his altered sense the change is wrought,\nA thousand fathoms deep he fain would lie\nBuried in earth, unseen of any eye.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>So speaking, to the natural shape she wore\nBefore his eyes returned the magic dame;\nNor old Atlantes' form was needed more,\nThe good effect obtained for which she came.\nTo tell you that which was not told before,\nMelissa was the sage enchantress' name:\nWho to Rogero now her purpose said,\nAnd told with what design she thither sped:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Dispatched by her, who him in anxious pain\nDesires, nor longer can without him be,\nWith the intent to loose him from the chain\nWherewith he was begirt by sorcery;\nAnd had put on, more credence to obtain,\nAtlantes de Carena's form; but she,\nSeeing his health restored, now willed the youth,\nThrough her should hear and see the very truth.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"That gentle lady who so loves thee, who\nWere well deserving love upon thy part;\nTo whom (unless forgot, thou know'st how true\nThe tale thou debtor for thy freedom art, ) \n\nThis ring, which can each magic spell undo,\nSends for thy succour, and would send her heart,\nIf with such virtue fraught, her heart could bring\nThee safely in thy perils, like the ring.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>How Bradamant had loved, and loves, she says,\nContinuing to Rogero her relation;\nTo this, her worth commends with fitting praise,\nTempering in truth and fondness her narration;\nAnd still employs the choicest mode and phrase,\nWhich fits one skilful in negociation,\nAnd on the false Alcina brings such hate,\nAs on things horrible is wont to wait;</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Brings hate on that which he so loved before;\nNor let the tale astonish which you hear,\nFor since his love was forced by magic lore,\nThe ring the false enchantment served to clear.\nThis too unmasked the charms Alcina wore,\nAnd made all false, from head to food, appear.\nNone of her own, but borrowed, all he sees,\nAnd the once sparkling cup now drugged with lees.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Like boy who somewhere his ripe fruit bestows,\nAnd next forgets the place where it is laid,\nThen, after many days, conducted goes\nBy chance, where he the rich deposit made,\nAnd wonders that the hidden treasure shows,\nNot what it is, but rotten and decayed;\nAnd hates, and scorns, and loathes, with altered eyes,\nAnd throws away what he was used to prize.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Rogero thus, when by Melissa's lore\nAdvised, he to behold the fay returned,\nAnd that good ring of sovereign virtue wore,\nWhich, on the finger placed, all spells o'erturned;\nFor that fair damsel he had left before,\nTo his surprise, so foul a dame discerned,\nThat in this ample world, examined round,\nA hag so old and hideous is not found.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Pale, lean, and wrinkled was the face, and white,\nAnd thinly clothed with hair Alcina's head;\nHer stature reached not to six palms in height,\nAnd every tooth was gone; for she had led\nA longer life than ever mortal wight,\nThan Hecuba or she in Cuma bred;\nBut thus by practice, to our age unknown,\nAppeared with youth and beauty not her own.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>By art she gave herself the lovely look,\nWhich had on many like Rogero wrought;\nBut now the ring interpreted the book,\nWhich secrets, hid for many ages, taught.\nNo wonder then that he the dame forsook,\nAnd banished from his mind all further thought\nOf love for false Alcina, found in guise\nWhich no new means of slippery fraud supplies.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>But, as Melissa counselled him, he wore\nHis wonted semblance for a time, till he\nWas with his armour, many days before\nLaid by, again accoutred cap-a-pee.\nAnd, lest Alcina should his end explore,\nFeigned to make proof of his agility;\nFeigned to make proof if for his arms he were\nToo gross, long time unwont the mail to bear.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Next Balisarda to his flank he tied\n(For so Rogero's trenchant sword was hight),\nAnd took the wondrous buckler, which, espied,\nNot only dazzled the beholder's sight,\nBut seemed, when its silk veil was drawn aside,\nAs from the body if exhaled the sprite:\nIn its close cover of red sendal hung,\nThis at his neck the youthful warrior slung.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Provided thus, he to the stables came,\nAnd bade with bridle and with saddle dight\nA horse more black than pitch; for so the dame\nCounselled, well-taught how swift the steed and light.\nHim Rabicano those who know him name,\nAnd he the courser was, that with the knight,\nWho stands beside the sea, the breeze's sport,\nThe whale of yore conducted to that port.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The hippogryph he might have had at need,\nWho next below good Rabican was tied,\nBut that the dame had cried to him, \"Take heed,\nThou know'st how ill that courser is to ride\";\nAnd said the following day the winged steed\n'Twas her intention from that realm to guide,\nWhere he should be instructed at his leisure,\nTo rein and run him every where at pleasure:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Nor, if he took him not, would he suggest\nSuspicion of the intended flight: The peer\nThis while performed Melissa's every hest,\nWho, still invisible, was at his ear.\nSo feigning, from the wanton dome possessed\nBy that old strumpet, rode the cavalier;\nAnd pricking forth drew near unto a gate,\nWhence the road led to Logistilla's state.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Assaulting suddenly the guardian crew,\nHe, sword in hand, the squadron set upon;\nThis one he wounded, and that other slew,\nAnd, point by point made good, the drawbridge won:\nAnd ere of his escape Alcina knew,\nThe gentle youth was far away and gone.\nMy next shall tell his route, and how he gained\nAt last the realm where Logistilla reigned.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 8"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Rogero flies; Astolpho with the rest,\nTo their true shape Melissa does restore;\nRinaldo levies knights and squadrons, pressed\nIn aid of Charles assaulted by the Moor:\nAngelica, by ruffians found at rest,\nIs offered to a monster on the shore.\nOrlando, warned in visions of his ill,\nDeparts from Paris sore against his will.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>I</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>How many enchantresses among us!  oh,\nHow many enchanters are there, though unknown!\nWho for their love make man or woman glow,\nChanging them into figures not their own.\nNor this by help of spirits from below,\nNor observation of the stars is done:\nBut these on hearts with fraud and falsehood plot,\nBinding them with indissoluble knot.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>II</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Who with Angelica's, or rather who\nWere fortified with Reason's ring, would see\nEach countenance, exposed to open view,\nUnchanged by art or by hypocrisy.\nThis now seems fair and good, whose borrowed hue\nRemoved, would haply foul and evil be.\nWell was it for Rogero that he wore\nThe virtuous ring which served the truth to explore!</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>III</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Rogero, still dissembling, as I said,\nArmed, to the gate on Rabican did ride;\nFound the guard unprepared, not let his blade,\nAmid that crowd, hang idle at his side:\nHe passed the bridge, and broke the palisade,\nSome slain, some maimed; then t'wards the forest hied;\nBut on that road small space had measured yet,\nWhen he a servant of the fairy met.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>IV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>He on his fist a ravening falcon bore,\nWhich he made fly for pastime every day;\nNow on the champaign, now upon the shore\nOf neighbouring pool, which teemed with certain prey;\nAnd rode a hack which simple housings wore,\nHis faithful dog, companion of his way.\nHe, marking well the haste with which he hies,\nConjectures truly what Rogero flies.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>V</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Towards him came the knave, with semblance haught,\nDemanding whither in such haste he sped:\nTo him the good Rogero answers naught.\nHe hence assured more clearly that he fled,\nWithin himself to stop the warrior thought,\nAnd thus, with his left arm extended, said:\n\"What, if I suddenly thy purpose balk,\nAnd thou find no defence against this hawk?\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>VI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Then flies his bird, who works so well his wing,\nRabican cannot distance him in flight:\nThe falconer from his back to ground did spring,\nAnd freed him from the bit which held him tight;\nWho seemed an arrow parted from the string,\nAnd terrible to foe, with kick and bite;\nWhile with such haste behind the servant came,\nHe sped as moved by wind, or rather flame.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>VII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Nor will the falconer's dog appear more slow;\nBut hunts Rogero's courser, as in chace\nOf timid hare the pard is wont to go.\nNot to stand fast the warrior deems disgrace,\nAnd turns towards the swiftly-footed foe,\nWhom he sees wield a riding-wand, place\nOf other arms, to make his dog obey.\nRogero scorns his faulchion to display.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>VIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The servant made at him, and smote him sore;\nThe dog his left foot worried; while untied\nFrom rein, the lightened horse three times and more\nLashed from the croup, nor missed his better side.\nThe hawk, oft wheeling, with her talons tore\nThe stripling, and his horse so terrified,\nThe courser, by the whizzing sound dismayed,\nLittle the guiding hand or spur obeyed.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>IX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Constrained at length, his sword Rogero drew\nTo clear the rabble, who his course delay;\nAnd in the animals' or villain's view\nDid now its point, and now its edge display.\nBut with more hinderance and vexatious crew\nSwarm here and there, and wholly block the way;\nAnd that dishonour will ensue and loss,\nRogero sees, if him they longer cross.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>X</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>He knew each little that he longer stayed,\nWould bring the fay and followers on the trail;\nAlready drums were beat, and trumpets brayed,\nAnd larum-bells rang loud in every vale.\nAn act too foul it seemed to use his blade\nOn dog, and knave unfenced with arms or mail:\nA better and shorter way it were\nThe buckler, old Atlantes' work, to bare.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>He raised the crimson cloth in which he wore\nThe wondrous shield, enclosed for many a day;\nIts beams, as proved a thousand times before,\nWork as they wont, when on the sight they play;\nSenseless the falconer tumbles on the moor;\nDrop dog and hackney; drop the pinions gay,\nWhich poised in air the bird no longer keep:\nThen glad Rogero leaves a prey to sleep.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>In the mean time, Alcina, who had heard\nHow he had forced the gate, and, in the press,\nSlaughtered a mighty number of her guard,\nRemained nigh dead, o'erwhelmed with her distress;\nShe tore her vesture, and her visage marred,\nAnd cursed her want of wit and wariness.\nThen made forthwith her meiny sound to arms,\nAnd round herself arrayed her martial swarms.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Divided next, one squadron by the way\nRogero took, she sent; the bands were two:\nShe at the port embarked the next array,\nAnd straight to sea dispatched the warlike crew.\nWith this good squadron went the desperate fay,\nAnd darked by loosened sails the billows grew;\nFor so desire upon her bosom preyed,\nOf troops she left her city unpurveyed.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Without a guard she left her palace there,\nWhich to Melissa, prompt her time to seize,\nTo loose her vassals that in misery were,\nAfforded all convenience and full ease;\n— To range, at leisure, through the palace fair,\nAnd so examine all her witcheries;\nTo raze the seal, burn images, and loose\nOr cancel hag-knot, rhomb, or magic noose.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Thence, through the fields, fast hurrying from that dome,\nThe former lovers changed, a mighty train,\nSome into rock or tree, to fountain some,\nOr beast, she made assume their shapes again:\nAnd these, when they anew are free to roam,\nFollow Rogero's footsteps to the reign\nOf Logistilla's sage; and from that bourn\nTo Scythia, Persia, Greece, and Ind return.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>They to their several homes dispatched, repair,\nBound by a debt which never can be paid:\nThe English duke, above the rest her care,\nOf these, was first in human form arrayed:\nFor much his kindred and the courteous prayer\nOf good Rogero with Melissa weighed.\nBeside his prayers, the ring Rogero gave;\nThat him she by its aid might better save.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Thus by Rogero's suit the enchantress won,\nTo his first shape transformed the youthful peer;\nBut good Melissa deemed that nought was done\nSave she restored his armour, and that spear\nOf gold, which whensoe'er at tilt he run,\nAt the first touch unseated cavalier;\nOnce Argalia's, next Astolpho's lance,\nAnd source of mighty fame to both in France.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The sage Melissa found this spear of gold,\nWhich now Alcina's magic palace graced,\nAnd other armour of the warrior bold,\nOf which he was in that ill dome uncased.\nShe climbed the courser of the wizard old,\nAnd on the croup, at ease, Astolpho placed:\nAnd thus, an hour before Rogero came,\nRepaired to Logistilla, knight and dame.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Meantime, through rugged rocks, and shagged with thorn,\nRogero wends, to seek the sober fay;\nFrom cliff to cliff, from path to path forlorn,\nA rugged, lone, inhospitable way:\nTill he, with labour huge oppressed and worn,\nIssued at noon upon a beach, that lay\n'Twixt sea and mountain, open to the south,\nDeserted, barren, bare, and parched with drouth.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The sunbeams on the neighbouring mountain beat\nAnd glare, reflected from the glowing mass\nSo fiercely, sand and air both boil with heat,\nIn mode that might have more than melted glass.\nThe birds are silent in their dim retreat,\nNor any note is heard in wood or grass,\nSave the bough perched Cicala's wearying cry,\nWhich deafens hill and dale, and sea and sky.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The heat and thirst and labour which he bore\nBy that drear sandy way beside the sea,\nAlong the unhabited and sunny shore,\nWere to Rogero grievous company:\nBur for I may not still pursue this lore,\nNor should you busied with one matter be,\nRogero I abandon in this heat,\nFor Scotland; to pursue Rinaldo's beat.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>By king, by daughter, and by all degrees,\nTo Sir Rinaldo was large welcome paid;\nAnd next the warrior, at his better ease,\nThe occasion of his embassy displayed:\nThat he from thence and England, subsidies\nOf men was seeking, for his monarch's aid,\nIn Charles's name; and added, in his care,\nThe justest reasons to support his prayer.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The king made answer, that `without delay,\nTaxed to the utmost of his powers and might,\nHis means at Charlemagne's disposal lay,\nFor the honour of the empire and the right.\nAnd that, within few days, he in array\nSuch horsemen, as he had in arms, would dight;\nAnd, save that he was now waxed old, would lead\nThe expedition he was prayed to speed.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>`Nor like consideration would appear\nWorthy to stop him, but that he possessed\nA son, and for such charge that cavalier,\nMeasured by wit and force, was worthiest.\nThough not within the kingdom was the peer,\nIt was his hope (as he assured his guest)\nHe would, while yet preparing was the band,\nReturn, and find it mustered to his hand.'</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>So sent through all his realm, with expedition,\nHis treasures, to levy men and steeds;\nAnd ships prepared, and warlike ammunition,\nAnd money, stores and victual for their needs.\nMeantime the good Rinaldo on his mission,\nLeaving the courteous king, to England speeds;\nHe brought him on his way to Berwick's town,\nAnd was observed to weep when he was gone.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The wind sat in the poop; Rinaldo good\nEmbarked and bade farewell to all; the sheet\nStill loosening to the breeze, the skipper stood,\nTill where Thames' waters, waxing bitter, meet\nSalt ocean: wafted thence by tide of flood,\nThrough a sure channel to fair London's seat,\nSafely the mariners their course explore,\nMaking their way, with aid of sail and oar.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The Emperor Charles, and he, King Otho grave,\nWho was with Charles, by siege in Paris pressed,\nA broad commission to Rinaldo brave,\nWith letters to the Prince of Wales addressed,\nAnd countersigns had given, dispatched to crave\nWhat foot and horse were by the land possessed.\nThe whole to be to Calais' port conveyed;\nThat it to France and Charles might furnish aid.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The prince I speak of, who on Otho's throne\nSate in his stead, the vacant helm to guide,\nSuch honor did to Aymon's valiant son,\nHe not with such his king had gratified.\nNext, all to good Rinaldo's wish, was done:\nSince for his martial bands on every side,\nIn Britain, or the isles which round her lay,\nTo assemble near the sea he fixed a day.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>But here, sir, it behoves me shift my ground,\nLike him that makes the sprightly viol ring,\nWho often changes chord and varies sound,\nAnd now a graver strikes, now sharper string:\nThus I: — who did to good Rinaldo bound\nMy tale, Angelica remembering;\nLate left, where saved from him by hasty flight,\nShe had encountered with an anchorite.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Awhile I will pursue her story: I\nTold how the maid of him with earnest care,\nEnquired, how she towards the shore might fly:\nWho of the loathed Rinaldo has such fear,\nShe dreads, unless she pass the sea, to die,\nAs insecure in Europe, far or near,\nBut she was by the hermit kept in play,\nBecause he pleasure took with her to stay.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>His heart with love of that rare beauty glowed,\nAnd to his frozen marrow pierced the heat;\nWho, after, when he saw that she bestowed\nSmall care on him, and thought but of retreat,\nHis sluggish courser stung with many a goad;\nBut with no better speed he plied his feet.\nIll was his walk, and worse his trot; nor spur\nCould that dull beast to quicker motion stir:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And for the flying maid was far before,\nAnd he would soon have ceased to track her steed,\nTo the dark cave recurred the hermit hoar,\nAnd conjured up of fiends a grisly breed:\nOne he selected out of many more,\nAnd first informed the demon of his need;\nThen in the palfrey bade him play his part,\nWho with the lady bore away his heart:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And as sagacious dog on mountain tried\nBefore, accustomed fox and hare to chase,\nIf he behold the quarry choose one side,\nThe other takes, and seems to slight the trace:\nBut at the turn arriving, is espied,\nAlready tearing what he crossed to face;\nSo her the hermit by a different road\nWill meet, wherever she her palfrey goad.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>What was the friar's design I well surmise;\nAnd you shall know; but in another page.\nAngelica now slow, now faster, flies,\nNought fearing this: while conjured by the sage,\nThe demon covered in the courser lies;\nAs fire sometimes will hide its smothered rage:\nThen blazes with devouring flame and heat,\nUnquenchable, and scarce allows retreat.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>After the flying maid had shaped her course\nBy the great sea which laves the Gascon shore,\nStill keeping to the rippling waves her horse,\nWhere best the moistened sand the palfrey bore,\nHim, plunged into the brine, the fiend perforce\nDragged, till he swam amid the watery roar.\nNor what to do the timid damsel knew,\nSave that she closer to her saddle grew.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>She cannot, howsoe'er the rein she ply,\nGovern the horse, who swims the surge to meet:\nHer raiment she collects and holds it high;\nAnd, not to wet them, gathers up her feet.\nHer tresses, which the breeze still wantonly\nAssaults, dishevelled on her shoulders beat.\nThe louder winds are hushed, perchance in duty,\nIntent, like ocean, on such sovereign beauty.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Landward in vain her eyes the damsel bright\nDirects, which water face and breast with tears,\nAnd ever sees, decreasing to her sight,\nThe beach she left, which less and less appears.\nThe courser, who was swimming to the right,\nAfter a mighty sweep, the lady bears\nTo shore, where rock and cavern shag the brink,\nAs night upon the land begins to sink.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>When in that desert, which but to descry\nBred fear in the beholder, stood the maid\nAlone, as Phoebus, plunged in ocean, sky\nAnd nether earth had left obscured in shade;\nShe paused in guise, which in uncertainty\nMight leave whoever had the form surveyed,\nIf she were real woman, or some mock\nResemblance, coloured in the living rock.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>She, fixed and stupid in her wretchedness,\nStood on the shifting sand, with ruffled hair:\nHer hands were joined, her lips were motionless,\nHer languid eyes upturned, as in despair,\nAccusing Him on high, that to distress\nAnd whelm her, all the fates united were.\nAstound she stood awhile; when grief found vent\nThrough eyes and tongue, in tears and in lament.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XL</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Fortune what more remains, that thou on me\nShouldst not now satiate thy revengeful thirst?\nWhat more (she said can I bestow on thee ) \n\nThan, what thou seekest not, this life accurst?\nThou wast in haste to snatch me from the sea,\nWhere I had ended its sad days, immersed;\nBecause to torture me with further ill\nBefore I die, is yet thy cruel will.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"But what worse torment yet remains in store\nBeyond, I am unable to descry:\nBy thee from my fair throne, which nevermore\nI hope to repossess, compelled to fly;\nI, what is worse, my honour lost deplore;\nFor if I sinned not in effect, yet I\nGive matter by my wanderings to be stung\nFor wantonness of every carping tongue.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"What other good is left to woman, who\nHas lost her honour, in this earthly ball?\nWhat profits it that, whether false or true,\nI am deemed beauteous, and am young withal?\nNo thanks to heaven for such a gift are due,\nWhence on my head does every mischief fall.\nFor this my brother Argalia died;\nTo whom small help enchanted arms supplied:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"For this the Tartar king, Sir Agrican,\nSubdued my sire, who Galaphron was hight,\nAnd of Catay in India was great khan;\n'Tis hence I am reduced to such a plight,\nThat wandering evermore, I cannot scan\nAt morn, where I shall lay my head at night.\nIf thou hast ravished what thou couldst, wealth, friends,\nAnd honour; say what more thy wrath intends.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"If death by drowning in the foaming sea\nWas not enough thy wrath to satiate,\nSend, if thou wilt, some beast to swallow me,\nSo that he keep me not in pain!  Thy hate\nCannot devise a torment, so it be\nMy death, but I shall thank thee for my fate!\"\nThus, with loud sobs, the weeping lady cried,\nWhen she beheld the hermit at her side.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>From the extremest height the hermit hoar\nOf that high rock above her, had surveyed\nAngelica, arrived upon the shore,\nBeneath the cliff, afflicted and dismayed.\nHe to that place had come six days before;\nFor him by path untrod had fiend conveyed:\nAnd he approached her, feigning such a call\nAs e'er Hilarion might have had, or Paul.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>When him, yet unagnized, she saw appear,\nThe lady took some comfort, and laid by,\nEmboldened by degrees, her former fear:\nThough still her visage was of death-like dye.\n\"Misericord!  father,\" when the friar was near\n(She said), \"for brought to evil pass am I.\"\nAnd told, still broke by sobs, in doleful tone,\nThe story, to her hearer not unknown.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>To comfort her, some reasons full of grace,\nSage and devout the approaching hermit cites:\nAnd, now his hand upon her moistened face,\nIn speaking, now upon her bosom lights:\nAs her, securer, next he would embrace:\nHim, kindling into pretty scorn, she smites\nWith one hand on his breast, and backward throws,\nThen flushed with honest red, all over glows.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>A pocket at the ancient's side was dight,\nWhere he a cruise of virtuous liquor wore;\nAnd at those puissant eyes, whence flashed the light\nOf the most radiant torch Love ever bore,\nThrew from the flask a little drop, of might\nTo make her sleep: upon the sandy shore\nAlready the recumbent damsel lay,\nThe greedy elder's unresisting prey.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>(Stanza XLIX untranslated by Rose)</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>L</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>(Lines 1-2 untranslated by Rose)\nHopeless, at length upon the beach he lies,\nAnd by the maid, exhausted, falls asleep.\nWhen to torment him new misfortunes rise:\nFortune does seldom any measure keep;\nUnused to cut her cruel pastime short,\nIf she with mortal man is pleased to sport.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>It here behoves me, from the path I pressed,\nTo turn awhile, ere I this case relate:\nIn the great northern sea, towards the west,\nGreen Ireland past, an isle is situate.\nEbuda is its name, whose shores infest,\n(Its people wasted through the Godhead's hate)\nThe hideous orc, and Proteus' other herd,\nBy him against that race in vengeance stirred.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Old stories, speak they falsely or aright,\nTell how a puissant king this country swayed;\nWho had a daughter fair, so passing bright\nAnd lovely, 'twas no wonder if the maid,\nWhen on the beach she stood in Proteus' sight,\nLeft him to burn amid the waves: surveyed,\nOne day alone, upon that shore in-isled,\nHer he compressed, and quitted great with child.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>This was sore torment to the sire, severe\nAnd impious more than all mankind; nor he,\nSuch is the force of wrath, was moved to spare\nThe maid, for reason or for piety.\nNor, though he saw her pregnant, would forbear\nTo execute his sentence suddenly;\nBut bade together with the mother kill,\nEre born, his grandchild, who had done no ill.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Sea-Proteus to his flocks' wide charge preferred\nBy Neptune, of all ocean's rule possessed,\nInflamed with ire, his lady's torment heard,\nAnd, against law and usage, to molest\nThe land (no sluggard in his anger stirred ) \n\nHis monsters, orc and sea-calf, with the rest;\nWho waste not only herds, but human haunts,\nFarm-house and town, with their inhabitants:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And girding them on every side, the rout\nWill often siege to walled cities lay;\nWhere in long weariness and fearful doubt,\nThe townsmen keep their watch by night and day.\nThe fields they have abandoned all about,\nAnd for a remedy, their last assay,\nTo the oracle, demanding counsel, fly,\nWhich to the suppliant's prayer made this reply:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>`That it behoved them find a damsel, who\nA form as beauteous as that other wore,\nTo be to Proteus offered up, in lieu\nOf the fair lady, slain upon the shore:\nHe, if he deems her an atonement due,\nWill keep the damsel, not disturb them more:\nIf not, another they must still present,\nAnd so, till they the deity content.'</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And this it was the cruel usage bred;\nThat of the damsels held most fair of face,\nTo Proteus every day should one be led.\nTill one should in the Godhead's sight find grace.\nThe first and all those others slain, who fed,\nAll a devouring orc, that kept his place\nBeside the port, what time into the main\nThe remnant of the herd retired again.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Were the old tale of Proteus' false or true,\n(For this, in sooth, I know not who can read)\nWith such a clause was kept by that foul crew\nThe savage, ancient statute, which decreed\nThat woman's flesh the ravening monster, who\nFor this came every day to land, should feed.\nThough to be woman is a crying ill\nIn every place, 'tis here a greater still.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>O wretched maids!  whom 'mid that barbarous rout\nIll-fortune on that wretched shore has tost!\nWho for the stranger damsel prowl about,\nOf her to make an impious holocaust;\nIn that the more they slaughter from without,\nThey less the number of their own exhaust.\nBut since not always wind and waves convey\nLike plunder, upon every strand they prey.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>With frigate and with galley wont to roam,\nAnd other sort of barks they range the sea,\nAnd, as a solace to their martyrdom,\nFrom far, or from their isle's vicinity,\nBear women off; with open rapine some,\nThese bought by gold, and those by flattery:\nAnd, plundered from the different lands they scower,\nCrowd with their captives dungeon-cell and tower.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Keeping that region close aboard, to explore\nThe island's lonely bank, a gallery creeps;\nWhere, amid stubs upon the grassy shore,\nAngelica, unhappy damsel, sleeps.\nTo wood and water there the sailor's moor,\nAnd from the bark, for this, a party leaps;\nAnd there that matchless flower of earthly charms\nDiscovers in the holy father's arms.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Oh!  prize too dear, oh!  too illustrious prey!\nTo glut so barbarous and so base a foe!\nOh!  cruel Fortune!  who believed thy sway\nWas of such passing power in things below?\nThat thou shouldst make a hideous monster's prey\nThe beauty, for which Agrican did glow,\nBrought with half Scythia's people from the gates\nOf Caucasus, in Ind, to find their fates.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The beauty, by Circassian Sacripant\nPreferred before his honour and his crown,\nThe beauty which made Roland, Brava's vaunt,\nSully his wholesome judgment and renown,\nThe beauty which had moved the wide Levant,\nAnd awed, and turned its kingdom upside down,\nNow has not (thus deserted and unheard)\nOne to assist it even with a word.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Oppressed with heavy sleep upon the shore,\nThe lovely virgin, ere awake, they chain:\nWith her, the enchanter friar the pirates bore\nOn board their ship, a sad, afflicted train.\nThis done, they hoisted up their sail once more,\nAnd the bark made the fatal isle again,\nWhere, till the lot shall of their prey dispose,\nHer prisoned in a castle they enclose.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>But such her matchless beauty's power, the maid\nWas able that fierce crew to mollify,\nWho many days her cruel death delayed,\nPreserved until their last necessity;\nAnd while they damsels from without purveyed,\nSpared such angelic beauty: finally,\nThe damsel to the monstrous orc they bring,\nThe people all behind her sorrowing.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Who shall relate the anguish, the lament\nAnd outcry which against the welkin knock?\nI marvel that the sea-shore was not rent,\nWhen she was placed upon the rugged block,\nWhere, chained and void of help, the punishment\nOf loathsome death awaits her on the rock.\nThis will not I, so sorrow moves me, say,\nWhich makes me turn my rhymes another way;</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>To find a verse of less lugubrious strain,\nTill I my wearied spirit shall restore:\nFor not the squalid snake of mottled stain,\nNor wild and whelpless tiger, angered more,\nNor what of venomous, on burning plain,\nCreeps 'twixt the Red and the Atlantic shore,\nCould see the grisly sight, and choose but moan\nThe damsel bound upon the naked stone.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Oh!  if this chance to her Orlando, who\nWas gone to Paris-town to seek the maid,\nHad been reported!  or those other two,\nDuped by a post, dispatched from Stygian shade,\nThey would have tracked her heavenly footsteps through\nA thousand deaths, to bear the damsel aid.\nBut had the warriors of her peril known.\nSo far removed, for what would that have done?</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>This while round Paris-walls the leaguer lay\nOf famed Troyano's son's besieging band,\nReduced to such extremity one day,\nThat it nigh fell into the foeman's hand;\nAnd, but that vows had virtue to allay\nThe wrath of Heaven, whose waters drenched the land,\nThat day had perished by the Moorish lance\nThe holy empire and great name of France.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>To the just plaint of aged Charlemagne\nThe great Creator turned his eyes, and stayed\nThe conflagration with a sudden rain,\nWhich haply human art had not allayed.\nWise whosoever seeketh, not in vain,\nHis help, than whose there is no better aid!\nWell the religious king, to whom 'twas given,\nKnew that the saving succour was from Heaven.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>All night long counsel of his weary bed,\nVexed with a ceaseless care, Orlando sought;\nNow here, now there, the restless fancy sped,\nNow turned, now seized, but never held the thought:\nAs when, from sun or nightly planet shed,\nClear water has the quivering radiance caught,\nThe flashes through the spacious mansion fly,\nWith reaching leap, right, left, and low, and high.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>To memory now returned his lady gay,\nShe rather ne'er was banished from his breast;\nAnd fanned the secret fire, which through the day\n(Now kindled into flame had seemed at rest; ) \n\nThat in his escort even from Catay\nOr farthest Ind, had journeyed to the west;\nThere lost: Of whom he had discerned no token\nSince Charles's power near Bordeaux-town was broken.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>This in Orlando moved great grief, and he\nLay thinking on his folly past in vain:\n\"My heart,\" he said, \"oh! how unworthily\nI bore myself!  and out, alas!  what pain,\n(When night and day I might have dwelt with thee,\nSince this thou didst not in thy grace disdain.)\nTo have let them place thee in old Namus' hand!\nWitless a wrong so crying to withstand.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Might I not have excused myself? — The king\nHad not perchance gainsaid my better right —\nOf if he had gainsaid my reasoning,\nWho would have taken thee in my despite?\nWhy not have armed, and rather let them wring\nMy heart out of my breast?  But not the might\nOf Charles or all his host, had they been tried,\nCould have availed to tear thee from my side.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Oh!  had he placed her but in strong repair,\nGuarded in some good fort, or Paris-town!\n— Since he would trust her to Duke Namus' care,\nThat he should lose her in this way, alone\nSorts with my wish. — Who would have kept the fair\nLike me, that would for her to death have gone?\nHave kept her better than my heart or sight:\nWho should and could, yet did not what I might.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Without me, my sweet life, beshrew me, where\nArt thou bestowed, so beautiful and young!\nAs some lost lamb, what time the daylight fair\nShuts in, remains the wildering woods among,\nAnd goes about lamenting here and there,\nHoping to warn the shepherd with her tongue;\nTill the wolf hear from far the mournful strain,\nAnd the sad shepherd weep for her in vain.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"My hope, where are thou, where?  In doleful wise\nDost thou, perchance, yet rove thy lonely round?\nArt thou, indeed, to ravening wolf a prize,\nWithout thy faithful Roland's succour found?\nAnd is the flower, which, with the deities,\nMe, in mid heaven had placed, which, not to wound,\n(So reverent was my love thy feelings chaste, ) \n\nI kept untouched, alas!  now plucked and waste?</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"If this fair flower be plucked, oh, misery!  oh,\nDespair!  what more is left me but to die?\nAlmighty God, with every other woe\nRather than this, thy wretched suppliant try.\nIf this be true, these hands the fatal blow\nShall deal, and doom me to eternity.\"\nMixing his plaint with bitter tears and sighs,\nSo to himself the grieved Orlando cries.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Already every where, with due repose,\nCreatures restored their weary spirits; laid\nThese upon stones and upon feathers those,\nOr greensward, in the beech or myrtle's shade:\nBut scarcely did thine eyes, Orlando close,\nSo on thy mind tormenting fancies preyed.\nNor would the vexing thoughts which bred annoy,\nLet thee in peace that fleeting sleep enjoy.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>To good Orlando it appeared as he,\nMid odorous flowers, upon a grassy bed,\nWere gazing on that beauteous ivory,\nWhich Love's own hand had tinged with native red;\nAnd those two stars of pure transparency,\nWith which he in Love's toils his fancy fed:\nOf those bright eyes, and that bright face, I say,\nWhich from his breast had torn his heart away.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>He with the fullest pleasure overflows,\nThat ever happy lover did content:\nBut, lo!  this time a mighty tempest rose,\nAnd wasted flowers, and trees uptore and rent.\nNot with the rage with which this whirlwind blows,\nJoust warring winds, north, south, and east, unpent.\nIt seemed, as if in search of covering shade,\nHe, vainly wandering, through a desert strayed.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Meanwhile the unhappy lover lost the dame\nIn that dim air, nor how he lost her, weets;\nAnd, roving far and near, her beauteous name\nThrough every sounding wood and plain repeats.\nAnd while, \"Oh wretched me!\" is his exclaim,\n\"Who has to poison changed my promised sweets?\"\nHe of his sovereign lady who with tears\nDemands his aid, the lamentation hears.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Thither, whence comes the sound, he swiftly hies,\nAnd toils, now here, now there, with labour sore:\nOh!  what tormenting grief, to think his eyes\nCannot again the lovely rays explore!\n— Lo!  other voice from other quarter cries —\n\"Hope not on earth to enjoy the blessing more.\"\nAt that alarming cry he woke, and found\nHimself in tears of bitter sorrow drowned.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Not thinking that like images are vain,\nWhen fear, or when desire disturbs our rest,\nThe thought of her, exposed to shame and pain,\nIn such a mode upon his fancy pressed,\nHe, thundering, leaped from bed, and with what chain\nAnd plate behoved, his limbs all over dressed;\nTook Brigliadoro from the stall he filled,\nNor any squire attendant's service willed.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And to pass every where, yet not expose\nBy this his dignity to stain or slight,\nThe old and honoured ensign he foregoes,\nHis ancient bearing, quartered red and white.\nAnd in its place a sable ensign shows,\nPerhaps as suited to his mournful plight,\nThat erst he from an Amostantes bore,\nWhom he had slain in fight some time before.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>At midnight he departed silently,\nNot to his uncle spake, not to his true\nAnd faithful comrade Brandimart, whom he\nSo dearly cherished, even bade adieu;\nBut when, with golden tresses streaming-free,\nThe sun from rich Tithonus' inn withdrew,\nAnd chased the shades, and cleared the humid air,\nThe king perceived Orlando was not there.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>To Charles, to his displeasure, were conveyed\nNews that his nephew had withdrawn at night,\nWhen most he lacked his presence and his aid;\nNor could he curb his choler at the flight,\nBut that with foul reproach he overlaid,\nAnd sorely threatened the departed knight,\nBy him so foul a fault should be repented,\nSave he, returning home, his wrath prevented.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Nor would Orlando's faithful Brandimart,\nWho loved him as himself, behind him stay;\nWhether to bring him back he in his heart\nHoped, or of him ill brooked injurious say:\nAnd scarce, in his impatience to depart,\nTill fall of eve his sally would delay.\nLest she should hinder his design, of this\nHe nought imparted to his Flordelis:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>To him this was a lady passing dear,\nAnd from whose side he unwont to stray;\nEndowed with manners, grace, and beauteous cheer,\nWisdom and wit: if now he went away\nAnd took no leave, it was because the peer\nHoped to revisit her that very day.\nBut that befel him after, as he strayed,\nWhich him beyond his own intent delayed.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XC</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>She when she has expected him in vain\nWell nigh a month, and nought of him discerns,\nSallies without a guide or faithful train,\nSo with desire of him her bosom yearns:\nAnd many a country seeks for him in vain;\nTo whom the story in due place returns.\nNo more I now shall tell you of these two,\nMore bent Anglantes' champion to pursue;</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XCI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Who having old Almontes' blazonry\nSo changed, drew nigh the gate; and there the peer\nApproached a captain of the guard, when he;\n\"I am the County,\" whispered in his ear,\nAnd (the bridge quickly lowered, and passage free\nAt his commandment by the way most near ) \n\nWent straight towards the foe: but what befell</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>Canto which ensues shall tell.</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 9"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>So far Orlando wends, he comes to where\nHe of old Proteus' hears the cruel use\nBut feels such pity for Olympia fair,\nWronged by Cymosco, who in prison mews\nHer plighted spouse, that ere he makes repair\nFurther, he gives her hope to venge the abuse:\nHe does so, and departs; and with his spouse\nDeparts Bireno, to repeat his vows.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>I</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>What cannot, when he has a heart possess'd\nThis false and cruel traitor Love?  since he\nCan banish from Orlando's faithful breast\nSuch tried allegiance and due loyalty?\nWise, full of all regards, and of the blest\nAnd glorious church the champion wont to be,\nNow, little for himself or uncle, driven\nBy a vain love, he cares, and less for heaven.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>II</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>But I excuse him well, rejoiced to know\nI have like partner in my vice: for still\nTo seek my good I too am faint and slow,\nBut sound and nimble in pursuit of ill.\nThe count departs, disguised in sable show,\nNor for so many friends, with froward will,\nDeserted cares; and comes where on the plain\nAre camped the hosts of Afric and of Spain;</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>III</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Rather uncamped: for, in less troops or more,\nRains under shed and tree had driven the band.\nHere ten, there twenty, seven or eight, or four,\nNear or further off, Orlando scanned.\nEach sleeps, oppressed with toil and wearied sore;\nThis stretched on earth, that propped upon his hand:\nThey sleep, and many might the count have slain,\nYet never bared his puissant Durindane.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>IV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>So generous is Orlando's heart, he base\nEsteems it were to smite a sleeping foe.\nNow this he seeks, and now that other place;\nYet cannot track his lady, high or low.\nIf he finds any one in waking case,\nSighing, to him he paints her form and show;\nThen prays him that for courtesy, he where\nThe damsel is, will reach him to repair.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>V</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And when the day its shining light displayed,\nHe wholly searched the Moorish army through.\nIn that the gentle warrior was arrayed\nIn Arab weeds, he this might safely do;\nAnd of his purpose came alike in aid\nThat other tongues beside the French he knew;\nAnd in the African so well was read,\nHe seemed in Tripoly one born and bred:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>VI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>He sojourns there three days, the camp to see;\nStill seeking nought beside: next up and down,\nWithin, without, both burgh and city he\nSpies; nor surveys the realm of France alone;\nBut fair Auvergne, and even Gascony\nRevisits, to its farthest little town.\nRoves from Provence to Brittany's domain,\nAnd from the Picards to the bounds of Spain.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>VII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Between October and November's moon,\nIn that dull season when the leafy vest\nIs stript from trembling plant, whose limbs are shown\nOf all their mantling foliage dispossess'd\nAnd in close flights the swarming birds are flown,\nOrlando enters on his amorous quest:\nThis he pursues the livelong winter through,\nNor quits when gladsome spring returns anew.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>VIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>As (such his wont from land to land he goes, ) \n\nA river's side he reaches on a day;\nWhich to the neighbouring sea in quiet flows.\nBretons and Normans parting on its way:\nBut, swoln with mountain rain and melted snows,\nThen thundered, white with foam and flashing-spray:\nAnd with impetuous stream had overtopt\nIts brim, and burst the bridge, and passage stopt.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>IX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The paladin this bank and the other eyed,\nAlong the river's channel, to explore,\nSince neither fish nor fowl, if from his side\nHe could gain footing on the adverse shore;\nWhen, with a damsel in the poop, he spied\nA ready pinnace that towards him bore:\nShe steered, as if she would approach the strand;\nBut would not let her shallop make the land.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>X</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Steered not to land; as haply with suspicion\nTo take a lading, in her own despite.\nTo her the good Orlando made petition\nTo put him o'er the stream; and she: \"No knight\nPasses this ferry, but upon condition\nHe shall his faith and promise duly plight,\nThat he will do a battle, at my prayer,\nUpon the justest quarrel and most fair.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"So that if thou on that other shore to land\nDost by my aid, Sir cavalier, desire,\nPromise me, ere the month which is at hand\"\n(The damsel so pursued her speech \"expire, ) \n\nThat thou wilt join the Hibernian monarch's hand,\nWho forms a fair armada, in his ire,\nTo sack Ebuda's isle; of all compress'd\nBy ocean's circling waves, the cruellest.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Know, beyond Ireland, in the briny flood,\nAn island, amid many others, lies;\nEbuda is its name; whose people rude\n(Such is their law), in search of plunder hies;\nAnd all the women that it takes, for food\nTo a voracious animal supplies;\nWhich every day to shore for this does speed,\nAnd finds new wife or maid whereon to feed:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"For of these merchant still and Corsair sell\nA large supply, and most of those most fair.\nReckoning one slain a-day, you thus may well\nCompute what wives and maids have perished there.\nBut if compassion in your bosom dwell,\nNor you to Love an utter rebel are,\nBe you contented with this band to wend,\nUnited for such profitable end.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>To hear the whole Orlando scarce could bear,\nEre to be first in that emprize he swore,\nAs one who evil deed misliked to hear,\nAnd with impatience like relation bore:\nHence first induced to think, and next to fear,\nAngelica is captive on that shore:\nSince he so long the missing maid pursues,\nNor of the damsel yet can gather news.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Breaking his every scheme, this phantasy\nThe troubled cavalier did so confound,\nThat will all speed to that fell island he\nResolved to navigate; nor yet the round\nOf a new sun was buried in the sea,\nEre he a vessel at St. Malo's found;\nIn which, embarking on his quest, the count\nPut forth, and cleared that night St. Michael's Mount.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Breac and Landriglier past on the left hand,\nOrlando's vessel skims the Breton shore;\nThen shapes her course towards the chalky strand,\nWhence England's isle the name of Albion bore:\nBut the south wind, which had her canvas fanned,\nShifts to north-west, and freshening, blows so sore,\nThe mariners are fain to strike all sail,\nAnd wear and scud before the boisterous gale.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>A distance traversed in four days, in one\nBackwards the ceaseless wind the frigate bore;\nThe helmsman kept the sea, lest she should run\nAground, and break like glass upon the shore.\nThe wind upon the fifth day changed its tune,\nSo loud and furious through the other four;\nAnd let, without more strife, the vessel gain\nA port, where Antwerp's river met the main.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>As soon as harboured there in shattered plight,\nThe weary mariners their frigate moor,\nOut of a city, seated on the right\nOf that fair stream, descends upon the shore,\nAs his gray hairs may warrant him, a wight\nStricken in years; who, full of courteous lore,\nTurns to the county, after greetings due,\nReputing him the leader of that crew.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And prays him, on a damsel's part, `that he\nTo her would think not irksome to repair;\nWhom of unequalled affability\nAnd sweetness, he would find, as well as fair;\nOr otherwise would be content, that she\nShould to his bark resort, to seek him there,\nNor prove less pliant than had been before\nAll the knights errant, who had sought that shore:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>For hitherto, by land or sea conveyed,\nNo cavalier had journeyed to that place\nThat had refused to parlay with the maid,\nAnd give her counsel in a cruel case.'\nOrlando, hearing this, no more delayed,\nBut issued from the bark with hurried pace,\nAnd, in all kind and courteous usage bred,\nHis way directed where the ancient led.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>With him did Roland to the city go,\nAnd at the bottom of a palace-stair,\nConducted by that elder, full of woe\nA lady found, if face may grief declare,\nAnd sable cloth, with which (a mournful show)\nChamber, and hall, and gallery, furnished were;\nWho, after honourable welcome paid,\nSeated the paladin, and sadly said:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"The daughter of the Count of Holland,\" (cried\nThe Lady \"know in me, Sir cavalier. ) \n\nThough not his only offspring (for beside\nMyself two brothers were to him so dear, ) \n\nThat, for whatever favour I applied,\nI never met refusal from the peer.\nI living glady in this happy sort,\nA duke by chance was guested at our court;</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"The Duke of Zealand, meaning for Biscay;\nWith purpose there to war upon the Moor;\nHis youth and beauty, then in manhood's May,\nAnd force of love, unfelt by me before,\nMade me, with little strife, his easy prey:\nPersuaded by his outward cheer yet more,\nI thought, and think, and still shall think, the peer\nLoved me, and loves me yet with heart sincere.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Those days, whenas the wind was contrary,\n(Which fair for me, if foul for others blew)\nTo others forty seemed, an hour to me;\nSo upon speedy wings the moments flew.\nThis while, we oftentimes held colloquy,\nWhen, to be given with solemn right and due,\nI promised him, and he to me, his hand,\nOn his return, in wedlock's holy band.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Bireno hardly from our court was gone,\nFor such the name my faithful lover bore,\nWhen Friesland's king, whose realm is from our own\nNo further than this stream from Ocean's shore,\nDesigning to bestow me on his son,\nArbantes hight (the monarch had no more),\nTo Holland sent the worthiest of his land,\nMe of the count, my father, to demand.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"I without power to falsify that vow,\nWhich to my gentle lover I had plight;\nNor though I had the power, would Love allow\nMe so to play the ingrate, if I might,\n(The treaty, well on foot, to overthrow,\nAnd nigh concluded with afflicted sprite, ) \n\nCried to my father, I would rather shed\nMy very life-blood, than in Friesland wed.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"My gracious father, he who took but pleasure\nIn what pleased me, nor would my will constrain;\nMarking my grief, broke off the intended measure,\nTo give me comfort and relieve my pain.\nAt this proud Friesland's sovereign such displeasure\nConceived, and entertained such high disdain,\nHe entered Holland, and the war began,\nIn which my kin were slaughtered to a man.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Besides, that both his puissance and his might\nAre such, as in our age are matched of few,\nSuch is in evil deeds his cunning sleight,\nHe laughs to scorn what wit and force can do.\nStrange arms he bears, unknown to any wight,\nSave him, of the ancient nations or the new:\nA hollow iron, two yards long, whose small\nChannel he loads with powder and a ball</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"He, where 'tis closed behind, in the iron round,\nTouches with fire a vent, discerned with pain;\nIn guise that skilful surgeon tries his ground,\nWhere need requires that he should breathe a vein.\nWhence flies the bullet with such deafening sound,\nThat bolt and lightening from the hollow cane\nAppear to dart, and like the passing thunder,\nBurn what they smite, beat-down or rend asunder.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Twice broken, he our armies overthrew\nWith this device, my gentle brethren slain;\nThe first the shot in our first battle slew,\nReaching his heart, through broken plate and chain;\nThe other in the other onset, who\nWas flying from the fatal field in vain.\nThe ball his shoulder from a distance tore\nBehind, and issued from his breast before.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"My father next, defending on a day\nThe only fortress which he still possessed,\nThe others taken which about it lay,\nWas sent alike to his eternal rest:\nWho going and returning, to purvey\nWhat lacked, as this or that occasion pressed,\nWas aimed at from afar, in privy wise,\nAnd by the traytour struck between the eyes.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"And I remaining, sire and brethren dead,\nThe isle of Holland's only heir, the king\nOf Friesland, who by the desire was led\nOf better there his power establishing,\nTo me, and also to my people said,\nI peace and quiet to my state might bring,\nWould I (when I before would not accord)\nNow take his son Arbantes for my lord.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"I, not so much for deadly hate I bear\nTo him and all his kindred, by whose spite\nMy sire and both my brothers slaughtered were,\nMy country sacked and waste, as that the knight\nI would not wrong, to whom I fealty sware,\nAnd had my solemn word already plight\nThat me to wedlock man should woo in vain,\nTill he to Holland should return from Spain.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"For one ill-born, a hundred yet behind,\nWill bear (replied to hazard all content, ) \n\n— Slain, burnt alive, to let them to the wind\nScatter my ashes, rather than consent. —\nMy people seek to move my stedfast mind,\nBy prayer and by protest, from this intent;\nAnd threat to yield my city up and me,\nLest all be lost through my obduracy.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"When in my fixt and firm resolve they read,\nThat prayer and protest are alike in vain;\nMy town and me, with Friesland's king agreed,\nSurrendered, as they vowed, my vassal train.\nNot doing by me any shameful deed,\nMe he assured of life and of domain,\nSo I would soften my obdurate mood,\nAnd be to wed with his Arbantes wooed.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"I who would have consented to forego\nMy life to scape from him, reflection made,\nThat, save I first avenged myself, all woe\nEndured, would be by this regret outweighed.\n— Long time I muse, and to my misery know,\n'Tis only simulation which can aid.\nNot simple willingness, I feign desire,\nTo win his grace, and have him for my sire.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"  Mid many in my father's service, I\nSelect two brothers fitted for my view,\nOf valiant heart and great ability\nBut more approved for truth, as followers, who\nBred in my father's court, from infancy\nHad with myself grown up; the brothers two\nSo wholly bound to me, they would have thought\nMy safety with their lives was cheaply bought.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"To them I tell my project, and the pair\nOf brethren promise me their faithful aid:\nTo Flanders this, a pinnace to prepare,\nI sent, and that with me in Holland stayed.\nNow, while both foreigners and natives were,\nOf Friesland's kingdom, to our nuptials prayed,\nBireno in Biscay (the tidings went)\nFor Holland had equipt an armament.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Since on the issue of the earliest fray,\nWhen in the rout one hapless brother fell,\nI had dispatched a courier to Biscay,\nWho the sad news should to Bireno tell:\nWhile he toils sore his squadron to array,\nProud Friesland's arms our wretched remnant quell.\nBireno, who knew nought of this, had weighed,\nAnd with his barks put forth to bring us aid.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XL</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"These tidings told to Friesland's monarch, he\nConfiding to his son the wedding's care,\nTo meet Bireno's squadron puts to sea,\nAnd (so chance willed burns, sinks, or routs them there, ) \n\nLeading him off into captivity; —\nBut none to us as yet the tidings bear.\nThis while I to the amorous youth am wed,\nWho, when the sun sought his, would seek my bed.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Behind the curtains, I had hid the tried\nAnd faithful follower, of whom I said,\nWho moved not till the bridegroom he descried,\nYet waited not till he in bed was laid:\nBut raised a hatchet, and so well applied\nBehind the stripling's head the ponderous blade,\nOf speech and life it reft him; I, who note\nThe deed, leap lightly up and cut his throat.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"As falls the bullock upon shamble-sill,\nThus fell the ill-starred stripling, in despite\nOf king Cymosco, worst among the ill;\nSo was the impious king of Friesland hight\nWho did my brothers and my father kill,\nAnd, in my state to found a better right;\nIn wedlock wished to join me with his son,\nHaply to slay me when his end was won.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Ere new disturbance interrupt the deed,\nTaking what costliest was and lightest weighed,\nMe my companion by a chord, with speed,\nDrops from a window, where with boat purveyed\nIn Flanders (as related for my need, ) \n\nHis brother, watchful of our motions, stayed:\nWe dip the oar, we loose the sail, and driven\nBy both, escape, as was the will of Heaven.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"The daring feat achieved, I cannot say\nIf Friesland's king more sorrowed for his son,\nOr raged at me: he there arrived, the day\nEnsuing, where the dreadful deed was done,\nProud he returned, both he and his array,\nOf the duke taken, and the victory won:\nAnd thought to feast and nuptials he was bound,\nBut in his home all grief and darkness found.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"His pity for his son, the hate he fed\nTowards me, torment the father day and night;\nBut as lamenting will not raise the dead,\nAnd vengeance is a vent for smothered spite;\nThat portion of his thoughts, which should have led\nThe king, to ease by sighs his troubled sprite,\nNow willingly takes counsel with his hate,\nTo seize me, and his vengeance satiate.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"All known or said to by my friends, or who\nWere friends of those that, chosen from my train,\nHad aided me the deadly deed to do,\nTheir goods and chattels burnt, were doomed or slain:\nAnd he had killed Bireno, since he knew\nNo other trouble could inflict such pain;\nBut that he, saving him in malice, thought\nHe had a net wherewith I might be caught.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Yet him a cruel proposition made,\nGranting a year his purpose to complete;\nCondemned to privy death, till then delayed,\nSave in that time, through force or through deceit,\nHe by his friends' and kindred's utmost aid,\nDoing or plotting, me from my retreat\nConveyed into his prisons; so that he\nCan only saved by my destruction be.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"What for his safety could be done, behold,\nShort of my own destruction, had been tried.\nSix towns I had in Flanders: these I sold,\nAnd (great or small the produce set aside)\nA part of it, to wily persons told,\nThat it to tempt his guards might be applied;\nThe rest of it dispensed to move and arm\nGermans or English, to the miscreant's harm.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"My agents, whether they their trust betrayed,\nOr that they could in truth perform no more,\nMe with vain words instead of help have paid,\nAnd scorn me, having drained my scanty store:\nAnd now the term is nigh expired, when aid,\nWhether of open force or treasured ore,\nNo longer will arrive in time to save\nMy cherished spouse from torture and the grave.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>L</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Through him, from me was my dominion rent;\nThrough him, my father and my brethren slain;\nThrough him, the little treasure left me, spent\n(What served alone existence to sustain)\nTo rescue him, in cruel durance pent;\nNor other means to succour him remain;\nSave I, to liberate him from prison, go\nAnd yield myself to such a cruel foe.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"If nothing more be left me then to try,\nNor other way for his escape appear,\nThan his with this my wretched life to buy,\nThis life I gladly will lay down: one fear\nAlone molests me; and it is that I\nCan never my conditions make so clear,\nAs to assure me, that with new deceit,\nMe, when his prey, the tyrant will not cheat.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"I fear, when I shall be in captive plight,\nAnd he has put all tortures upon me,\nHe may not loose Bireno, and the knight\nHave not to thank me for his liberty:\nLike perjured king, and full of foul despite,\nWho with my murder will not satiate be;\nBut by Bireno neither less nor more\nWill do, than he had done by me before.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"The occasion now that I confer with you,\nAnd tell my case to all who seek the land,\nBoth lords and knights, is with the single view,\nThat taking counsel of so large a band,\nSome one may indicate assurance due,\nThat when before the cruel king I stand,\nNo longer he Bireno shall detain;\nNor, after I am killed, the duke be slain.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Warrior to went with me, I in my need,\nWhen I shall be to Friesland given, have prayed;\nBut so he promise, that the exchange agreed\nShall be between us in such manner made,\nThat from his bonds Bireno shall be freed\nWhen I am to the monarch's hands conveyed:\nThus I, when I am slain, shall die content,\nWho to my spouse shall life by death have lent.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Not to this day have chanced upon a wight\nWho on his faith will give me warranty,\nThat if the king refuse to loose the knight,\nWhen I am offered, from captivity,\nHe will not suffer that in my despite\n(So feared those weapons! I shall taken be. ) \n\nSo feared those weapons, upon every hand!\nWhich, howsoever thick, no plates withstand.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Now, if as strong Herculean port and bold\nAppear to vouch, such worth to you belong;\nAnd you believe to give me or withhold\nIs in your power, should he intend me wrong;\nBe with me, when committed to his hold,\nSince I shall fear not, in your convoy strong,\nWhen you are with me, that my lord, though I\nBe after slain, shall by his order die.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Here her discourse, wherewith were interposed\nLoud sobs, the lady ceased, and silent stood:\nOrlando, when her lips the damsel closed,\nWhose ready will ne'er halts in doing good,\nBriefly to her replies, as indisposed\nTo idle speeches of his natural mood:\nBut plights his solemn word, that better aid\nShe should from him receive than that she prayed.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>'Tis not his scheme to place her in the hand\nOf her foul foe, to have Bireno freed;\nHe will save both the lovers, if his brand\nAnd wonted valour fail him not at need.\nEmbarked that very day, they put from land\nWith a clear sky and prosperous wind to speed.\nThe county hastes in his impatient heat,\nEager to reach that isle, the monster's seat.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Through the still deeps, on this or the other side,\nThe skipper veered his canvas to the wind:\nThis isle, and that of Zealand, they descried,\nOne seen before, and one shut in behind.\nThe third day, from the harboured vessel's side,\nIn Holland, Roland disembarks, not joined\nBy the complaining dame; whom to descend\nHe will not till she hear that tyrant's end.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Armed at all points, the county passed ashore,\nBorne on a horse 'twixt brown and black, the breed\nOf Denmark, but in Flanders nurtured, more\nEsteemed for weight and puissance than for speed:\nFor when the paladin embarked before,\nIn Brittany he left the gallant steed,\nHis Brigliador; so nimble and so fair,\nThat but Bayardo could with him compare.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Orlando fares to Dordrecht, where he views\nA numerous squadron, which the gate maintain;\nAs well, because suspicion still ensues\nOn the foundation of a new domain;\nAs that before they had received the news,\nThat out of Zealand, backed with armed train,\nWas coming with a fleet of many sail,\nA cousin of the lord here pent in jail.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>One, good Orlando to the monarch's ear\nBade bear a message, `that an errant knight\nOh him would prove himself, with sword and spear;\nBut would lay down this pact before the fight: —\nThat if the king unhorsed the cavalier,\nHer who Arbantes slew, he, as his right,\nShould have, that, at the cavalier's command,\nWas ready for delivery to his hand;</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>`And willed the king should on his side agree,\nIf him the knight in combat overbore,\nForthwith released from his captivity,\nBireno to full freedom to restore.'\nTo him the footman does his embassy;\nBut he, who knightly worth or courteous lore\nHad never known, directs his whole intent\nThe count by treacherous fraud to circumvent.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>He hopes as well, if he the warrior slay,\nTo have the dame, whom, so aggrieved, he hates,\nIf in the knight's disposal, and the say\nOf that strange knight, the footman well relates.\nHence thirty men dispatched by other way\nThan to the portal led, where Roland waits;\nWho with a long and privy circuit wind,\nAnd come upon the paladin behind.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>He all this while had made his guard delay\nThe knight with words, till horse and foot he spied\nArrived, where he this ambuscade did lay;\nWhen from the gate he with as many hied:\nAs is the practised hunter's wonted way,\nTo circle wood and beasts on every side:\nAs nigh Volana, with his sweeping nets,\nThe wary fisher fish and pool besets.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>'Tis thus the king bars every path which lies\nFree for the warrior's flight, with armed train:\nHe him alive, and in no other guise,\nWould have, and lightly hopes his end to gain;\nNor for the earthly thunderbolt applies,\nThat had so many and so many slain:\nWhich here he deems would serve his purpose ill,\nWhere he desires to take and not to kill.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>As wary fowler, bent on greater prey,\nWisely preserves alive the game first caught,\nThat by the call-bird and his cheating play,\nMore may within the circling net be brought;\nSuch cunning art Cymosco would assay:\nBut Roland would not be so lightly bought;\nLike them by the first toil that springs betrayed;\nAnd quickly forced the circle which was made.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Where he perceives the assailants thickest stand,\nHe rests his lance, and sticks in his career\nFirst one and afterwards another, and\nAnother, and another, who appear\nOf paste; till six he of the circling band\nOf foes impales upon a single spear;\nA seventh left out, who by the push is slain,\nSince the clogged weapon can no more contain.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>No otherwise, upon the further shore\nOf fosse or of canal, the frogs we spy,\nBy cautious archer, practised in his lore,\nSmote and transfixed the one the other nigh;\nUpon the shaft, until it hold no more,\nFrom barb to feathers full, allowed to lie.\nThe heavy lance Orlando from him flung,\nAnd to close combat with his faulchion sprung.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The lance now broke, his sword the warrior drew,\nThat sword which never yet was drawn in vain,\nAnd still with cut or thrust some soldier slew;\nNow horse, now footman of the tyrant's train.\nAnd, ever where he dealt a stroke, changed blue,\nYellow, green, white and black, to crimson stain.\nCymosco grieves, when most his need require,\nNot to have now his hollow cane and fire;</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And with loud voice and menacing command\nBids these be brought, but ill his followers hear;\nFor those who have found safety of his band,\nTo issue from the city are in fear.\nHe, when he sees them fly on either hand,\nWould fly as well from that dread cavalier;\nMakes for the gate, and would the drawbridge lift,\nBut the pursuing county is too swift.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The monarch turns his back, and leaves the knight\nLord of the drawbridge and of either gate.\nThanks to his swifter steed, the rest in flight\nHe passes: good Orlando will not wait\n(Intent the felon, not his band, to smite)\nUpon the vulgar herd to wreck his hate.\nBut his slow horse seems restive; while the king's,\nMore nimble, flies as if equipt with wings.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>From street to street, before the count he made;\nAnd vanished clean; but after little stay,\nCame with new arms, with tube and fire purveyed;\nWhich, at his hest, this while his men convey.\nAnd posted at a corner, he waylaid:\nHis foe, as hunter watches for his prey,\nIn forest, with armed dogs and spear, attending\nThe boar in fury from the hill descending,</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Who rends the branch and overthrows the stone;\nAnd wheresoe'er he turns his haughty front,\nAppears (so loud the deafening crash and groan)\nAs if he were uprending wood and mount,\nIntent to make him his bold deed atone,\nCymosco at the pass expects the count;\nAs soon as he appears, with ready light\nTouches the hole, and fires upon the knight.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Behind, the weapon flames in lightning's guise,\nAnd vents the thunder from before; the ground\nShakes under foot and city wall; the skies\nThe fearful echo all about rebound.\nThe burning bolt with sudden fury flies,\nNot sparing aught which in its course is found.\nHissing and whizzing through the skies it went;\nBut smote not, to the assassin's foul intent.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Whether it was his great desire to kill\nThat baron, or his hurry made him fail,\nOr trembling heart, like leaf which flutters still,\nMade hand and arm together flinch and quail;\nOr that it was not the Creator's will\nThe church so soon her champion should bewail;\nThe glancing stroke his courser's belly tore,\nOutstretched on earth, from thence to rise no more.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>To earth fall horse and rider: this the knight\nScarce touched; the other thundering pressed the plain:\nFor the first rose so ready and so light,\nHe from the fall seemed breath and force to gain.\nAs African Anteus, in the fight,\nRose from the sand with prouder might and main;\nSo when Orlando touched the ground, to view\nHe rose with doubled force and vigour new.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>He who has seen the thunder, from on high,\nDischarged by Jove with such a horrid sound,\nDescend where nitre, coal, and sulphur lie,\nStored up for use in magazine profound,\nWhich scarce has reached — but touched it, ere the sky\nIs in a flame, as well as burning ground,\nFirm walls are split, and solid marbles riven,\nAnd flying stones cast up as high as heaven;</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Let him imagine, when from earth he sprung,\nSuch was the semblance of the cavalier;\nWho moved in mode to frighten Mars among\nThe Gods, so fierce and horrid was his cheer.\nAt this dismay'd, the King of Friesland stung\nHis horse, and turned his rein, to fly the peer:\nBut fierce Orlando was upon his foe\nFaster than arrow flies from bended bow:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And, what before he could not, when possest\nOf his good courser, now afoot will do.\nHis speed outgoes all thought in every breast,\nExceeds all credence, save in those who view.\nThe tyrant shortly joined, he on the crest\nSmote at his head so well, he cleft it through;\nAnd to the neck divided by the blow,\nSent it, to shake its last on earth below.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Lo!  in the frighted city other sound\nWas heard to rise, and other crash of brands,\nFrom troop, who, thither in his guidance bound,\nFollowed Bireno's cousin from his lands:\nWho, since the unguarded gates he open found,\nInto the city's heart had poured his bands;\nWhere the bold paladin had struck such fear,\nHe without let might scour it far and near.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>In rout the people fly, who cannot guess\nWho these may be, or what the foes demand:\nBut, when this man and that by speech and dress\nAs Zealand-men distinguishes the band,\nCarte blanche they proffer, and the chief address,\nBidding him range them under his command;\nAgainst the Frieslanders to lend him aid,\nWho have their duke in loathsome prison stayed.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>To Friesland's king that people hatred bore\nWith all his following: who their ancient lord\nHad put to death, and who by them yet more,\nAs evil and rapacious, was abhorred.\nOrlando interposed with kindly lore,\nAs friend of both, the parties to accord:\nBy whom, so joined, no Frieslander was left\nBut was of life or liberty bereft.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>They would not wait to seek the dungeon-key,\nBut breaking-down the gate, their entrance made;\nBireno to the count with courtesy\nAnd grateful thanks the service done repaid.\nThence they, together with large company,\nWent where Olympia in her vessel stayed:\nFor so was the expecting lady hight,\nTo whom that island's crown belonged of right.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>She who had thither good Orlando brought,\nNot hoping that he would have thriven so well;\n— Enough for her, if by her misery bought,\nHer spouse were rescued from the tyrant's cell! —\nHer, full of love and loyal homage, sought\nThe people one and all:  Twere long to tell\nHow she caressed Bireno, he the maid, —\nWhat thanks both lovers to the county paid.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The people, throned in her paternal reign,\nReplace the injured dame, and fealty swear:\nShe on the duke, to whom in solid chain\nLove with eternal knot had linked the fair,\nThe empire of herself and her domain\nConferred: He, called away by other care,\nLeft in the cousin's guardian care this while\nHis fortresses, and all the subject isle.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Since he to visit Zealand's duchy planned,\nHis faithful consort in his company;\nAnd thence, upon the king of Friesland's land,\nWould try his fortune (as he said), for he\nA pledge, he rated highly, had in hand,\nWhich seemed of fair success the warranty,\nThe daughter of the king: who here forsaken,\nWith many others had been prisoner taken.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>To a younger brother, her, the duke pretends,\nTo be conjoined in wedlock, he conveyed.\nThe Roman senator thence parting wends\nUpon the very day Bireno weighed;\nBut he to nothing else his hand extends\nOf all the many, many prized made,\nSave to that engine, found amid the plunder,\nWhich in all points I said resembled thunder.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Not with intent, in his defence to bear\nWhat he had taken, of the prize possest;\nFor he still held it an ungenerous care\nTo go with vantage on whatever quest:\nBut with design to cast the weapon where\nIt never more should living wight molest;\nAnd, what was appertaining to it, all\nBore off as well, the powder and the ball.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XC</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And thus, when of the tidesway he was clear,\nAnd in the deepest sea his bark descried,\nSo that no longer distant signs appear\nOf either shore on this or the other side,\nHe seized the tube, and said: \"That cavalier\nMay never vail through thee his knightly pride,\nNor base be rated with a better foe,\nDown with thee to the darkest deep below!</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XCI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"O loathed, O cursed piece of enginery,\nCast in Tartarean bottom, by the hand\nOf Beelzebub, whose foul malignity\nThe ruin of this world through thee has planned!\nTo hell, from whence thou came, I render thee.\"\nSo said, he cast away the weapon: fanned\nMeanwhile, with flowing sheet, his frigate goes,\nBy wind, which for the cruel island blows.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XCII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Such was the paladin's desire to explore\nIf in the place his missing lady were;\nWhom he prefers the united world before,\nNor can an hour of life without her bear.\nHe fears, if he set foot on Ireland's shore,\nSome other chance may interrupt him there:\nSo that he after have in vain to say,\n\"Why hasted I no faster on my way?\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XCIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Nor he in England nor in Ireland port\nWill make, nor on the coast that's opposite.\nBut let him go, the naked archer's sport,\nSore smitten in the heart! — ere I indite\nYet more of him, to Holland I resort,\nAnd you to hear me company invite.\nFor well I wot that you as well as me\n'Twould grieve that bridal should without us be.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XCIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Sumptuous and fair the bridal there is made;\nBut neither yet so sumptuous nor so fair\nAs it will be in Zealand, it is said:\nBut 'tis not my design you should repair\nThither; since by new accidents delayed\nThe feast will be, of which be it my care,\nIn other strain, the tidings to report;\nIf you to hear that other strain resort.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 10"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Another love assails Bireno's breast,\nWho leaves one night Olympia on the shore.\nTo Logistilla's holy realm addressed,\nRogero goes, nor heeds Alcina more:\nHim, of that flying courser repossest,\nThe hippogryph on airy voyage bore:\nWhence he the good Rinaldo's levy sees,\nAnd next Angelica beholds and frees.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>I</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Of all the loves, of all fidelity\nYet proved, of all the constant hearts and true,\nOf all the lovers, in felicity\nOr sorrow faithful found, a famous crew,\nTo Olympia I would give the first degree\nRather than second: if this be not due,\nI well may say that hers no tale is told\nOf truer love, in present times or old.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>II</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And this she by so many proofs and clear,\nHad made apparent to the Zealand lord,\nNo woman's faith more certain could appear\nTo man, though he her open heart explored:\nAnd if fair truth such spirits should endear,\nAnd they in mutual love deserve reward,\nBireno as himself, nay, he above\nHimself, I say, should kind Olympia love.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>III</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Not only should he nevermore deceive\nHer for another, were that woman she\nWho so made Europe and wide Asia grieve,\nOr fairer yet, if one more fair there be;\nBut rather that quit her the light should leave,\nAnd what is sweet to taste, touch, hear, and see,\nAnd life and fame, and all beside; if aught\nMore precious can in truth be styled, or thought.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>IV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>If her Bireno loved, as she had loved\nBireno, if her love he did repay\nWith faith like hers, and still with truth unmoved,\nVeered not his shifting sail another way;\nOr ingrate for such service — cruel proved\nFor such fair love and faith, I now will say;\nAnd you with lips comprest and eye-brows bent,\nShall listen to the tale for wonderment;</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>V</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And when you shall have heard the impiety,\nWhich of such passing goodness was the meed,\nWoman take warning from this perfidy,\nAnd let none make a lover's word her creed.\nMindless that God does all things hear and see,\nThe lover, eager his desires to speed,\nHeaps promises and vows, aye prompt to swear,\nWhich afterwards all winds disperse in air.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>VI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The promises and empty vows dispersed\nIn air, by winds all dissipated go,\nAfter these lovers have the greedy thirst\nAppeased, with which their fevered palates glow.\nIn this example which I offer, versed,\nTheir prayers and tears to credit be more slow.\nCheaply, dear ladies mine, is wisdom bought\nBy those who wit at other's cost are taught.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>VII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Of those in the first flower of youth beware,\nWhose visage is so soft and smooth to sight:\nFor past, as soon as bred, their fancies are;\nLike a straw fire their every appetite.\nSo the keen hunter follows up the hare\nIn heat and cold, on shore, or mountain-height;\nNor, when 'tis taken, more esteems the prize;\nAnd only hurries after that which flies.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>VIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Such is the practise of these striplings who,\nWhat time you treat them with austerity,\nLove and revere you, and such homage do,\nAs those who pay their service faithfully;\nBut vaunt no sooner victory, than you\nFrom mistresses shall servants grieve to be;\nAnd mourn to see the fickle love they owed,\nFrom you diverted, and elsewhere bestowed.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>IX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>I not for this (for that were wrong opine ) \n\nThat you should cease to love; for you, without\nA lover, like uncultivated vine,\nWould be, that has no prop to wind about.\nBut the first down I pray you to decline,\nTo fly the volatile, inconstant rout;\nTo make your choice the riper fruits among,\nNor yet to gather what too long has hung.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>X</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>A daughter they have found (above was said)\nOf the proud king who ruled the Friesland state;\nThat with Bireno's brother was to wed,\nAs far as rumour tells; but to relate\nThe truth, a longing in Bireno bred\nThe sight of food so passing delicate;\nAnd he to talk his palate deemed would be,\nFor other's sake, a foolish courtesy.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The gentle damsel had not past fourteen,\nWas beautiful and fresh, and like a rose,\nWhen this first opening from its bud is seen,\nAnd with the vernal sun expands and grows.\nTo say Bireno loved the youthful queen\nWere little; with less blaze lit tinder glows,\nOr ripened corn, wherever envious hand\nOf foe amid the grain has cast a brand,</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Than that which on Bireno's bosom fed,\nAnd to his marrow burned; when, weeping sore\nThe fate of her unhappy father dead,\nHe saw her bathed in ceaseless tears deplore:\nAnd, as cold water, on the cauldron shed,\nShops short the bubbling wave, which boiled before;\nSo was the raging rife Olympia blew\nWithin his breast, extinguished by a new.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Nor feels Bireno mere satiety;\nHe loathes her so, he ill endures her sight;\nAnd, if his hope he long deferred, will die:\nFor other such his fickle appetite!\nYet till the day prefixed to satisfy\nHis fond desire, so feigns the wary knight,\nOlympia less to love than to adore\nHe seems, and but her pleasure to explore.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And if the other he too much caress,\nWho cannot but caress her, there are none\nSee evil in the deed, but rather guess\nIt is in pity, is in goodness done:\nSince to raise up and comfort in distress\nWhom Fortune's wheel beats down in changeful run,\nWas never blamed; with glory oftener paid;\n— So much the more, a young — a harmless maid.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Almighty God!  how fallible and vain\nIs human judgment, dimmed by clouds obscure!\nBireno's actions, impious and profane,\nBy others are reputed just and pure.\nAlready stooping to their oars, the train\nHave loosed his vessel from the port secure,\nAnd with the duke and his companions steer\nFor Zealand through the deep, with meery cheer.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Already Holland and its headlands all\nAre left astern, and now descried no more;\nSince to shun Friesland they to larboard hawl.\nAnd keep their course more nigh the Scottish shore:\nWhen they are overtaken by a squall,\nAnd drive three days the open sea before:\nUpon the third, when now, near eventide,\nA barren and unpeopled isle is spied.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>As soon as they were harboured in a hight,\nOlympia landed and the board was spread;\nShe there contented, with the faithless knight,\nSupt, unsuspecting any cause for dread.\nThence, with Bireno, where a tent was pight\nIn pleasant place, repaired, and went to bed.\nThe others of their train returned abroad,\nAnd rested in their ship, in haven moored.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The fear and late sea sorrow, which had weighed\nSo long upon the dame and broke her rest,\nThe finding herself safe in greenwood shade\nRemoved from noise, and, for her tranquil breast\n(Knowing her lover was beside her laid)\nNo further thoughts, no further cares molest,\nOlympia lap in slumber so profound,\nNo sheltered bear or dormouse sleeps more sound.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The lover false, who, hatching treason lies,\nStole from his bed in silence, when he knew\nShe slept: his clothes he in a bundle ties,\nNor other raiment on his body threw.\nThen issuing forth from the pavilion hies,\nAs if on new-born wings, towards his crew;\nWho, roused, unmoor without a cry, as he\nCommands, and loosen thence and put to sea.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Behind the land was left; and there to pine\nOlympia, who yet slept the woods among;\nTill from her gilded wheels the frosty rhine\nAurora upon earth beneath had flung;\nAnd the old woe, beside the tumbling brine,\nLamenting, halcyons mournful descant sung;\nWhen she, 'twixt sleep and waking, made a strain\nTo reach her loved Bireno, but in vain.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>She no one found: the dame her arm withdrew;\nShe tried again, yet no one found; she spread\nBoth arms, now here, now there, and sought anew;\nNow either leg; but yet no better sped.\nFear banished sleep; she oped her eyes: in view\nWas nothing: she no more her widowed bed\nWould keep, but from the couch in fury sprung,\nAnd headlong forth from the pavilion flung.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And seaward ran, her visage tearing sore,\nPresaging, and now certain of her plight:\nShe beat her bosom, and her tresses tore,\nAnd looked (the moon was shining if she might ) \n\nDiscover any thing beside the shore;\nNor, save the shore, was any thing in sight.\nShe calls Bireno, and the caverns round,\nPitying her grief, Bireno's name rebound.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>On the far shore there rose a rock; below\nScooped by the breaker's beating frequently:\nThe cliff was hollowed underneath, in show\nOf arch, and overhung the foaming sea.\nOlympia (MIND such vigour did bestow)\nSprang up the frowning crest impetuously,\nAnd, at a distance, stretched by favouring gale,\nThence saw her cruel lord's departing sail.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Saw it, or seemed to see: for ill her eyes,\nThings through the air, yet dim and hazy, view.\nShe falls, all-trembling, on the ground, and lies\nWith face than snow more cold and white in hue:\nBut when she has again found strength to rise,\nGuiding her voice towards the bark which flew,\nCalling with all her might, the unhappy dame\nCalls often on her cruel consort's name.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Where unavailing was the feeble note,\nShe wept and clapt her hands in agony.\n\"Without its freight,\" she cried, \"thy ship does float.\n— Where, cruel, dost thou fly so swiftly? — Me\nReceive as well: — small hinderance to thy boat,\nWhich bears my spirit, would my body be.\"\nAnd she her raiment waving in her hand,\nSigned to the frigate to return to land.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>But the loud wind which, sweeping ocean, bears\nThe faithless stripling's sail across the deep,\nBears off as well the shriek, and moan, and prayers\nOf sad Olympia, sorrowing on the steep.\nThrice, cruel to herself, the dame prepares\nFrom the high rock amid the waves to leap.\nBut from the water lifts at length her sight,\nAnd there returns where she had passed the night.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Stretched on the bed, upon her face she lay,\nBathing it with her tears.  \"Last night in thee\nTogether two found shelter,\" did she say;\n\"Alas!  why two together are not we\nAt rising?  False Bireno!  cursed day\nThat I was born!  What here remains to me\nTo do?  What can be done? — Alone, betrayed —\nWho will console me, who afford me aid?</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Nor man I see, nor see I work, which shows\nThat man inhabits in this isle; nor I\nSee ship, in which (a refuge from my woes),\nEmbarking, I from hence may hope to fly.\nHere shall I starve; nor any one to close\nMy eyes, or give me sepulture, be by,\nSave wolf perchance, who roves this wood, a tomb\nGive me, alas!  in his voracious womb.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"I live in terror, and appear to see\nRough bear or lion issue even now,\nOr tiger, from beneath the greenwood tree,\nOr other beast with teeth and claws: but how\nCan ever cruel beast inflict on me,\nO cruel beast, a fouler death than thou?\nEnough for them to slay me once!  while I\nAm made by thee a thousand deaths to die.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"But grant, e'en now, some skipper hither fare,\nWho may for pity bear me hence away;\nAnd that I so eschew wolf, lion, bear,\nTorture, and dearth, and every horrid way\nOf death; to Holland shall he take me, where\nFor thee is guarded fortilage and bay;\nOr take me to the land where I was born,\nIf this thou hast from me by treachery torn?</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Thou, with pretence, from me my state didst wrest\nOf our connection and of amity;\nAnd quickly of my land thy troops possest,\nTo assure the rule unto thyself.  Shall I\nReturn to Flanders where I sold the rest,\nThough little, upon which I lived, to buy\nThee needful succour and from prison bear?\nWretch, whither shall I go? — I know not where.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Can I to Friesland go, where I to reign\nAs queen was called, and this for thee forewent;\nWhere both my brethren and my sire were slain,\nAnd every other good from me was rent? —\nThee would I not, thou ingrate, with my pain\nReproach, not therefore deal thee punishment:\nAs well as I, the story dost thou know;\nNow, see the meed thou dost for this bestow!</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Oh!  may I but escape the wild corsair,\nNor taken be, and after sold for slave!\nRather than this may lion, wolf, or bear,\nTiger, or other beast, if fiercer rave,\nMe with his claws and rushes rend and tear,\nAnd drag my bleeding body to his cave.\"\nSo saying she her golden hair offends,\nAnd lock by lock the scattered tresses rends.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>She to the shore's extremest verge anew,\nTossing her head, with hair dishevelled, run;\nAnd seemed like maid beside herself, and who\nWas by ten fiends possessed, instead of one;\nOf like the frantic Hecuba, at view\nOf murdered Polydore, her infant son;\nFixed on a stone she gazed upon the sea,\nNor less than real stone seemed stone to be.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>But let her grieve till my return.  To show\nNow of the Child I wish: his weary way\nRogero, in the noon's intensest glow,\nTakes by the shore: the burning sunbeams play\nUpon the hill and thence rebound; below\nBoils the white sand; while heated with the ray,\nLittle is wanting in that journey dire,\nBut that the arms he wears are all on fire.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>While to the warrior thirst and labour sore,\nStill toiling through that heavy sand, as he\nPursued his path along the sunny shore,\nWere irksome and displeasing company,\nBeneath the shadow of a turret hoar,\nWhich rose beside the beach, amid the sea,\nHe found three ladies of Alcina's court,\nAs such distinguished by their dress and port.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Reclined on Alexandrian carpets rare\nThe ladies joyed the cool in great delight;\nAbout them various wines in vessels were,\nAnd every sort of comfit nicely dight;\nFast by, and sporting with the ripple there,\nLay, waiting on their needs, a pinnace light,\nUntil a breeze should fill her sail anew:\nFor then no breath upon the waters blew.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>They, who beheld along the shifting sand\nRogero wend, upon his way intent,\nAnd saw thirst figured on his lips, and scanned\nHis troubled visage, all with sweat besprent,\nBegan to pray, `on what he had in hand\nHe would not show his heart so deeply bent,\nBut that he in the cool and grateful shade\nWould rest his weary limbs, beside them laid.'</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>To hold the stirrup one approaching near,\nWould aid him to alight: the other bore\nA cup of chrystal to the cavalier,\nWith foaming wine, which raised his thirst the more;\nBut to the music of their speech no ear\nHe lent, who weened if he his way forbore\nFor anything, each lett would time supply\nTo Alcina to arrive, who now was nigh.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XL</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Now so saltpetre fine and sulphur pure,\nTouched with the fiery spark, blaze suddenly;\nNot so loud ocean raves, when the obscure\nWhirlwind descends and camps in middle sea,\nAs viewing thus the knight proceed secure\nUpon his journey, and aware that he\nScorns them, who yet believe they beauteous are,\nKindled the third of those three damsels fair.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>As loud as she could raise her voice, she said,\n\"Thou art not gentle, nor art thou a knight;\nAnd hast from other arms and horse conveyed:\nWhich never could be thine by better right.\nSo be thy theft, if well I guess, appaid\nBy death, which this may worthily requite!\nFoul thief, churl, haughty ingrate, may I thee\nBurned, gibbeted, or cut in quarters see!\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Beside all these and more injurious cries,\nWhich the proud damsel at the warrior throws,\nThough to her taunts Rogero nought replies,\nWho weens small fame from such a contest flows;\nShe with her sisters to the frigate hies,\nWhich waits them, and aboard the tender goes;\nAnd plying fast her oars, pursues the knight\nAlong the sandy beach, still kept in sight.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>On him with threat and curse she ever cried;\nWhose tongue collected still fresh cause for blame.\nMeanwhile, where to the lovelier fairy's side\nThe passage lay across a straight, he came;\nAnd there an ancient ferryman espied\nPut from the other shore with punctual aim,\nAs if forewarned and well prepared, the seer\nWaited the coming of the cavalier.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The ferryman put forth the Child to meet,\nTo bear him to a better shore rejoicing: he\nAppeared as all benign and all discreet,\nIf of the heart the face is warranty.\nGiving God thanks, Rogero took his seat\nAboard the bark, and passed the quiet sea,\nDiscoursing with that ancient pilot, fraught\nWith wisdom, and by long experience taught.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>He praised Rogero much, that he had fled\nIn time from false Alcina, and before\nTo him the dame had given the chalice dread,\nHer lover's final guerdon evermore.\nNext that he had to Logistilla sped,\nWhere he should duly witness holy lore,\nAnd beauty infinite and grace enjoy,\nWhich feed and nourish hearts they never cloy.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Her shall you, struck with wonderment, revere,\"\n(He said), \"when first you shall behold the fay;\nBut better contemplate her lofty cheer,\nAnd you no other treasure shall appay.\nIn this her love from other differs; fear\nAnd hope in other on the bosom prey:\nIn hers Desire demands not aught beside,\nAnd with the blessing seen is satisfied.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"You shall in nobler studies be professed,\nTutored by her, than bath and costly fare,\nSong, dance, and perfumes; as how fashioned best,\nYour thoughts may tower more high than hawks in air;\nAnd how some of the glory of the blest\nYou here may in the mortal body share.\"\nSo speaking, and yet distant from the shore,\nTo the safe bank approached the pilot hoar.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>When he beholds forth-issuing from the strand,\nA fleet of ships, which all towards him steer.\nWith these came wronged Alcina, with a band\nOf many vassals, gathered far and near;\nTo risk the ruin of herself and land,\nOr repossess the thing she held so dear.\nLove, no light cause, incites the dame aggrieved,\nNor less the bitter injury received.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Such choler she had never felt before\nAs that which now upon her bosom fed:\nAnd hence she made her followers ply the oar\nTill the white foam on either bank was shed\nThe deafening noise and din o'er sea and shore,\nBy echo every where repeated, spread,\n\"Now — now, Rogero, bare the magic shield,\nOr in the strife be slain, or basely yield\":</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>L</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Thus Logistilla's pilot; and beside,\nSo saying, seized the pouch, wherein was dight\nThe buckler, and the covering torn aside,\nExposed to open view the shining light.\nThe enchanted splendor, flashing far and wide,\nSo sore offends the adversaries' sight,\nThey from their vessels drop amazed and blind,\nTumbling from prow before, and poop behind.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>One who stood sentry on the citadel\nDescried the navy of the invading dame,\nAnd backwards rang the castle larum-bell,\nWhence speedy succours to the haven came.\nThe artillery rained like storm, whose fury fell\nOn all who would Rogero scathe and shame:\nSo that such aid was brought him in the strife,\nAs saved the warrior's liberty and life.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Four ladies are arrived upon the strand,\nThither by Logistilla sped in haste:\nLeagued with the valiant Anrondica stand\nFronesia sage, Dicilla good, and chaste\nSofrosina, who, as she has in had\nMore than the others, 'mid the foremost placed,\nConspicuous flames.  Forth issues from the fort\nA matchless host, and files towards the port.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Beneath the castle, safe from wind and swell,\nOf many ships and stout, a squadron lay;\nWhich, in the harbour, at a sound from bell, —\nA word, were fit for action, night or day;\nAnd thus by land and sea was battle, fell\nAnd furious, waged on part of either fay:\nWhence was Alcina's realm turned upside down,\nOf which she had usurped her sister's crown.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Oh!  of how many battles the success\nIs different from what was hoped before!\nNot only failed the dame to repossess,\nAs thought, her lover flying from her shore,\nBut out of ships, even now so numberless,\nThat ample ocean scarce the navy bore,\nFrom all her vessels, to the flames a prey,\nBut with one bark escaped the wretched fay.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Alcina flies; and her sad troop around\nRouted and taken, burnt or sunk, remains\nTo have lost Rogero, sorrow more profound\nWakes in her breast than all her other pains;\nAnd she in bitter tears for ever drowned,\nOf the Child's loss by night and day complains;\nAnd bent to end her woes, with many a sigh,\nOften laments her that she cannot die.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>No fairy dies, or can, while overhead\nThe sun shall burn, or heaven preserve their stile,\nOr Clotho had been moved to cut her thread,\nTouched by such grief; or, as on funeral pile\nFair Dido, she beneath the steel had bled;\nOr, haply, like the gorgeous Queen of Nile,\nIn mortal slumber would have closed her eye:\nBut fairies cannot at their pleasure die.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Return we, where eternal fame is due,\nLeaving Alcina in her trouble sore:\nI speak of valorous Rogero, who\nHad disembarked upon the safer shore.\nHe turned his back upon the waters blue,\nGiving God thanks for all with pious lore;\nAnd on dry ground now landed, made repair\nTowards the lofty castle planted there.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Than this a stronger or more bright in show\nWas never yet before of mortal sight,\nOr after, viewed; with stones the ramparts glow\nMore rich than carbuncle or diamond bright.\nWe of like gems discourse not here below,\nAnd he who would their nature read aright\nMust thither speed: none such elsewhere, I ween,\nExcept perhaps in heaven above, are seen.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>What gives to them superiority\nO'er every other sort of gem, confessed,\nIs, man in these his very soul may see;\nHis vices and his virtues see expressed.\nHence shall he after heed no flattery,\nNor yet by wrongful censure be depressed.\nHis form he in the lucid mirror eyes,\nAnd by the knowledge of himself grows wise.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Their rays, which imitate the sunshine, fill\nAll round about with such a flood of light,\nThat he who has them, Phoebus, may at will\nCreate himself a day, in thy despite.\nNor only marvellous the gems; the skill\nOf the artificer and substance bright\nSo well contend for mastery, of the two,\n'Tis hard to judge where preference is due.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>On arches raised, whereon the firmament\nSeemed to repose as props, so fair in show\nAre lovely gardens, and of such extent,\nAs even would be hard to have below.\nClustering 'twixt lucid tower or battlement,\nGreen odoriferous shrubs are seen to grow,\nWhich through the summer and the winter shoot,\nAnd teem with beauteous blossom and ripe fruit.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Never in any place such goodly tree\nIs grown, except within these gardens fine;\nOr rose, or violet of like quality,\nLilies, or amaranth, or jessamine.\nElsewhere it seems as if foredoomed to be\nBorn with one sun, to live and to decline,\nUpon its widowed stalk the blossom dies,\nSubject to all the changes of the skies.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>But here the verdure still is permanent,\nStill permanent the eternal blossoms are;\nNot that kind nature, in her government,\nSo nicely tempers here the genial air,\nBut that, unneeding any influence lent\nBy planet, Logistilla's zeal and care\nEver keep fast (what may appear a thing\nImpossible her own perpetual spring. ) \n</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>That such a gentle lord had sought her rest,\nDid much the prudent Logistilla please,\nAnd she commanded he should be carest,\nAnd all should seek to do him courtesies.\nSometime had Sir Astolpho been her guest,\nWhom with a joyful heart Rogero sees.\nThere in few days resorted all the crew,\nChanged by Melissa to their shapes anew.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>When they a day or more their weariness\nHad eased, Rogero sought the prudent fay;\nWith him the duke Astolpho, who no less\nDesired to measure back his western way.\nMelissa was for both embassadress,\nAnd for the warlike pair, with humble say\nTo favour, warn and help them, prayed the dame;\nSo that they might return from whence they came.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"I\" (said the fay \"will think upon this need, ) \n\nAnd in two days the pair will expedite.\"\nThen thought how good Rogero she should speed.\nAnd afterwards how aid the English knight.\nShe wills the first shall, on the griffin steed,\nTo the Aquitanian shores direct his flight;\nBut first will fashion for the flying-horse\nA bit, to guide him and restrain his course.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>She shows him what to do, if he on high\nWould make him soar, or down to earth would bring,\nAnd what, would he in circles make him fly,\nOr swiftly speed, or pause upon the wing.\nAnd all that skilful horsemen use to try\nUpon plain ground, beneath her tutoring,\nRogero learned in air, and gained dominion\nOver the griffin-steed of soaring pinion.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>When at all points Rogero was prepared,\nHe bade farewell to the protecting fay,\nFor ever to the loving knight endeared,\nAnd issued from her realm upon his way.\nI first of him, who on his journey fared\nIn happy hour, and afterwards shall say\nOf the English knight, who spent more time and pain\nSeeking the friendly court of Charlemagne.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Rogero thence departs; but as before\nTakes not the way he took in his despite,\nWhen him above the sea the courser bore,\nAnd seldom was the land beneath in sight.\nBut taught to make him beat his wings and soar,\nHere, there, as liked him best, with docile flight,\nReturning, he another path pursued;\nAs Magi erst, who Herod's snare eschewed.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Borne hither, good Rogero, leaving Spain,\nHad sought, in level line, the Indian lands,\nWhere they are watered by the Eastern main;\nWhere the two fairies strove with hostile bands.\nHe now resolved to visit other reign\nThan that where Aeolus his train commands;\nAnd finish so the round he had begun,\nCircling the world beneath him like the sun.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Here the Catay, and there he Mangiane,\nPassing the great Quinsay beheld; in air\nAbove Imavus turned, and Sericane\nLeft on the right; and thence did ever bear\nFrom the north Scythians to the Hyrcanian main:\nSo reached Sarmatia's distant land; and, where\nEurope and Asia's parted climes divide,\nRuss, Prussian, he and Pomeranian spied.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Although the Child by every wish was pressed\nQuickly to seek his Bradamant, yet he\nWith taste of roving round the world possest,\nWould not desist from it, till Hungary\nHe had seen; and Polacks, Germans, and the rest\nShould in his wide extended circuit see,\nInhabiting that horrid, northern land;\nAnd came at last to England's farthest strand.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Yet think not, sir, that in so long a flight,\nThe warrior is for ever on the wing.\nWho lodges, housed in tavern every night,\nAs best as can, through his capacious ring.\nSo nights and days he passes: such delight\nProspects to him of land and ocean bring.\nArrived one morn nigh London-town, he stopt;\nAnd over Thames the flying courser dropt.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Where he in meadows to the city nigh\nSaw troops of men at arms, and footmen spread;\nWho, to the drum and trumpet marching by,\nDivided into goodly bands, were led\nBefore Rinaldo, flower of chivalry;\nHe that (if you remember it was said ) \n\nTo have been sent by Charlemagne, and made\nHis envoy to these parts in search of aid.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Rogero came exactly as the show\nOf that fair host was made without the town,\nAnd of a knight the occasion sought to know;\nBut from the griffin-horse first lighted down:\nAnd he who courteous was, informed him how\nOf kingdoms holding of the British crown,\nEnglish, Scotch, Irish, and the Islands nigh,\nThose many banners were, upreared on high:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And added, having ended this display\nOf arms, the troops would file towards the strand,\nWhere vessels anchored in the harbour lay,\nWaiting to bear them to another land.\n\"The French beseiged, rejoice in this array,\nAnd hope (he said deliverance through the band. ) \n\nBut that I may of all inform you well,\nI of each troop shall separately tell.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Lo!  where yon mighty banner planted stands,\nWhich pards and flower-de-luces does unfold,\nThat our great captain to the wind expands,\nUnder whose ensign are the rest enrolled:\nThe warrior's name, renowned throughout these lands,\nIs Leonetto, flower of all the bold;\nLancaster's duke, and nephew to the king,\nValiant in war, and wise in counselling.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"That next the royal gonfalon, which stirred\nBy fluttering wind, is borne towards the mount,\nWhich on green field, three pinions of a bird\nBears agent, speaks Sir Richard, Warwick's count.\nThe Duke of Gloucester's blazon is the third,\nTwo antlers of a stag, and demi-front;\nThe Duke of Clarence shows a torch, and he\nIs Duke of York who bears that verdant tree.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Upon the Duke of Norfolk's gonfalon\nYou see a lance into three pieces broke;\nThe thunder on the Earl of Kent's; upon\nPembroke's a griffin; underneath a yoke;\nIn Essex's, conjoined, two snakes are shown:\nBy yonder lifted balance is bespoke\nThe Duke of Suffolk; and Northumbria's Earl\nA garland does on azure field unfurl.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Arundel's Earl is yonder cavalier,\nWhose banner bears a foundering bark!  In sight\nThe next, is Berkeley's noble Marquis; near\nAre March and Richmond's Earls: the first on white\nShows a cleft mount; a palm the second peer;\nA pine amid the waves the latter knight.\nThe next of Dorset and Southampton's town,\nAre earls; this bears a car, and that a crown.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"The valiant Raymond, Earl of Devon, bears\nThe hawk, which spreads her wings above her nest;\nWhile or and sable he of Worcester wears:\nDerby's a dog, a bear is Oxford's crest.\nThere, as his badge, a cross of chrystal rears\nBath's wealthy prelate, camped among the rest.\nThe broken seat on dusky field, next scan,\nOf Somerset's good duke, Sir Ariman.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Forty-two thousand muster in array,\nThe men at arms and mounted archers there.\nBy a hundred I misreckon not, or they,\nThe fighting footmen, twice as many are.\nThose ensigns yellow, brown, and green, survey,\nAnd that striped blue and black.  The foot repair\nEach to his separate flag where these are spread;\nBy Godfrey, Henry, Hermant, Edward, led.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"The first is the Duke of Buckingham; and he,\nThe next, is Henry, Earl of Salisbury;\nOld Hermant Aberga'nny hold in fee,\nThat Edward is the Earl of Shrewsbury.\nIn those who yonder lodge, the English see\nCamped eastward; and now westward turn your eye,\nWhere you shall thirty thousand Scots, a crew\nLed by their monarch's son, Zerbino, view.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"The lion 'twixt two unicorns behold\nUpon the standard of the Scottish king!\nWhich has a sword of silver in its hold.\nThere camps his son: of all his following\nIs none so beauteous: nature broke the mould\nIn which she cast him, after fashioning\nHer work: Is none in whom such chivalry\nAnd valour shines.  The Duke of Rothsay he!</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Behold the Earl of Huntley's flag display\nUpon an azure field a gilded bar:\nIn that a leopard in the toils survey,\nThe bearing of the noble Duke of Mar.\nWith many birds, and many colours gay,\nSee Alcabrun's, a valiant man in war;\nWho neither duke, nor count, nor marquis hight,\nIs in his savage country first of right.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"The Duke of Strathforth shows the bird, who strains\nHis daring eyes to keep the sun in view;\nThe Earl Lurcanio, that in Angus reigns,\nA bull, whose flanks are torn by deerhounds two.\nSee there the Duke of Albany, who stains\nHis ensign's field with colours white and blue.\nThe Earl of Buchan next his banner bears,\nIn which a dragon vert a vulture tears.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Herman, the lord of Forbes, conducts that band,\nAnd stripes his gonfalon with black and white;\nWith Errol's earl upon his better hand,\nWho on a field of green displays a light.\nNow see the Irish, next the level land,\nInto two squadrons ordered for the fight.\nKildare's redoubted earl commands the first;\nLord Desmond leads the next, in mountains nursed.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"A burning pine by Kildare is displayed;\nBy Desmond on white field a crimson bend.\nNor only England, Scotland, Ireland, aid\nKing Charlemagne; but to assist him wend\nThe Swede and Norse, and succours are conveyed\nFrom Thule, and the farthest Iceland's end.\nAll lands that round them lie, in fine, increase\nHis host, by nature enemies to peace.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Issued from cavern and from forest brown,\nThey sixteen thousand are, or little less;\nVisage, legs, arms, and bosom overgrown\nWith hair, like beasts.  Lo!  yonder, where they press\nAbout a standard white, the level down\nOf lances seems a bristling wilderness.\nSuch Moray's flag, the savage squadron's head,\nWho means with Moorish blood to paint it red.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XC</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>What time Rogero sees the fair array,\nWhose bands to succour ravaged France prepare,\nAnd notes and talks of ensigns they display,\nAnd names of British lords, to him repair\nOne and another, crowding to survey\nHis courser, single of its kind, or rare:\nAll thither hasten, wondering and astound,\nAnd compassing the warrior, form a round.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XCI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>So that to raise more wonder in the train.\nAnd to make better sport, as him they eyed,\nRogero shook the flying courser's rein,\nAnd lightly with the rowels touched his side:\nHe towards heaven, uprising, soared amain,\nAnd left behind each gazer stupefied.\nHaving from end to end the English force\nSo viewed, he next for Ireland shaped his course;</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XCII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And saw fabulous Hibernia, where\nThe goodly, sainted elder made the cave,\nIn which men cleansed from all offences are;\nSuch mercy there, it seems, is found to save.\nThence o'er that sea he spurred, through yielding air,\nWhose briny waves the lesser Britain lave;\nAnd, looking down, Angelica descried\nIn passing, to the rock with fetters tied;</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XCIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Bound to the naked rock upon the strand,\nIn the isle of tears; for the isle of tears was hight,\nThat which was peopled by the inhuman band,\nSo passing fierce and full of foul despite;\nWho (as I told above on every hand ) \n\nCruized with their scattered fleet by day or night;\nAnd every beauteous woman bore away,\nDestined to be a monster's evil prey:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XCIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>There but that morning bound in cruel wise;\nWhere (to devour a living damsel sped)\nThe orc, that measureless sea-monster, hies,\nWhich on abominable food is fed.\nHow on the beach the maid became the prize\nOf the rapacious crew, above was said,\nWho found her sleeping near the enchanter hoar,\nWho her had thither brought by magic lore.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XCV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The cruel and inhospitable crew\nTo the voracious beast the dame expose\nUpon the sea-beat shore, as bare to view\nAs nature did at first her work compose.\nNot even a veil she had, to shade the hue\nOf the white lily and vermillion rose,\nWhich mingled in her lovely members meet,\nProof to December-snow and July-heat.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XCVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Her would Rogero have some statue deemed\nOf alabaster made, or marble rare,\nWhich to the rugged rock so fastened seemed\nBy the industrious sculptor's cunning care,\nBut that he saw distinct a tear which streamed\nAmid fresh-opening rose and lily fair,\nStand on her budding paps beneath in dew,\nAnd that her golden hair dishevelled flew.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XCVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And as he fastened his on her fair eyes,\nHis Bradamant he called to mind again.\nPity and love within his bosom rise\nAt once, and ill he can from tears refrain:\nAnd in soft tone he to the damsel cries,\n(When he has checked his flying courser's rein)\n\"O lady, worthy but that chain to wear,\nWith which Love's faithful servants fettered are,</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XCVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"And most unworthy this or other ill,\nWhat wretch has had the cruelty to wound\nAnd gall those snowy hands with livid stain,\nThus painfully with griding fetters bound?\"\nAt this she cannot choose but show like grain,\nOf crimson spreading on an ivory ground;\nKnowing those secret beauties are espied,\nWhich, howsoever lovely, shame would hide;</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XCIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And gladly with her hands her face would hood,\nWere they not fastened to the rugged stone:\nBut with her tears (for this at least she could)\nBedewed it, and essayed to hold it down.\nSobbing some while the lovely damsel stood;\nThen loosed her tongue and spake in feeble tone;\nBut ended not; arrested in mid-word,\nBy a loud noise which in the sea was heard.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>C</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Lo!  and behold!  the unmeasured-beast appears,\nHalf surging and half hidden, in such sort\nAs sped by roaring wind long carack steers\nFrom north or south, towards her destined port.\nSo the sea monster to his food repairs:\nAnd now the interval between is short.\nHalf dead the lady is through fear endured,\nIll by that other's comfort reassured.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>CI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Rogero overhand, not in the rest\nCarries his lance, and beats, with downright blow,\nThe monstrous orc.  What this resembled best,\nBut a huge, writhing mass, I do not know;\nWhich wore no form of animal exprest,\nSave in the head, with eyes and teeth of sow.\nHis forehead, 'twixt the eyes, Rogero smites,\nBut as on steel or rock the weapon lights.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>CII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>When he perceives the first of no avail,\nThe knight returns to deal a better blow;\nThe orc, who sees the shifting shadow sail\nOf those huge pinions on the sea below,\nIn furious heat, deserts his sure regale\nOn shore, to follow that deceitful show:\nAnd rolls and reels behind it, as it fleets.\nRogero drops, and oft the stroke repeats.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>CIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>As eagle, that amid her downward flight,\nSurveys amid the grass a snake unrolled,\nOr where she smoothes upon a sunny height,\nHer ruffled plumage, and her scales of gold,\nAssails it not where prompt with poisonous bite\nTo hiss and creep; but with securer hold\nGripes it behind, and either pinion clangs,\nLest it should turn and wound her with its fangs;</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>CIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>So the fell orc Rogero does not smite\nWith lance or faulchion where the tushes grow,\nBut aims that 'twixt the ears his blow may light;\nNow on the spine, or now on tail below.\nAnd still in time descends or soars upright,\nAnd shifts his course, to cheat the veering foe:\nBut as if beating on a jasper block,\nCan never cleave the hard and rugged rock.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>CV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>With suchlike warfare is the mastiff vext\nBy the bold fly in August's time of dust,\nOr in the month before or in the next,\nThis full of yellow spikes and that of must;\nFor ever by the circling plague perplext,\nWhose sting into his eyes or snout is thrust:\nAnd oft the dog's dry teeth are heard to fall;\nBut reaching once the foe, he pays for all.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>CVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>With his huge tail the troubled waves so sore\nThe monster beats, that they ascend heaven-high;\nAnd the knight knows not if he swim, or soar\nUpon his feathered courser in mid sky;\nAnd oft were fain to find himself ashore:\nFor, if long time the spray so thickly fly,\nHe fears it so will bathe his hippogryph,\nThat he shall vainly covet gourd or skiff.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>CVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>He then new counsel took, and 'twas the best,\nWith other arms the monster to pursue;\nAnd lifting from his shield the covering vest,\nTo dazzle with the light his blasted view.\nLandward towards the rock-chained maid he pressed,\nAnd on her little finger, lest a new\nMischance should follow, slipt the ring, which brought\nThe enchantment of the magic shield to nought.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>CVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>I say the ring, which Bradamant, to free\nRogero, from Brunello's hand had rent,\nAnd which, to snatch him from Alcina, she\nHad next to India by Melissa sent.\nMelissa (as before was said by me),\nIn aid of many used the instrument;\nAnd to Rogero this again had born;\nBy whom 'twas ever on his finger worn.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>CIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>He gave it now Angelica; for he\nFeared lest the buckler's light should be impaired,\nAnd willed as well those beauteous eyes should be\nDefended, which had him already snared.\nPressing beneath his paunch full half the sea,\nNow to the shore the monstrous whale repaired:\nFirm stood Rogero, and the veil undone,\nAppeared to give the sky another sun.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>CX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>He in the monster's eyes the radiance throws,\nWhich works as it was wont in other time.\nAs trout or grayling to the bottom goes\nIn stream, which mountaineer disturbs with lime;\nSo the enchanted buckler overthrows\nThe orc, reversed among the foam and slime.\nRogero here and there the beast astound\nStill beats, but cannot find the way to wound.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>CXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>This while the lady begs him not to bray\nLonger the monster's rugged scale in vain.\n\"For heaven's sake turn and loose me\" (did she say,\nStill weeping \"ere the orc awake again. ) \n\nBear me with thee, and drown me in mid-way.\nLet me not this foul monster's food remain.\"\nBy her just plaint Rogero moved, forebore,\nUntied the maid, and raised her from the shore.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>CXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Upon the beach the courser plants his feet,\nAnd goaded by the rowel, towers in air,\nAnd gallops with Rogero in mid seat,\nWhile on the croup behind him sate the fair;\nWho of his banquet so the monster cheat;\nFor him too delicate and dainty fare.\nRogero turns and with thick kisses plies\nThe lady's snowy breast and sparkling eyes.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>CXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>He kept no more the way, as he before\nProposed, for compassing the whole of Spain:\nBut stopt his courser on the neighbouring shore\nWhere lesser Britain runs into the main.\nUpon the bank there rose an oakwood hoar,\nWhere Philomel for ever seemed to plain;\nI' the middle was a meadow with a fountain,\nAnd, at each end, a solitary mountain.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>CXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>'Twas here the wishful knight first checked the rein,\nAnd dropping in the meadow, made his steed\nFurl, yet not shut so close, his wings again,\nAs he had spread them wide for better speed.\nDown lights Rogero, and forbears with pain\nFrom other leap; but this his arms impede:\nHis arms impede; a bar to his desire,\nAnd he must doff them would he slake the fire.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>CXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Now here, now there, confused by different throng,\nRogero did his shining arms undo:\nNever the task appeared to him so long;\nFor where he loosed one knot, he fastened two.\nBut, sir, too long continued is this song,\nAnd haply may as well have wearied you;\nSo that I shall delay to other time,\nWhen it may better please, my tedious rhyme.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 11"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Assisted by the magic ring she wears,\nAngelica evanishes from view.\nNext in a damsel, whom a giant bears\nBeneath his arm, his bride Rogero true\nBeholds.  Orlando to the shore repairs,\nWhere the fell orc so many damsels slew;\nOlympia frees, and spoils the beast of life:\nHer afterwards Oberto takes to wife.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>I</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Although a feeble rein, in mid career,\nWill oft suffice to stop courageous horse;\n'Tis seldom Reason's bit will serve to steer\nDesire, or turn him from his furious course,\nWhen pleasure is in reach: like headstrong bear,\nWhom from the honeyed meal 'tis ill to force,\nIf once he scent the tempting mess, or sup\nA drop, which hangs upon the luscious cup.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>II</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>What reason then Rogero shall withhold\nFrom taking with Angelica delight, —\nThat gentle maid, there naked in his hold,\nIn the lone forest, and secure from sight?\nOf Bradamant he thinks not, who controlled\nHis bosom erst: and foolish were the knight,\nIf thinking of that damsel as before,\nBy this he had not set an equal store;</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>III</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Warmed by whose youthful beauties, the severe\nXenocrates would not have been more chaste.\nThe impatient Child had dropt both shield and spear,\nAnd hurrying now his other arms uncased;\nWhen, casting down her eyes in shame and fear,\nThe virtuous ring upon her finger placed,\nAngelica descried, and which of yore\nFrom her Brunello in Albracca bore.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>IV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>This is the ring she carried into France,\nWhen thither first the damsel took her way;\nWith her the brother, bearer of the lance,\nAfter, the paladin, Astolpho's prey.\nWith this she Malagigi's spells and trance\nMade vain by Merlin's stair; and on a day\nOrlando freed, with many knights and good,\nFrom Dragontina's cruel servitude:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>V</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>With this passed viewless from the turret-cell,\nWhere her that bad old man had mewed; but why\nRecount its different wonders, if as well\nYou know the virtues of the ring as I?\nFrom her this even in her citadel,\nHis monarch Agramant to satisfy,\nBrunello took: since where she had been crost\nBy Fortune, till her native realm was lost.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>VI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Now that she this upon her hand surveys,\nShe is so full of pleasure and surprise,\nShe doubts it is a dream, and, in amaze,\nHardly believes her very hand and eyes.\nThen softly to her mouth the hoop conveys,\nAnd, quicker than the flash which cleaves the skies,\nFrom bold Rogero's sight her beauty shrowds,\nAs disappears the sun, concealed in clouds.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>VII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Yet still Rogero gazed like wight distraught,\nAnd hurried here and there with fruitless speed:\nBut when he had recalled the ring to thought,\nFoiled and astounded, cursed his little heed.\nAnd now the vanished lady, whom he sought,\nOf that ungrateful and discourteous deed\nAccusing stood, wherewith she had repaid,\n(Unfitting recompense his generous aid. ) \n</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>VIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Ungrateful damsel!  and is this the pay\nYou render for the service done?\" (said he)\n\"Why rather would you steal my ring away\nThan have it as a welcome gift from me?\nNot only this, (but use me as you may)\nI, and my shield and courser, yours shall be;\nSo you no more conceal your beauteous cheer.\nCruel, though answering not, I know you hear.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>IX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>So saying, like one blind, with bootless care,\nFeeling his way about the fount he strayed.\nHow often he embraced the empty air,\nHoping in this to have embraced the maid!\nMeanwhile, now far removed, the flying fair\nHad halted not, till to a cave conveyed.\nFormed in a mountain was that harbour rude;\nSpacious, and for her need supplied with food.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>X</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>'Twas here an aged herdsman, one who tended\nA numerous troop of mares, had made his won:\nThese, seeking pasture, through the valley wended,\nWhere the green grass was fed by freshening run:\nWhile stalls on either side the cave, defended\nHis charge from the oppressive noon-tide sun;\nAngelica, within, that livelong day,\nUnseen of prying eyes, prolonged her stay;</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And about evening, when refreshed with rest\nAnd food, she deemed her course she might renew;\nIn certain rustic weeds her body dressed:\nHow different from those robes of red, or blue,\nGreen, yellow, purple, her accustomed vest,\nSo various in its fashion, shape, and hue!\nYet her not so that habit misbecame,\nBut that she looked the fair and noble dame.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Then Phillis' and Neaera's praise forbear,\nAnd ye who sing of Amaryllis cease,\nOr flying Galataea, not so fair,\nTityrus and Melibaeus, with your peace!\n'Twas here the beauteous lady took a mare,\nWhich liked her best, of all that herd's increase.\nThen, and then first conceived the thought, again\nTo seek in the Levant her antient reign.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>This while Rogero, after he had passed\nLong space in hope the maid might re-appear,\nAwakened from his foolish dream at last,\nAnd found she was not nigh, and did not hear.\nThen to remount his griffin-courser cast,\nIn earth and air accustomed to career.\nBut, having slipt his bit, the winged horse\nHad towered and soared in air a freer course.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>To his first ill addition grave and sore\nWas to have lost the bird of rapid wing,\nWhich he no better than the mockery bore\nPut on him by the maid; but deeper sting\nThan this or that, implants, and pains him more,\nThe thought of having lost the precious ring;\nNot for its power so much, esteemed above\nIts worth, as given him by his lady love.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Afflicted beyond measure, he, with shield\nCast on his shoulder, and new-cased in mail,\nLeft the sea-side, and through a grassy field\nPursued his way, towards a spacious vale:\nWhere he beheld a path, by wood concealed,\nThe widest and most beaten in the dale.\nNor far had wound the closest shades within,\nEre on his right he heard a mighty din.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>He heard a din, and fearful clashing sound\nOf arms, and hurrying on with eager pace\n'Twixt tree and tree, two furious champions found,\nWaging fierce fight in close and straightened place:\nWho to each other (warring on what ground\nI know not neither showed regard nor grace. ) \n\nThe one a giant was of haughty cheer,\nAnd one a bold and gallant cavalier.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Covered with shield and sword, one, leaping, sped\nNow here now there, and thus himself defended,\nLest a two-handed mace upon his head\nShould fall, with which the giant still offended: —\nOn the field lay his horse, already dead.\nRogero paused, and to the strife attended:\nAnd straight his wishes leant towards the knight,\nWhom he would fain see conqueror in the fight:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Yet not for this would lend the champion aid,\nBut to behold the cruel strife stood nigh.\nLo!  a two-handed stroke the giant made\nUpon the lesser warrior's casque, and by\nThe mighty blow the knight was overlaid:\nThe other, when astound he saw him lie,\nTo deal the foe his death, his helm untied,\nSo that the warrior's face Rogero spied.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Of his sweet lady, of his passing fair,\nAnd dearest Bradamant Rogero spies\nThe lovely visage of its helmet bare;\nTowards whom, to deal her death, the giant hies:\nSo that, advancing with his sword in air,\nTo sudden battle him the Child defies,\nBut he, who will not wait for new alarm,\nTakes the half-lifeless lady in his arm,</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And on his shoulder flings and bears away;\nAs sometimes wolf a little lamb will bear,\nOr eagle in her crooked claws convey\nPigeon, or such-like bird, through liquid air.\nRogero runs with all the speed he may,\nWho sees how needed is his succour there.\nBut with such strides the giant scours the plain,\nHim with his eyes the knight pursues with pain.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>This flying and that following, the two\nKept a close path which widened still, and they\nPiercing that forest, issued forth to view\nOn a wide meadow, which without it lay.\n— No more of this.  Orlando I pursue,\nThat bore Cymosco's thunder-bolt away;\nAnd this had in the deepest bottom drowned,\nThat never more the mischief might be found.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>But with small boot: for the impious enemy\nOf human nature, taught the bolt to frame,\nAfter the shaft, which darting from the sky\nPierces the cloud and comes to ground in flame,\nWho, when he tempted Eve to eat and die\nWith the apple, hardly wrought more scathe and shame,\nSome deal before, or in our grandsires' day,\nGuided a necromancer where it lay.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>More than a hundred fathom buried so,\nWhere hidden it had lain a mighty space,\nThe infernal tool by magic from below\nWas fished and born amid the German race;\nWho, by one proof and the other, taught to know\nIts powers, and he who plots for our disgrace,\nThe demon, working on their weaker wit,\nAs last upon its fatal purpose hit.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>To Italy and France, on every hand\nThe cruel art among all people past:\nAnd these the bronze in hollow mould expand,\nFirst in the furnace melted by the blast:\nOthers the iron bore, and small or grand,\nFashion the various tube they pierce or cast.\nAnd bombard, gun, according to its frame,\nOr single cannon this, or double, name.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>This saker, culverine, or falcon hight,\nI hear (all names the inventor has bestowed);\nWhich splits or shivers steel and stone outright,\nAnd, where the bullet passes, makes a road.\n— Down to the sword, restore thy weapons bright,\nSad soldier, to the forge, a useless load;\nAnd gun or carbine on thy shoulder lay,\nWho without these, I wot, shalt touch no pay.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>How, foul and pestilent discovery,\nDidst thou find place within the human heart?\nThrough thee is martial glory lost, through thee\nThe trade of arms became a worthless art:\nAnd at such ebb are worth and chivalry,\nThat the base often plays the better part.\nThrough thee no more shall gallantry, no more\nShall valour prove their prowess as of yore.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Through thee, alas!  are dead, or have to die,\nSo many noble lords and cavaliers\nBefore this war shall end, which, Italy\nAfflicting most, has drowned the world in tears,\nThat, if I said the word, I err not, I,\nSaying he sure the cruellest appears\nAnd worst, of nature's impious and malign,\nWho did this hateful engine first design:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And I shall think, in order to pursue\nThe sin for ever, God has doomed to hell\nThat cursed soul, amid the unhappy crew,\nBeside the accursed Judas there to dwell.\nBut follow we the good Orlando, who\nSo burns to seek Ebuda's island fell,\nWhose foul inhabitants a monster sate\nWith flesh of women, fair and delicate.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>But no less slow than eager was the knight:\nThe winds appear, which still his course delay;\nWho, whether blowing on the left or right,\nOr poop, so faintly in his canvas play,\nHis bark makes little speed; and, spent outright,\nThe breeze which wafts her sometimes dies away,\nOr blows so foul, that he is fain to steer\nAnother course, or to the leeward veer.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>It was the will of Heaven that he, before\nThe King of Ireland, should not reach the land,\nThe he with greater ease upon that shore\nMight act what shortly you shall understand.\n\"Make for the isle.  Now\" (said he \"may'st thou moor,\" ) \n\n(Thus issuing to the pilot his command),\n\"And give me for my need the skiff; for I\nWill to the rock without more company.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"The biggest cable that thou hast aboard,\nAnd biggest anchor to my hands consign;\nThou shalt perceive why thus my boat is stored,\nIf I but meet that monster of the brine.\"\nHe bade them lower the pinnace overboard,\nWith all things that befitted his design:\nHis arms he left behind, except his blade,\nAnd singly for the rocky island made.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Home to his breast the count pulls either oar,\nWith the island at his back, to which he wends,\nIn guise that, crawling up the sandy shore,\nThe crooked crab from sea or marsh ascends.\nIt was the hour Aurora gay before\nThe rising sun her yellow hair extends\n(His orb as yet half-seen, half-hid from sight)\nNot without stirring jealous Tithon's spite.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Approaching to the naked rock as near\nAs vigorous hand might serve to cast a stone,\nHe knew not if he heard, or did not hear\nA cry, so faint and feeble was the moan.\nWhen, turning to the left, the cavalier,\nHis level sight along the water thrown,\nNaked as born, bound to a stump, espied\nA dame whose feet were wetted by the tide.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Because she distant is, and evermore\nHolds down her face, he ill can her discern:\nBoth sculls he pulls amain, and nears the shore,\nWith keen desire more certain news to learn:\nBut now the winding beach is heard to roar,\nAnd wood and cave the mighty noise return;\nThe billows swell, and, lo!  the beast!  who pressed,\nAnd nigh concealed the sea beneath his breast.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>As cloud from humid vale is seen to rise,\nPregnant with rain and storm, which seems withal\nTo extinguished day, and charged with deeper dyes\nThan night, to spread throughout this earthly ball,\nSo swims the beast, who so much occupies\nOf sea, he may be said to keep it all.\nWaves roar: collected in himself, the peer\nLooks proudly on, unchanged in heart and cheer.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>He, as one well resolved in his intent,\nMoved quickly to perform the feat he planned;\nAnd, for he would the damsel's harm prevent,\nAnd would with that assail the beast at hand,\nBetween her and the orc the boat he sent,\nLeaving within the sheath his idle brand,\nAnchor and cable next he takes in hold,\nAnd waits the foe with constant heart and bold.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>As soon as him the monster has descried,\nAnd skiff at little interval, his throat\nThe fish, to swallow him, expands so wide,\nThat horse and horseman through his jaws might float.\nHere Roland with the anchor, and beside\n(Unless I am mistaken with the boat ) \n\nPlunged, and engulphed the parted teeth betwixt,\nHis anchor in the tongue and palate fixt;</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>So that the monster could no longer drop\nOr raise his horrid jaws, which this extends.\n'Tis thus who digs the mine is wont to prop\nThe ground, and where he works the roof suspends,\nLest sudden ruin whelm him from atop,\nWhile he incautiously his task intends.\nRoland (so far apart was either hook)\nBut by a leap could reach the highest crook.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The prop so placed, Orlando now secure\nThat the fell beast his mouth no more can close,\nUnsheathes his sword, and, in that cave obscure,\nDeals here and there, now thrusts, now trenchant blows.\nAs well as citadel, whose walls immure\nThe assailants, can defend her from her foes,\nThe monster, harassed by the war within,\nDefends himself against the Paladin.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XL</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Now floats the monstrous beast, o'ercome with pain,\nWhose scaly flanks upon the waves expand;\nAnd now descends into the deepest main,\nScowers at the bottom, and stirs up the sand.\nThe rising flood ill able to sustain,\nThe cavalier swims forth, and makes for land.\nHe leaves the anchor fastened in his tongue,\nAnd grasps the rope which from the anchor hung.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>So swimming till the island is attained,\nWith this towards the rock Orlando speeds:\nHe hawls the anchor home (a footing gained),\nPricked by whose double fluke, the monster bleeds.\nThe labouring orc to follow is constrained,\nDragged by that force which every force exceeds;\nWhich at a single sally more achieves\nThan at ten turns the circling windlass heaves.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>As a wild bull, about whose horn is wound\nThe unexpected noose, leaps here and there,\nWhen he has felt the cord, and turns him round,\nAnd rolls and rises, yet slips not the snare;\nSo from his pleasant seat and ancient bound,\nDragged by that arm and rope he cannot tear,\nWith thousands of strange wheels and thousand slides,\nThe monster follows where the cable guides.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>This the red sea with reason would be hight\nTo-day, such streams of blood have changed its hue;\nAnd where the monster lashed it in his spite,\nThe eye its bottom through the waves might view.\nAnd now he splashed the sky, and dimmed the light\nOf the clear sun, so high the water flew.\nThe noise re-echoing round, the distant shore\nAnd wood and hill rebound the deafening roar.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Forth from his grotto aged Proteus hies,\nAnd mounts above the surface at the sound;\nAnd having seen Orlando dive, and rise\nFrom the orc, and drag the monstrous fish to ground,\nHis scattered flock forgot, o'er ocean flies;\nWhile so the din increases, that, astound,\nNeptune bids yoke his dolphins, and that day\nFor distant Aethiopia posts away.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>With Melicerta on her shoulders, weeping\nIno, and Nereids with dishevelled hair,\nThe Glauci, Tritons, and their fellows, leaping\nThey know not whither, speed, some here, some there.\nOrlando draws to land, the billows sweeping,\nThat horrid fish, but might his labour spare:\nFor, with the torment worn, and travel sore,\nThe brute, exhausted, died, ere dragged ashore.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Of the islanders had trooped no petty throng,\nTo witness that strange fight, who by a vain\nAnd miserable superstition stung,\nEsteemed such holy deed a work profane;\nAnd said that this would be another wrong\nTo Proteus, and provoke his ire again;\nMake him his herds pour forth upon the strand,\nAnd with the whole old warfare vex the land;</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And that it better were to sue for peace,\nFirst from the injured god, lest worse ensue;\nAnd Proteus from his cruel hate would cease,\nIf they into the sea the offender threw.\nAs torch to torch gives fire, and lights increase,\nUntil the flame is spread the country through,\nEven so from heart to heart the fury spread,\nWhich in the waves would doom Orlando dead.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>These, armed with sling or bow, upon the shore,\nAnd these supplied with spear or sword descend;\nAnd on each side, behind him and before,\nDistant and near, as best they can, offend.\nAt such a brutal insult wonders sore\nThe peer, who sees that mischief they intend,\nIn vengeance for the cruel monster slain,\nWhence he had glory hoped, and praise to gain.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>But as the usage is of surly bear,\nBy sturdy Russ or Lithuanian led,\nLittle to heed the dogs in crowded fair,\nNor even at their yelps to turn his head,\nThe clamour of the churls assembled there\nOrlando witnessed with as little dread;\nWho knew that he the rout which threatened death,\nHad power to scatter at a single breath:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>L</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And speedily he made them yield him place,\nWhen turned on them, he grasped his trenchant blade.\nMisjudging of his worth, the foolish race\nDeemed that he would have short resistance made;\nSince him they saw no covering buckler brace,\nUncuirassed, nor in other arms arrayed;\nBut knew not that, from head to foot, a skin\nMore hard than diamond cased the Paladin.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>What by Orlando others cannot do,\nThe knight by others can; at half a score\nOf blows in all he thirty killed; by few\nHe passed that measure, if the strokes were more:\nAnd had already turned him to undo\nThe naked lady, having cleared the shore,\nWhen other larum sounds, and other cries\nFrom a new quarter of the island rise.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>While so the Paladin had kept in play\nThe barbarous islanders, upon that hand,\nThe men of Ireland, without let or fray,\nHad poured from many quarters on the strand:\nAnd now, without remorse or pity, slay\nThe inhabitants, through all the wasted land;\nAnd, was it justice moved, or cruel rage,\nSlaughter without regard to sex or age.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Little or no defender the island-crew\nAttempt; in part as taken unaware,\nIn part that in the little place are few,\nAnd that those few without a purpose are.\n'Mid sack and fire, the wasted country through,\nThe islanders are slain, and everwhere\nThe walls are upon earth in ruin spread,\nNor in the land is left a living head.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>As if the mighty tumult which he hears,\nAnd shriek and ruin had concerned him nought,\nThe naked rock the bold Orlando nears,\nWhere she was placed, to feed the monster brought.\nHe looks, and known to him the dame appears,\nAnd more appears, when nigher her he sought:\nOlympia she appears, and is indeed\nOlympia, whose faith reaped so ill a meed.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Wretched Olympia; whom, beside the scorn\nWhich Love put on her, Fortune too pursued,\nWho sent the corsairs fell, which her had born\nThat very day to the island of Ebude.\nShe Roland recollects on his return\nLandward; but, for the damsel naked stood,\nNot only nought she to the warrior said,\nBut dared not raise her eyes, and dropt her head.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Orlando asks what evil destiny\nHer to that cruel island had conveyed\nFrom where she in as much felicity\nWas with her consort left as could be said:\n\"I know not (cried the weeping dame if I ) \n\nHave thanks to render thee for death delayed,\nOr should lament me that, through means of thee,\nThis day did not my woes concluded see.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"I have to thank thee that from death, too dread\nAnd monstrous, thy good arm deliverance gave;\nWhich would have been too monstrous, had I fed\nThe beast, and in his belly found a grave:\nBut cannot thank thee that I am not dead,\nSince death alone can me from misery save,\nWell shall I thank thee for that wished relief,\nWhich can deliver me from every grief.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Next she related, with loud sobs and sighs,\nHow her false spouse betrayed her as she lay\nAsleep, and how of pirates made the prize,\nThey bore her from the desert isle away.\nAnd, as she spake, she turned her in the guise\nOf Dian, framed by artists, who pourtray\nHer carved or painted, as in liquid font\nShe threw the water in Actaeon's front.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>For, as she can, her waist she hides, and breast,\nMore liberal of flowing flank and reins.\nRoland desires his ship, to find a vest\nTo cover her, delivered from her chains:\nWhile he is all intent upon this quest,\nOberto comes; Oberto, he that reigns\nO'er Ireland's people, who had understood\nHow lifeless lay the monster of the flood;</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And, swimming, how, amid the watery roar,\nA knight a weighty anchor in his throat\nHad fix'd, and so had dragged him to the shore,\nAs men against the current track a boat.\nThis while Oberto comes; who, if his lore,\nWho told the tale, were true, desires to note;\nWhile his invading army, far and wide,\nEbuda burn and waste on every side.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Oberto, though the Paladin to sight\nWas dripping, and with water foul and gore;\nWith gore, that from the orc, emerged to light,\nWhom he had entered bodily, he bore,\nHe for the country knew the stranger knight\nAs he perused his face; so much the more,\nThat he had thought when told the tidings, none\nSave Roland could such mighty fear have done;</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Knew him, because a page of honour he\nHad been in France, and for the crown, his right\nUpon his father's death, had crossed the sea\nThe year before.  So often he the knight\nHad seen, and had with him held colloquy,\nTheir times of meeting had been infinite.\nHe doffed his casque, with festive welcome pressed\nTowards the count, and clasped him to the breast.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Orlando is no less rejoined to see\nThe king, than is the king that champion true.\nAfter with friendly cheer and equal glee\nHad once or twice embraced the noble two,\nTo Oberto Roland told the treachery\nWhich had been done the youthful dame, and who\nHad done it, — false Bireno — that among\nAll men should least have sought to do her wrong.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>To him he told the many proofs and clear\nBy which the dame's affection had been tried;\nAnd how she for Bireno kin and geer\nHad lost, and would in fine for him have died.\nAnd how he this could warrant, and appear\nTo vouch for much, as witness on her side.\nWhile thus to him her griefs Orlando showed,\nThe lady's shining eyes with tears o'erflowed.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Her face was such as sometimes in the spring\nWe see a doubtful sky, when on the plain\nA shower descends, and the sun, opening\nHis cloudy veil, looks out amid the rain.\nAnd as the nightingale then loves to sing\nFrom branch of verdant stem her dulcet strain,\nSo in her beauteous tears his pinions bright\nLove bathes, rejoicing in the chrystal light.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The stripling heats his golden arrow's head\nAt her bright eyes, then slacks the weapon's glow\nIn streams, which falls between white flowers and red;\nAnd, the shaft tempered, strongly draws his bow,\nAnd roves at him, o'er whom no shield is spread,\nNor iron rind, nor double mail below;\nWho, gazing on her tresses, eyes, and brow,\nFeels that his heart is pierced, he knows not how.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Olympia's beauties are of those most rare,\nNor is the forehead's beauteous curve alone\nExcellent, and her eyes and cheeks and hair,\nMouth, nose, and throat, and shoulders; but, so down\nDescending from the lady's bosom fair,\nParts which are wont to be concealed by gown,\nAre such, as haply should be placed before\nWhate'er this ample world contains in store.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>In whiteness they surpassed unsullied snow,\nSmooth ivory to the touch: above were seen\nTwo rounding paps, like new-pressed milk in show,\nFresh-taken from its crate of rushes green;\nThe space betwixt was like the valley low,\nWhich oftentimes we see small hills between,\nSweet in its season, and now such as when\nWinter with snows has newly filled the glen.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The swelling hips and haunches' symmetry,\nThe waist more clear than mirror's polished grain,\nAnd members seem of Phidias' turnery,\nOr work of better hand and nicer pain.\nAs well to you of other parts should I\nRelate, which she to hide desired in vain.\nTo sum the beauteous whole, from head to feet,\nIn her all loveliness is found complete.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And had she in the Idaean glen unveiled\nIn ancient days before the Phrygian swain,\nBy how much heavenly Venus had prevailed\nI know not, though her rivals strove in vain.\nNor haply had the youth for Sparta sailed,\nTo violate the hospitable reign;\nBut said:  \"With Menelaus let Helen rest!\nNo other prize I seek, of this possest\";</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Or in Crotona dwelt, where the divine\nZeuxis in days of old his work projected,\nTo be the ornament of Juno's shrine,\nAnd hence so many naked dames collected;\nAnd in one form perfection to combine,\nSome separate charm from this or that selected,\nHe from no other model need have wrought.\nSince joined in her were all the charms he sought.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>I do not think Bireno ever viewed\nNaked that beauteous form; for sure it were\nHe never could have been so stern of mood,\nAs to have left her on that desert lair.\nThat Ireland's king was fired I well conclude,\nNor hid the flame that he within him bare.\nHe strives to comfort her, and hope instill,\nThat future good shall end her present ill.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And her to Holland promises to bear,\nAnd vows till she is to her state restored,\nAnd just and memorable vengeance there\nAchieved upon her perjured, traitor lord,\nHe never will unceasing war forbear,\nWaged with all means that Ireland can afford;\nAnd this with all his speed.  He, up and down,\nMeantime bids seek for female vest and gown.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Now will it need to send in search of vest\nBeyond the savage island's narrow bound,\nSince thither every day in such came dressed,\nSome dame, to feed the beast, from countries round.\nNor long his followers there pursued the quest,\nEre many they of various fashions found.\nSo was Olympia clothed; while sad of mood\nWas he, not so to clothe her as he wou'd.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>But never silk so choice or gold so fine\nDid the industrious Florentine prepare,\nNor whosoever broiders gay design,\nThough on his task be spent time, toil, and care,\nNor Lemnos' god, nor Pallas' art divine,\nForm raiment worthy of those limbs so fair,\nThat King Oberto cannot choose but he\nRecalls them at each turn to memory.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>To see that love so kindled by the dame,\nOn many grounds Orlando was content;\nWho not alone rejoiced that such a shame\nPut upon her, Bireno should repent;\nBut, that in the design on which he came,\nHe should be freed from grave impediment.\nNot for Olympia thither had he made,\nBut, were his lady there, to lend her aid.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>To him, that there she was not, soon was clear,\nBut clear it was not if she had been there,\nOr no; since of those islesmen, far and near,\nOne was not left the tidings to declare.\nThe following day they from the haven steer,\nAnd all united in one squadron fare.\nThe Paladin with them to Ireland hies,\nFrom whence to France the warrior's passage lies.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Scarcely a day in Ireland's realm he spends:\nAnd for no prayers his purposed end forbore:\nLove, that in quest of his liege-lady sends\nThe knight upon this track, permits no more.\nDeparting, he Olympia recommends\nTo the Irish monarch, who to serve her swore:\nAlthough this needed not; since he was bent\nMore than behoved, her wishes to content:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>So levied in few days his warlike band,\nAnd (league with England's kind and Scotland's made)\nIn Holland and in Friesland left no land\nTo the false duke, so rapid was the raid.\nAnd to rebel against that lord's command\nHis Zealand stirred; nor he the war delayed,\nUntil by him Bireno's blood was spilt:\nA punishment that ill atoned his guilt.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Oberto takes to wife Olympia fair,\nAnd her of countess makes a puissant queen.\nBut be the Paladin again our care,\nWho furrows , night and day, the billows green,\nAnd strikes his sails in the same harbour, where\nThey to the wind erewhile unfurled had been\nAll armed, he on his Brigliadoro leaps,\nAnd leaves behind him winds and briny deeps.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The remnant of the winter, he with shield\nAnd spear achieved things worthy to be shown,\nI ween; but these were then so well concealed,\nIt is no fault of mine they are not blown;\nFor good Orlando was in fighting field,\nPrompter to do, than make his prowess known.\nNor e'er was bruited action of the knight,\nSave when some faithful witness was in sight.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>That winter's remnant he so passed that feat\nOf his was known not to the public ear;\nBut when within that animal discreet\nWhich Phryxus bore, the sun illumed the sphere,\nAnd Zephyrus returning glad and sweet,\nBrought back with him again the blooming year,\nThe wondrous deeds Orlando did in stower,\nAppeared with the new grass and dainty flower.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>From plain to hill, from champaign flat to shore,\nOppressed with grief and pain the County fares,\nWhen a long cry, entering a forest hoar,\n— A load lamenting smites upon his ears.\nHe grasps his brand and spurs his courser sore,\nAnd swiftly pricks toward the sound he hears.\nBut I shall at another season say\nWhat chanced, and may be heard in future lay.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 12"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Orlando, full of rage, pursues a knight\nWho bears by force his lady-love away,\nAnd comes where old Atlantes, by his sleight\nHad raised a dome, Rogero there to stay.\nHere too Rogero comes; where getting sight\nOf his lost love, the County strives in fray\nWith fierce Ferrau, and, after slaughter fell\nAmid the paynim host, finds Isabel.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>I</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Ceres, when from the Idaean dame in haste\nReturning to the lonely valley, where\nEnceladus the Aetnaean mountain placed\nOn his bolt-smitten flanks, is doomed to bear,\nHer girl she found not, on that pathless waste,\nBy her late quitted, having rent her hair,\nAnd marked cheeks, eyes, and breast, with livid signs,\nAt the end of her lament tore up two pines,</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>II</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And lit at Vulcan's fire the double brand,\nAnd gave them virtue never to be spent;\nAnd, afterwards, with one in either hand,\nDrawn by two dragons, in her chariot went,\nSearching the forest, hill, and level land,\nField, valley, running stream, or water pent,\nThe land and sea; and having searched the shell\nOf earth above, descended into hell.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>III</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Had Roland of Eleusis' deity\nThe sovereign power possessed no less than will,\nHe for Angelica had land and sea\nRansacked, and wood and field, and pool and rill,\nHeaven, and Oblivion's bottom: but since he\nHad not, his pressing purpose to fulfil,\nHer dragon and her car, the unwearied knight\nPursued the missing maid as best he might.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>IV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Through France he sought her, and will seek her through\nThe realms of Italy and of Almayn,\nAnd thence through the Castiles, both old and new,\nSo passing into Libya out of Spain.\nWhile bold Orlando has this plan in view,\nHe hears, or thinks he hears, a voice complain:\nHe forward spurs, and sees on mighty steed\nA warrior trot before him on the mead;</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>V</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Who in his arms a captive damsel bears,\nSore grieving, and across the pommel laid;\nShe weeps and struggles, and the semblance wears\nOf cruel woe, and ever calls for aid\nUpon Anglantes' prince; and now appears\nTo him, as he surveys the youthful maid,\nShe, for whom, night and day, with ceaseless pain,\nInside and out, he France had searched in vain.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>VI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>I say not is, but that she to the sight\nSeems the Angelica he loves so dear.\nHe who is lady-love and goddess' flight\nBeholds, borne off in such afflicted cheer,\nImpelled by fury foul, and angry spite,\nCalls back with horrid voice the cavalier;\nCalls back the cavalier, and threats in vain,\nAnd Brigliadoro drives with flowing rein.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>VII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>That felon stops not, nor to him replies,\nOn his great gain intent, his glorious prey;\nAnd with such swiftness through the greenwood hies,\nWind would not overtake him on his way.\nThe one pursues while him the other flies,\nAnd with lament resounds the thicket gray.\nThey issue in a spacious mead, on which\nAppears a lofty mansion, rare and rich.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>VIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Of various marbles, wrought with subtle care,\nIs the proud palace.  He who fast in hold\nBears off upon his arm the damsel fair,\nSore pricking, enters at a gate of gold.\nNor Brigliador is far behind the pair,\nBacked by Orlando, angry knight and bold.\nEntering, around Orlando turns his eyes,\nYet neither cavalier nor damsel spies.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>IX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>He suddenly dismounts, and thundering fares\nThrough the inmost palace, seeking still his foe,\nAnd here and there in restless rage repairs,\nTill he has seen each bower, each galleried row;\nWith the same purpose he ascends the stairs,\nHaving first vainly searched each room below.\nNor spends less labour, on his task intent,\nAbove, than he beneath had vainly spent.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>X</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Here beds are seen adorned with silk and gold;\nNor of partition aught is spied or wall:\nFor these, and floor beneath, throughout that hold,\nAre hid by curtains and by carpets all.\nNow here, now there, returns Orlando bold,\nNor yet can glad his eyes, in bower or hall,\nWith the appearance of the royal maid,\nOr the foul thief by whom she was conveyed.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>This while, as here and there in fruitless pain\nHe moves, oppressed with thought and trouble sore,\nGradasso, Brandimart, and him of Spain,\nFerrau, he finds, with Sacripant and more;\nWho ever toiling, like himself, in vain\nAbove, that building, and beneath explore,\nAnd as they wander, curse with one accord\nThe malice of the castle's viewless lord.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>All in pursuit of the offender speed,\nAnd upon him some charge of robbery lay:\nOne knight complains that he has stolen his steed,\nOne that he has purloined his lady gay.\nOther accuses him of other deed:\nAnd thus within the enchanted cage they stay,\nNor can depart; while in the palace pent,\nMany have weeks and months together spent.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Roland, when he round that strange dome had paced\nFour times or six, still vainly seeking, said\nWithin himself, at last, \"I here might waste\nMy time and trouble, still in vain delayed,\nWhile haply her the robber whom I chased\nHas far away, through other gate conveyed.\"\nSo thinking, from the house he issued out\nInto the mead which girt the dome about.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>While Roland wanders round the sylvan Hall,\nStill holding close his visage to the ground,\nTo see if recent print or trace withal\nCan, right or left, upon the turf be found,\nHe from a neighbouring window hears a call,\nAnd looks, and thinks he hears that voice's sound,\nAnd thinks he sees the visage by which he\nWas so estranged from what he wont to be.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>He thinks he hears Angelica, and she\n\"Help, help!\" entreating cries, and weeping sore,\n\"More than for life and soul, alas!  of thee\nProtection for my honour I implore.\nThen shall it in my Roland's presence be\nRavished by this foul robber?  Oh! before\nMe to such miserable fate you leave,\nLet me from your own hand my death receive!\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>These words repeated once, and yet again,\nMade Roland through each chamber, far and near,\nReturn with passion, and with utmost pain;\nBut tempered with high hope.  Sometimes the peer\nStopt in his search and heard a voice complain,\nWhich seemed to be Angelica's:  if here\nThe restless warrior stand, it sounds from there,\nAnd calls for help he knows not whence nor where,</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Returning to Rogero, left, I said,\nWhen through a gloomy path, upon his steed,\nFollowing the giant and the dame who fled,\nHe from the wood had issued on the mead;\nI say that he arrived where Roland dread\nArrived before him, if I rightly read.\nThe giant through the golden portal passed,\nRogero close behind, who followed fast.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>As soon as he his foot has lifted o'er\nThe threshold, he through court and gallery spies;\nNor sees the giant or the lady more,\nAnd vainly glances here and there his eyes.\nHe up and down returns with labour sore,\nYet not for that his longing satisfies;\nNor can imagine where the felon thief\nHas hid himself and dame in space so brief.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>After four times or five he so had wound\nAbove, below, through bower and gallery fair,\nHe yet returned, and, having nothing found,\nSearched even to the space beneath the stair.\nAt length, in hope they in the woodlands round\nMight be, he sallied; but the voice, which there\nRoland recalled, did him no less recall,\nAnd made as well return within the Hall.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>One voice, one shape, which to Anglantes' peer\nSeemed his Angelica, beseeching aid.\nSeemed to Rogero Dordogne's lady dear.\nWho him a truant to himself had made:\nIf with Gradasso, or with other near\nHe spake, of those who through the palace strayed.\nTo all of them the vision, seen apart,\nSeemed that which each had singly most at heart.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>This was a new and unwonted spell,\nWhich the renowned Atlantes had composed,\nThat in this toil, this pleasing pain, might dwell\nSo long Rogero, by these walls enclosed,\nFrom him should pass away  the influence fell,\n— Influence which him to early death exposed.\nThough vain his magic tower of steel, and vain\nAlcina's art, Atlantes plots again.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Not only he, but others who stood high\nFor valour, and in France had greatest fame,\nThat by their hands Rogero might not die,\nBrought here by old Atlantes' magic came:\nWhile these in the enchanted mansion lie,\nThat food be wanting not to knight or dame,\nHe has supplied the dome throughout so well,\nThat all the inmates there in plenty dwell.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>But to Angelica return we, who\nNow of that ring so wondrous repossessed,\n(Which, in her mouth, concealed the maid from view,\nPreserved from spell when it the finger pressed,)\nWas in the mountain-cavern guided to\nWhatever needed, viands, mare, and vest,\nAnd had conceived the project to pursue\nHer way to her fair Indian realm anew.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>King Sacripant, or Roland, willingly\nThe damsel would have taken for her guide;\nNot that, propitious to their wishes, she\n(Averse from both inclined to either side; ) \n\nBut, since her eastern journey was to be\nThrough town and city, scattered far and wide,\nShe needed company, and ill had found\nMore trusty guides than these for such a round.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Now this, now that she sought with fruitless care,\nBefore she lit on either warrior's trace,\nBy city or by farm, now here, now there,\nIn forest now, and now in other place.\nFortune, at length, where caged with Roland are\nFerrau and Sacripant, directs her chase;\nRogero, with Gradasso fierce, and more,\nNoosed with strange witcheries by Atlantes hoar.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>She enters, hidden from the enchanter's eyes,\nAnd by the ring concealed, examines all;\nAnd Roland there, and Sacripant espies,\nIntent to seek her vainly through the Hall;\nAnd with her image cheating both, descries\nAtlantes old.  The damsel doubts withal\nWhich of the two to take, and long revolves\nThis in her doubtful thought, nor well resolves.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>She knows not which with her will best accord,\nThe Count Orlando or Circassia's knight.\nAs of most powers, her would Rogero ward\nIn passage perilous, with better might.\nBut should she make the peer her guide, her lord,\nShe knew not if her champion she could slight,\nIf him she would depress with altered cheer,\nOr into France send back the cavalier:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>But Sacripant at pleasure could depose,\nThough him she had uplifted to the sky.\nHence him alone she for her escort chose,\nAnd feigned to trust in his fidelity.\nThe ring she from her mouth withdraws, and shows\nHer face, unveiled to the Circassian's eye:\nShe thought to him alone; but fierce Ferrau\nAnd Roland came upon the maid, and saw.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Ferrau and Roland came upon the maid;\nFor one and the other champion equally\nWithin the palace and without it strayed\nIn quest of her, who was their deity.\nAnd now, no longer by the enchantment stayed,\nEach ran alike towards the dame, for she\nHad placed the ring upon her hand anew,\nWhich old Atlantes' every scheme o'erthrew.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Helm on the head and corselet on the breast\nOf both the knights, of whom I sing, was tied;\nBy night or day, since they into this rest\nHad entered, never doffed and laid aside:\nFor such to wear were easy as a vest,\nTo these, so wont the burden to abide.\nAs well was armed, except with iron masque,\nFerrau, who wore not, nor would wear, a casque.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Till he had that erst wrested by the peer,\nOrlando, from the brother of Troyane;\nFor so had sworn the Spanish cavalier,\nWhat time he Argalia's helm in vain\nSought in the brook; yet though the count was near,\nHas not stretched forth his hand the prize to gain.\nFor so it was, that neither of the pair\nCould recognise the other knight while there.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Upon the enchanted dome lay such a spell,\nThat they from one another were concealed;\nThey doffed not, night nor day, the corselet's shell,\nNot sword, nor even put aside the shield.\nSaddled, with bridle hanging at the sell,\nTheir steeds were feeding, ready for the field,\nWithin a chamber, near the palace door,\nWith straw and barley heaped in plenteous store.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Nor might nor mean in old Atlantes lies\nTo stop the knights from mounting, who repair\nTo their good steeds, to chase the bright black eyes,\nThe fair vermillion cheeks and golden hair\nOf the sweet damsel, who before them flies,\nAnd goads to better speed her panting mare;\nIll pleased the three assembled to discern,\nThough haply she had taken each in turn.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And when these from the magic palace she\nHad ticed so far, that she no more supposed\nThe warriors to the wicked fallacy\nOf the malign enchanter were exposed,\nThe ring, which more than once from misery\nHad rescued her, she 'twixt her lips enclosed,\nHence from their sight she vanished in a thought,\nAnd left them wondering there, like men distraught.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Although she first the scheme had entertained\nRoland or Sacripant to have released,\nTo guide her thither, where her father reigned,\nKing Galaphron, who ruled i' the farthest East,\nThe aid of both she suddenly disdained,\nAnd in an instant from her project ceased;\nAnd deemed, without more debt to count or king,\nIn place of either knight sufficed the ring.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>In haste, they through the forest, here and there,\nSo scorned of her, still gaze with stupid face;\nLike questing hound which loses sight of hare\nOr fox, of whom he late pursued the trace,\nInto close thicket, ditch, or narrow lair,\nEscaping from the keen pursuer's chase.\nMeantime their ways the wanton Indian queen\nObserves, and at their wonder laughs unseen.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>In the mid wood, where they the maid did lose,\nWas but a single pathway, left or right;\nWhich they believed the damsel could not choose\nBut follow, when she vanished from their sight.\nFerrau halts not, and Roland fast pursues,\nNor Sacripant less plies the rowels bright.\nAngelica, this while, retrains her steed,\nAnd follows the three warriors with less speed.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>When pricking thus they came to where the way\nWas in the forest lost, with wood o'ergrown,\nAnd had begun the herbage to survey\nFor print of recent footsteps, up and down,\nThe fierce Ferrau, who might have borne away\nFrom all that ever proudest were, the crown,\nWith evil countenance, to the other two\nTurned him about, and shouted \"Whence are you?\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XXXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Turn back or take another road, save here,\nIn truth, you covet to be slain by me.\nNor when I chase or woo my lady dear,\nLet any think I bear with company.\"\nAnd — \"What more could he say, sir cavalier,\"\n(Orlando cried to Sacripant \"if we ) \n\nWere known for the two basest whores that pull\nAnd reel from spindle-staff the matted wool?\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XL</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Then turning to Ferrau,, \"But that thine head,\nThou brutish sot, as I behold, is bare,\nIf thy late words were ill or wisely said,\nThou should'st perceive, before we further fare.\"\nTo him Ferrau:  \"For that which breeds no dread\nIn me, why should'st thou take such sovereign care?\nWhat I have said unhelmed will I prove true,\nHere, single as I am, on both of you.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Oh!\" (to Circassia's king cried Roland dread)\n\"Thy morion for this man let me entreat,\nTill I have driven such folly from his head;\nFor never with like madness did I meet.\"\n— \"Who then would be most fool?\" the monarch said;\n\"But if indeed you deem the suit discreet,\nLend him thine own; nor shall I be less fit\nHaply than thee to school his lack of wit.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>— \"Fools, both of you!\" (the fierce Ferrau replied)\n\"As if, did I to wear a helm delight,\nYou would not be without your casques of pride,\nAlready reft by me in your despite;\nBut know thus much, that I by vow am tied\nTo wear no helm, and thus my promise quite;\nRoaming without, till that fine casque I win\nWorn by Orlando, Charles's paladin.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>— \"Then\" (smiling, to the Spaniard said the count)\n\"With naked head, thou thinkest to repeat\nOn Roland what he did in Aspramont,\nBy Agolant's bold son: but shouldst thou meet\nThe warrior whom thou seekest, front to front,\nI warrant thou wouldst quake from head to feet;\nNor only wouldst forego the casque, but give\nThe knight thine other arms to let thee live.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>— \"So oft have I had Roland on the hip,\nAnd oft,\" (exclaimed the boaster \"heretofore; ) \n\nFrom him it had been easy task to strip\nWhat other arms, beside his helm, he wore;\nAnd if I still have let the occasion slip,\n— We sometimes think of things unwished before:\nSuch wish I had not; I have now; and hope\nTo compass easily my present scope.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The good Orlando could no more forbear,\nAnd cried, \"Foul miscreant, liar, marched with me,\nSay, caitiff, in what country, when and where\nBoast you to have obtained such victory?\nThat paladin am I, o'er whom you dare\nTo vaunt, and whom you distant deemed: now see\nIf you can take my helm, or I have might\nTo take your other arms in your despite.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"Nor I o'er you the smallest vantage wou'd.\"\nHe ended, and his temples disarrayed,\nAnd to a beech hung up the helmet good,\nAnd nigh as quickly bared his trenchant blade.\nFerrau stands close, and in such attitude,\n(His courage not for what had chanced dismayed)\nCovered with lifted shield and naked sword,\nAs might best shelter to his head afford.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>'Twas thus those warriors two, with faulchions bare,\nTurning their ready steeds, began to wheel;\nAnd where the armour thinnest was, and where\nThe meeting plates were joined, probed steel with steel;\nNor was there in the world another pair\nMore fitted to be matched in fierce appeal:\nEqual their daring, equal was their might,\nAnd safe alike from wound was either knight.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>By you, fair sir, already, I presume,\nThat fierce Ferrau was charmed is understood,\nSave where the child, enclosed within the womb\nOf the full mother, takes its early food;\nAnd hence he ever, till the squalid tomb\nCovered his manly face, wore harness good\n(Such was his wont the doubtful part to guard, ) \n\nOf seven good plates of metal, tempered hard.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XLIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Alike a charmed life Orlando bore,\nSafe every where, except a single part:\nUnfenced beneath his feet, which evermore\nBy him were guarded with all care and art.\nThe rest than diamond dug from mountain hoar\nMore hard, unless report from truth depart;\nAnd armed to battle either champion went,\nLess for necessity than ornament.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>L</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Waxing more fierce and fell the combat rages,\nOf fear and horror full, between the twain:\nThe fierce Ferrau such dreadful battle wages,\nThat stroke or thrust is never dealt in vain:\nEach mighty blow from Roland disengages\nAnd loosens, breaks, or shatters, plate and chain.\nAngelica alone, secure from view,\nRegards such fearful sight, and marks the two.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>For, during this, the king of Circassy,\nWho deemed Angelica not far before,\nWhen Ferrau and Orlando desperately\nClosing in fight were seen, his horse did gore\nAlong the way by which he deemed that she\nHad disappeared; and so that battle sore\nWas witnessed 'twixt the struggling foes, by none,\nBeside the daughter of king Galaphron.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>After the damsel had sometime descried\nThis dread and direful combat, standing nigh;\nAnd it appearing that on either side\nWith equal peril both the warriors vie,\nShe, fond of novelty, the helm untied\nDesigns to take; desirous to espy\nWhat they would do when they perceived the wrong;\nBut, without thought to keep her plunder long.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>To give it to Orlando was she bent,\nBut first she would upon the warrior play:\nThe helmet she took down with this intent\nAnd in her bosom hid, and marked the fray:\nNext thence, without a word to either went,\nAnd from the scene of strife was far away\nEre either of the two had marked the feat;\nSo were they blinded by their angry heat.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>But Ferrau, who first chanced the loss to see,\nFrom Roland disengaged himself, and cried,\n\"How like unwary men and fools are we\nTreated by him, who late with us did ride!\nWhat meed, which worthiest of the strife might be,\nIf this be stolen, the victor shall abide?\"\nRoland draws back, looks upward, and with ire,\nMissing the noble casque, is all on fire:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And in opinion with Ferrau agreed,\nThat he the knight, who was with them before,\nHad born away the prize: hence turned his steed.\nAnd with the spur admonished Brigliador.\nFerrau, who from the field beheld him speed.\nFollowed him, and when Roland and the Moor\nArrived where tracks upon the herbage green\nOf the Circassian and the maid were seen,</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Towards a vale upon the left the count\nWent off, pursuing the Circassian's tread;\nThe Spaniard kept the path more nigh the mount,\nBy which the fair Angelica had fled.\nAngelica, this while, has reached a fount,\nOf pleasant site, and shaded overhead;\nBy whose inviting shades no traveller hasted,\nNor ever left the chrystal wave untasted.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Angelica, the sylvan spring beside,\nReposes, unsuspicious of surprise;\nAnd thinking her the sacred ring will hide,\nFears not that evil accident can rise.\nOn her arrival at the fountain's side,\nShe to a branch above the helmet ties;\nThen seeks the fittest sapling for her need,\nWhere, fastened to its trunk, her mare may feed.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The Spanish cavalier the stream beside\nArrived, who had pursued her traces there:\nAngelica no sooner him espied,\nThan she evanished clean, and spurred her mare:\nThe helm this while had dropt, but lay too wide\nTo be recovered of the flying fair.\nAs soon as sweet Angelica he saw,\nTowards her full of rapture sprang Ferrau.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>She disappeared, I say, as forms avaunt\nAt sleep's departure: toiling long and sore\nHe seeks the damsel there, 'twixt plant and plant,\nNow can his wretched eyes behold her more.\nBlaspheming his Mahound and Termagant,\nAnd cursing every master of his lore,\nFerrau returned towards the sylvan fount,\nWhere lay on earth the helmet of the count.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>This he soon recognised, for here he read\nLetters upon the margin, written fair,\nWhich how Orlando won the helmet said;\nAnd from what champion took, and when and where.\nWith it the paynim armed his neck and head,\nWho would not for his grief the prize forbear;\nHis grief for loss of her, conveyed from sight,\nAs disappear the phantoms of the night.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>When in this goodly casque he was arrayed,\nHe deemed nought wanting to his full content,\nBut the discovery of the royal maid,\nWho like a flash of lightning came and went:\nFor her he searches every greenwood shade,\nAnd when all hope of finding her is spent,\nHe for the vain pursuit no longer tarries,\nBut to the Spanish camp returns near Paris;</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Tempering the grief which glowed within his breast,\nFor such sore disappointment, with the thought\nThat he was with Orlando's morion blest,\nAs sworn.  By good Anglante's count, when taught\nThat the false Saracen the prize possest,\nLong time the Spanish knight was vainly sought;\nNor Roland took the helmet from his head,\nTill he between two bridges laid him dead.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Angelica thus, viewless and alone,\nSpeeds on her journey, but with troubled front;\nGrieved for the helmet, in her haste foregone\nOn her departure from the grassy fount.\n\"Choosing to do what I should least have done,\"\n(She said \"I took his helmet from the count. ) \n\nThis for his first desert I well bestow;\nA worthy recompense for all I owe!</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>\"With good intentions, as God knows, I wrought;\nThough these an ill and different end produce;\nI took the helmet only with the thought\nTo bring that deadly battle to a truce;\nAnd not that this foul Spaniard what he sought\nShould gain, or I to his intent conduce.\"\nSo she, lamenting, took herself to task\nFor having robbed Orlando of his casque.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>By what appeared to her the meetest way,\nMoody and ill-content she eastward pressed;\nOfttimes concealed, sometimes in face of day,\nAs seemed most opportune and pleased her best.\nAfter much country seen, a forest gray\nShe reached, where, sorely wounded in mid breast,\nBetween two dead companions on the ground,\nThe royal maid a bleeding stripling found.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>But of Angelica I now no more\nShall speak, who first have many things to say;\nNor shall to the Circassian or the Moor\nGive for long space a rhyme; thence called away\nBy good Anglante's prince, who wills, before\nI of those others tell, I should display\nThe labours and the troubles he sustained,\nPursuing the great good he never gained.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>At the first city, whither he was brought\n(Because to go concealed he had good care),\nHe a new helmet donned; but took no thought\nWhat was the head-piece he designed to bear.\nSo safe is he in fairy spell, it nought\nImports, if hard or soft its temper were.\nOrlando, covered thus, pursues the quest,\nNor him day, night, or rain, or sun arrest.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>It was the hour that our of Ocean's bed\nDan Phoebus drew his dripping steeds, and high\nAnd low, still scattering yellow flowers and red,\nAurora stained the heavens with various dye,\nAnd Stars had cast their veils about their head,\nDeparting from their revels in the sky;\nWhen passing on a day fair Paris near,\nOrlando made his mighty worth appear.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Two squadrons he encountered; one an old\nSaracen, Manilardo clept, obeyed;\nKing of Noritia, whilom fierce and bold.\nBut fitter now to counsel than to aid.\nThe next beneath the standard was enrolled\nOr Tremisena's monarch, who was said\n'Mid Africans to be a perfect knight;\nAlzirdo he by those who knew him, hight:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>These, with the other Saracen array,\nCantoned throughout the winter months had lain,\nSome near the city, some more far away,\nAll lodged nigh town or hamlet on the plain.\nFor since King Agramant had many a day\nSpent in attacking Paris' walls in vain,\nHe (for no other means remained to try)\nWould lastly with a siege the city ply;</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>And to do this had people infinite:\nSince he, beside the host that with him came,\nAnd that of Spain which followed to the fight\nThe Spanish King Marsilius' oriflame,\nMany of France did in his pay unite:\nFor all from Paris he to Arles's stream,\nWith part of Gascony, some straggling tower\nExcepted, had reduced beneath his power.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>The quivering brook, as warmer breezes blew,\nBeginning now from ice its waves to free,\nAnd the fresh-springing grass and foliage new,\nTo cloathe again the field and greenwood tree,\nAll those King Agramant assembled, who\nHad followed him in his prosperity;\nTo muster in review the armed swarm,\nAnd give to his affairs a better form:</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Hence did the King of Tremisen' repair,\nWith him who had Noritia in command,\nTo be in time at that full muster, where\nEach squadron, good or bad, was to be scanned\nOrlando thus by chance encountered there,\nAs I have told you, this united hand;\nWho, as his usage was, went seeking her,\nBy whom he had been made Love's prisoner.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Alzirdo, as the approaching count he eyes,\nWho in this world for valour has no peer,\nWith such a haughty front, and in such guise,\nThe God of war would less in arms appear,\nThe features known before astounded spies,\nThe fierce, disdainful glance and furious cheer;\nAnd him esteems a knight of prowess high,\nWhich, fondly, he too sore desires to try.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Arrogant, young, and of redoubted force,\nAlzirdo was, and prized for dauntless mind;\nWho bent to joust pricked forth his foaming horse,\nHappier had he remained in line behind!\nMet by Anglante's prince in middle course,\nWho pierced his heart as they encountering joined.\nFrighted, the lightened courser scoured the plain,\nWithout a rider to direct the rein.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Rises a sudden and a horrid cry,\nAnd air on every side repeats the scream;\nAs his scared band the falling youth descry,\nAnd issuing from his wound so wide a stream:\nDisordered, they the count in fury ply,\nAnd, raised to cut or thrust, their weapons gleam.\nAgainst that flower of knights, their feathered reeds,\nA thicker squadron yet in tempest speeds.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>With sound like that, with which from hill repair,\nOr from the champaign's flat the hurrying swine,\n(If the Wolf, issue from his grot, or Bear,\nDescending to the mountains' lower line,\nSome bristly youngling take away and tear,\nWho with loud squeal and grunt is heard to pine)\nCame driving at the count the barbarous rout;\n\"Upon him!\" and \"upon him!\" still their shout.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>At once spears, shafts, and swords, his corslet bore\nBy thousands, and as many pierce his shield.\nThis threatens on one side, and that before,\nAnd those the ponderous mace behind him wield.\nBut he esteems the craven rout no more.\nHe, who did never yet to terror yield,\nThan hungry Wolf in twilight makes account\nTo what the number of the flock may mount.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>He held unsheathed that thundering sword in hand,\nWhich with so many foes has heaped the plain,\nThat he who thinks to count the slaughtered band,\nHas undertaken, hard emprize and vain.\nThe road ran red, ensanguined by his brand,\nAnd scarce capacious of the many slain.\nFor neither targe nor head-piece good defends,\nWhere fatal Durindana's blade descends.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Nor safety cotton vest, nor cloths supply,\nIn thousand folds about the temples spread:\nNor only groan and lamentation fly\nThrough air, but shoulder, arm, and severed head,\nDeath roams the field in strange variety\nOf horrid forms, and all inspiring dread;\nAnd says, \"For hundreds of my scythes may stand\nHis Durindana in Orlando's hand.\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>His ceaseless strokes scarce one the other wait:\nSpeedily all his foemen are in flight.\nAnd when before they came at furious rate,\nThey hoped to swallow quick the single knight.\nNone is there who, in that unhappy straight,\nStops for his comrade, flying from the fight.\nHere one man speeds afoot, one gallops there;\nNone stays to question if the road be fair.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>His mirror Valour bore about, and here\nEach blemish of the soul was seen confest:\nNone looked therein, except an aged peer,\nWhose blood was chilled, but courage unreprest.\nThat death were better deems this cavalier\nThan life in flight, and in disgrace possest:\nI mean Noritia's king, who lays his lance\nIn rest against the paladin of France;</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>He broke it on the border of the shield\nOf the intrepid count, with stedfast hand,\nWho, by the stroke unshaken, nothing reeled:\nAnd smote the king, in passing, with his brand.\nHim Fortune saved; for as Orlando wheeled\nThe blade, it turned, descending, in his hand.\nAlthough an-edge he guides not still the sword,\nStunned from his saddle reels the paynim lord.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Astounded from his saddle reels the king,\nNor him Orlando turns about to see.\nHe cuts, and cleaves, and slays his following;\nWho all believe him at their backs to be.\nAs through the spacious air, with troubled wing,\nThe starlings from the daring merlin flee;\nSo, of that broken squadron, scattered round,\nSome fly, some dip, and some fall flat to ground.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>He ceased not his ensanguined blade to sway\nTill living wight remained not in his view.\nOrlando doubted to resume his way,\nAlthough the country all about he knew.\nDoes he the right or left-hand road assay,\nHis thoughts still rove from what his steps pursue,\nAnd he to seek the damsel is in dread\nThrough other path than that by which she fled.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXVI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Through wood and field his courser did he goad,\nOften inquiring for the royal dame:\nBeside himself, he strayed beside his road,\nAnd to the foot of rising mountain came,\nWhence (it was night-time through a fissure glowed ) \n\nThe distant flicker of a quivering flame.\nOrlando to the rock approached, to spy\nIf there Angelica concealed might lie.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXVII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>As where low junipers o'er shade her lair,\nOr in the stubble of the open lay,\nWhat time the hunters seek the fearful hare\nThrough traversed woods, and through uncertain way,\n— Lest peradventure she be hidden there,\nThey every bramble, every bush assay;\nEven so, where hope the toiling warrior leads,\nSearching his lady-love, Orlando speeds.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXVIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Pricking in haste towards that ray, the count\nArrived where in the wood the light was shed,\nForth-streaming from a crevice in the mount,\nWithin whose womb a spacious grotto spread;\nAnd there, like wall or bank, discerned in front,\nOf thorns and underwood a bristly bed,\nTo hide the grotto's inmates, and defend\nFrom scathe or scorn, which others might intend.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>LXXXIX</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>By day it had been hidden evermore;\nBut the clear flame betrayed the haunt by night.\nIts use he guessed; but would the place explore,\nAnd better certify himself by sight.\nWhen he without had tied his Brigliador,\nIn silence to the grotto stole the knight;\nThreading the shrubs; nor calling for a guide,\nEntered the passage in the mountain's side.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XC</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>By a long flight of steps was the descent\nInto the cave; where, in the rocky tomb,\nBuried were living folk.  Of wide extent,\nThe grot was chiselled into vaulted room;\nNor was, although its entrance little lent,\nAll daylight wanting to disperse the gloom:\nFor much was furnished by a window dight,\nWithin a natural fissure on the right.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XCI</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>In the mid cave, beside a fire was seen\nA gentle maid of pleasing look and guise;\nWho seemed to Roland little past fifteen,\nAs far as at first sight he might surmise.\nWith that so fair she made the rugged scene\nSeem in the warrior's sight a paradise.\nAlthough this while her eyes with tears o'erflow,\nClear tokens of a heart oppressed with woe.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XCII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>An aged dame was with her, and the pair\nWrangled, as oftentimes is women's way;\nBut when the County was descending there,\nConcluded the dispute and wordy fray.\nOrlando hastens to salute them fair\n(As still is due to womankind and they ) \n\nTo welcome him rise lightly form their seat,\nAnd with benign return the warrior greet.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XCIII</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>'Tis true, that when that sudden voice they hear,\nSomedeal confused in look they seem to be,\nAt the same time beholding thus appear\nSo fierce a wight, and harnessed cap-a-pee.\n\"What wight\" (demands Anglantes' cavalier)\nSo barbarous is, and void of courtesy,\nThat he keeps buried, in this rude repair,\nA face so gentle and so passing fair?\"</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>XCIV</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>With pain the virgin to the count replies,\nAs he inquires of her unhappy doom,\nIn sweet and broken accents, which by sighs\nImpelled, through rows of pearl and coral come:\nAnd between rose and lily, from her eyes\nTears fall so fast, she needs must swallow some.\nIn other canto, sir, be pleased to attend\nThe rest, for here 'tis time my strain should end.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  }
]